<FIRST>r i PM-Stroessner-Asylum     06-01 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stroessner-Asylum,0206</SECOND>
<UNK>Stroessner Receives Permanent Political Asylum in Brazil</UNK>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it has granted
deposed Paraguayan President Alfredo Stroessner permanent political
asylum.
   Brazil gave the 76-year-old former dictator a permanent visa on
May 24, according to Wednesday's ``Diario Oficial,'' the government
publication that announces official acts.
   Gen. Stroessner, ousted in a bloody coup after 34 years in
power, arrived in Brazil on Feb. 5 and lives in a beachfront
mansion in the coastal resort town of Guaratuba about 500 miles
southwest of Rio de Janeiro.
   In early April, Stroessner requested a temporary visa to the
United States to receive surgery for prostate cancer, but was
turned down by the State Department. Soon afterward, he was
hospitalized three days with a mild congestive heart failure at Sao
Paulo's Heart Institute.
   Brazil also granted a permanent visa to Stroessner's wife, Maria
Eugenia Heikel, but did not mention the ex-general's oldest son
Gustavo, who followed Stroessner into exile and is living in the
southeastern city of Curitiba.
   Col. Gustavo Stroessner, 46, faces charges in Paraguay of
extortion and illegal use of government funds during his father's
regime.
   Paraguayan justice officials have announced they would request
his extradition from Brazil.
</TEXT>
