<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Glasnost     06-01 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Glasnost,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Congress Raises Glasnost to New Level</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Name Ales cq in lead graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writer Ales Adamovich says the freedom to question
authority at the Congress of People's Deputies parliament is like a
pole-vault or high-jump contest.
   Each day the level goes higher. Everyone knows there's an upper
limit, but no one knows where it is.
   ``There is no prohibition _ just an ability to jump higher,''
the writer observed after Wednesday's session. ``But you can fall
and break your nose.''
   The session started May 25 with firm but polite questioning of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's privileges, powers, and his right
to be both Communist Party chief and head of state.
   On Tuesday, a former Olympic weightlifter pointedly accused
Gorbachev of holding back information on the military assault on
demonstrators in Tbilisi, Georgia, that killed 19, and he attacked
the feared KGB secret police.
   ``In no circumstances is it possible to accept that the head of
state doesn't know the circumstances of the case,'' said Yuri
Vlasov in reference to the Georgian violence. ``Otherwise, what
kind of head of state is he?''
   Vlasov urged the parliament to add an impeachment article to the
Soviet Constitution, to be imposed for withholding information from
the people.
   Then he attacked the KGB, which he said, is ``the most closed,
the most conspiratorial of all government institutions,''
controlling the lives of its citizens and set above every other
part of the government.
   He received prolonged applause.
   With his policy of glasnost, or greater openness, Gorbachev has
awakened open political debate in society, but the speed at which
Soviets have taken in the changes has startled even some of the
deputies.
   Gorbachev sought to reassure them the give-and-take of
parliamentary debate is a normal part of a more democratic system,
even if deputies occasionally lose their tempers.
   The deputies, whose performances were broadcast back home on TV,
took the opportunity to talk about their constituents' pet peeves.
   Boris N. Yeltsin criticized Gorbachev on Wednesday in what
amounted to an alternate policy address.
   The Communist maverick told reporters his speech would have been
impossible three years ago but may have been acceptable a year or
year and a half ago.
   Adamovich, a political reformer famous for his tales of World
War II horrors in Byelorussia, said the 2,250 deputies had become
more aggressive in their speeches and criticism.
   The rhetoric peaked last Saturday in a pitched battle between
reformers and conservatives over the makeup of the working
legislature, the Supreme Soviet. Historian Yuri Afanasyev said the
reformers were being oppressed by an ``aggressively obedient''
majority.
   Adamovich said he noticed from the Congress floor that the
rhetoric peaked again Tuesday in a sharp debate that included the
military commander of the Tbilisi assault, the former Communist
Party chief and a member of a commission that called the assault a
``planned mass massacre.''
   Lt. Col. Igor Rodionov, the military commander, said the
protesters were expressing separatist slogans and insulting
Russians and other non-Georgians.
   Commission member Thomas Gamkrelidze said in an interview
Wednesday that although debate in the Congress is freer, the
Tbilisi assault demonstrated that level of openness has not reached
the entire country.
   ``I think Rodionov's speech here has shown the whole world that
it is enough to raise slogans here to be punished or killed,'' he
said.
   ``Our democracy has not reached the point to realize that it is
not permissible to punish people for slogans. Gorbachev seems to be
more liberal in this respect than others, including the military.''
</TEXT>
