<FIRST>r w PM-Fauntroy-Probe     06-01 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fauntroy-Probe,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury to Begin Ghost Employee Investigation of Delegate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury will soon start hearing
testimony about the office hiring practices of Walter Fauntroy, the
District of Columbia's non-voting delegate to Congress, The
Associated Press has learned.
   As part of the ongoing Justice Department inquiry, current and
former employees of Fauntroy, a Democrat, and Rep. Gus Savage,
D-Ill., will be asked to testify on Fauntroy's hiring of Savage's
son, according to sources familiar with the investigation.
   Thomas John Savage, the son of Rep. Savage, was paid $21,398
while on Fauntroy's payroll between September 1987 and June 1988,
but swore on Illinois election documents that he was living in
Chicago during that time. Those records were filed as part of his
unsuccessful bid to win an Illinois House seat.
   Employees from the Fauntroy and Savage offices will be
subpoenaed to appear before a grand jury within the next month, and
investigators have already subpoenaed payroll documents and office
personnel data from the two congressmen, said sources, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
   Those records have been requested to determine whether the
younger Savage, his father or Fauntroy falsified payroll documents
or offered false statements to investigators.
   Fauntroy and Rep. Savage refused to comment when asked whether
documents from his office had been requested by federal authorities.
   When contacted by telephone in Chicago, Thomas John Savage
declined to comment Wednesday.
   In addition, investigators are examining all of Fauntroy's
congressional staff and committee hirings for the past five years,
the sources said.
   Investigators are also examining the personal banking records of
Thomas Savage to learn whether he returned any money to his father
or Fauntroy, the sources familiar with the investigation said.
   Investigators also are closely examining accounts of the younger
Savage's job duties submitted voluntarily to federal officials by
Johnny Barnes, Fauntroy's chief aide, and several other Fauntroy
staffers, sources said.
   Barnes refused Wednesday to comment on the documents.
   The FBI opened the case with a 90-day preliminary investigation
in December, shortly after the AP reported on Fauntroy's hiring of
the younger Savage.
   Officials at the Justice Department's Criminal Division then
recommended that Attorney General Dick Thornburgh appoint a special
prosecutor to look into the case under the terms an order by his
predecessor, Edwin Meese III. That rule, instituted by Meese just
days before he left office last August, required an independent
prosecutor to examine cases of alleged wrongdoing by members of
Congress.
   However, Thornburgh scuttled the Meese order and turned the
investigation back to the Justice Department's criminal division,
which traditionally handles such cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-ThirdWorldDebt     06-01 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Third World Debt,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 9 a.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Brady Plan Attacked as Inadequate to Cut Third World Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading economic expert today attacked
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's plan for reducing Third World
debt, saying the proposal will not effectively reduce the billions
paid out every year in interest.
   The debt of the developing nations is estimated at $1.2
trillion, about half of it owed to commercial banks.
   John Williamson, senior fellow at the Institute for
International Economics, points to an outflow of $37.3 billion from
debtor to creditor countries last year.
   ``It still looks as though it will be difficult to achieve
debt-service reduction of $7 billion a year with a pool of $25
billion or less,'' Williamson wrote in a revised edition of his
study ``Voluntary Approaches to Debt Relief,'' published today.
   Debt service usually includes payments on both principal and
interest. Few of the troubled debtor countries have paid any
principal since 1982. Some, such as Argentina, are far behind on
their interest payments.
   Williamson suggested that a pool of $40 billion to $50 billion
is needed. Some of the new borrowing might be used by the debtors
to pay off old debt at a discount. He would like see some old debt
swapped for new debt, with interest assured to the banks at a lower
rate.
   Brady's proposal, unveiled March 10, encourages banks to forgive
a substantial portion of their loans to heavily indebted countries
in return for guarantees that the rest will be paid. The guarantees
are to be furnished by the International Monetary Fund and its
sister agency, the World Bank.
   IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said Wednesday the
commercial banks must do more to help Third World countries reduce
their debts.
   Treasury spokesmen refuse to estimate officially how much may be
available for debt relief. They say that will depend on how many
countries ask for it, and how many promise to meet the conditions.
The bank and fund require some austerity policies from the
borrowing countries in return for help.
   Williamson says he finds disappointing Brady's call for new
policies by all debtors to qualify for support. The economist
suggests that countries which already have taken austerity measures
should be rewarded with arrangements to provide a definitive
solution to their crises. He names Bolivia, Chile, Colombia, Costa
Rica, Mexico and Uruguay.
   Williamson sees a failure by Brady to offer a solution to the
problem of ``free riders'' _ creditor banks that refuse to make any
reduction in the amount of debt or interest owed them.
   Williamson proposes that banks which will not provide any other
debt relief should accept a limit on debtors' payments to them, the
limit to be set by the amount the debtor country earns from its
exports. The rest of the money owed to the banks would be added to
the total debt.
   Williamson is a former adviser to the British Treasury and the
International Monetary Fund. The Institute for International
Economics was created by the (West) German Marshall Fund and gets
support from it and from other governments and foundations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     06-01 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Prices Edged Up Last Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overall prices on farm products edged upward
last month, with record demand for broilers, potatoes and tomatoes,
according to the Department of Agriculture.
   Prices on raw products rose 2.7 percent from April to May and
averaged 13 percent more than a year ago, the Agriculture
Department said Wednesday.
   Increases in the prices of hogs, oranges, potatoes, broilers and
tomatoes were partially offset by lower prices for sweet corn,
eggs, lettuce and soybeans, said the department's Agricultural
Statistics Board in a preliminary report.
   But broiler, potato and tomato prices were at record levels.
Hogs also increased sharply from April.
   Demand for oranges was so strong that the average price went
higher than it has been since November 1987.
   Cattle prices continued close to April levels. Wheat and corn
prices were up slightly while soybeans were down from a month
earlier.
   Based on the preliminary figures, the price index for livestock
and livestock products was up 2.6 percent from April to May, and
4.6 percent above a year ago at this time.
   Compared with April, higher prices for hogs and broilers more
than offset lower prices for eggs and milk.
   Crop prices, overall, rose 3.6 percent from a month earlier and
24 percent above a year earlier.
   The overall index of prices paid to farmers in May averaged 151
percent of a 1977 base used for comparison.
   The report said:
   _Cattle averaged $70.10 per 100 pounds of live weight
nationally, steady with April. The average is for all types of
cattle sold as beef.
   _Hogs averaged $42.70 per 100 pounds, compared with $36.30 in
April and $46.30 a year earlier.
   _Corn, at $2.58 a bushel, up from $2.56 in April and $1.98 in
May 1988.
   _Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures,
averaged $4.07 per bushel, compared with $4.03 in April and $2.97 a
year earlier.
   _Rice averaged $6.53 per 100 pounds, down from $6.66 in April
and $7.97 a year earlier.
   _Soybeans were $7.15 per bushel, compared with $7.29 in April
and $6.98 a year earlier.
   _Upland cotton was reported at 57.7 cents per pound, compared to
59 in April and 58.3 cents a pound in May 1988.
   _Eggs were 54.3 cents per dozen, compared with 58.1 cents in
April and 33 cents a year earlier.
   _Milk was $12.20 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.30 in April
and $11.40 a year earlier.
   _Broilers were 45.2 cents per pound, live weight, compared with
39 cents in April and 33.7 cents a year ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers will have to reduce the acreage they
plant in wheat next season by 5 percent, Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter says.
   ``We need more wheat,'' said Kelly Shipp, in explaining why the
set-aside was not higher.
   Each year, the agriculture secretary is required to decide what,
if any, acreage should be set aside in order to keep surpluses
down. Yeutter could have asked for a greater acreage reduction or
none at all.
   In past years acreage has been reduced by as much as 25 percent
because of large surpluses.
   Currently, U.S. wheat supplies are low because of the success of
the program in the past and two years of drought.
   Yeutter said price support loans and purchase rates would be
$1.95 a bushel, a 20 percent reduction from the basic loan and
purchase rate of $2.44.
   This is the minimum allowed by law and 5 percent below the 1989
loan and purchase rate of $2.06 a bushel.
   He also set the established target price at $4 a bushel, the
statutory minimum and down about 2 percent from the 1989 target
price.
   Furthermore, he said he would not implement paid land
diversions, marketing loans or related programs. No secretary since
1985 has implemented these programs for wheat or corn, in part
because prices have been high and there has been no need for them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven days of drenching rain was good for the
dry central Plains states and western Corn Belt, but caused
flooding in the Ozarks and Ohio Valley, slowing fieldwork for the
second consecutive week, according to a report released Wednesday.
   There were fewer than two suitable work days in Indiana and Ohio
during the week ending May 28, with three or four good days in the
Delta region.
   Winter wheat prospects continue to be fair to poor with
harvesting under way in California, Georgia, Oklahoma and Texas.
   In Kansas, rain improved winter wheat condition, but the outlook
is still very poor to poor. Wheat streak mosaic and Russian wheat
aphids were problems in the panhandle of Nebraska, while hail
damaged the crop in some east-central counties of Arkansas.
   Spring wheat was mostly good to fair with planting 98 percent
complete, according to the report by the Joint Agricultural Weather
Facility.
   Corn and soybean planting, at 89 percent and 55 percent complete
respectively, are behind schedule because of the heavy rain in the
Delta and eastern Corn Belt.
</TEXT>
