<FIRST>r w PM-Wright-Mack     06-01 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Mack,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Defends Hiring of Man Convicted of Assault</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright defended his decision
of 14 years ago to hire a man who had been convicted of brutally
assaulting a young woman, saying he wanted to ``give a young
gentleman a second chance.''
   Near the end of his resignation speech on Wednesday, Wright
said: ``I didn't know the nature of a crime that he had been
convicted of. I don't think ... it's bad judgment to try and give a
young gentleman a second chance.''
   Wright hired John P. Mack as a mail clerk, a $9,000-a-year job,
and Mack rose to become Wright's closest aide as executive director
of the Democratic Steering and Policy Committee. Mack resigned that
$86,000-a-year position position May 11 after his victim, Pamela
Small, told her story in The Washington Post.
   ``Maybe I should have known more about'' the crime, Wight said.
However, ``I don't think that America really stands for the notion
that a person should be forever condemned,'' he added.
   Mack pleaded guilty to beating and stabbing Ms. Small and
leaving her for dead in 1973 after she asked him for assistance in
a store in suburban Annandale, Va., where he worked. Mack, 19 at
the time of the crime, was sentenced to 15 years in prison but
served only 27 months in a county jail before being released.
   Wright noted that at the time he hired Mack as a clerk, Wright's
daughter was married to Mack's brother.
   ``I didn't know him,'' Wright told the House Wednesday. ``I knew
only that John Mack was a young man that my daughter had known in
high school.... All I knew was that he was convicted of
assault....''
   Mack had come under fire from several House members because,
they insisted, he had never shown contrition for his crime and had
offered no financial assistance to Ms. Small. In his resignation
statement, he apologized for ``a terrible and tragic mistake.''
   Mack added: ``To Pamela Small, and also to my family, all I can
say now is what I have said many times before and to myself every
day since this happened, and that is I am sorry. Truly sorry.''
</TEXT>
