<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-HijackAttempt     06-01 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack Attempt,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Haitians Arrested After Demanding to be Flown to Tel Aviv</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ORLANDO CUALES</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLEMSTAD, Curacao (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Claiming to have a bomb, two unarmed
Haitians tried to hijack an Antillean Airlines jet to Israel on
Wednesday and were seized when it landed and passengers rushed for
exits, authorities said.
   The two had boarded the DC-9 in Haiti, apparently thinking it
was bound for New York when its true destination was this tiny
Dutch island off the coast Venezuela, said airline spokesman Robin
Visser.
   He said one of the jet's more than 100 passengers was slightly
injured in the rush to leave the plane after it landed at Hato
International Airport around dusk.
   Visser said the flight originated in Miami and that an
undetermined number of U.S. citizens were aboard Flight 974.
   After its stopover in Port-au-Prince, Haiti, one of the suspects
told flight attendents that a small box he placed in a forward
bathroom had explosives inside that could be detonated by a Haitian
army colonel in a submarine somewhere in the Caribbean.
   He and his companion demanded to be flown to Tel Aviv, Israel,
Visser said.
   The spokesman said the hijackers apparently thought they were on
a flight to New York and the pilot continued on to Curacao without
telling passengers of the attempted hijacking, having convinced the
Haitians they bound for New York.
   The pilot taxied to a far end of the airstrip, informed the
passengers there was an emergency and ordered them off the plane as
quickly as possible.
   Visser said that as people rushed for the exits in panic, an ALM
employee who was aboard as a regular passenger jumped one of the
Haitians, who surrendered, and another Haitian man was arrested on
the tarmac.
   Local authorities had blocked roads leading to the airport and
stopped all flights shortly before the plane landed in Curacao.
   Explosives experts from the Royal Dutch Navy based in Curacao
searched the plane, but Visser did not know whether they had found
anything.
   Visser said the pilot dropped altitude from 29,000 feet to 3,000
feet to lessen the chance of an explosion being set off by cabin
pressure.
</TEXT>
