<DOCNO> AP890601-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SellingWomen     06-01 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Selling Women,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Thousands of Women Sold in One County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of women are being kidnapped and sold
to farmers in Hebei province, where hundreds of people are getting
rich through the illegal human trade, an official newspaper
reported today.
   Farmers in Quyang county have paid from $13 to $1,340 each for
about 5,000 women abducted from more than 10 provinces, the
English-language China Daily reported. Apparently, although the
story did not say, the farmers were buying wives.
   More than 1,000 people are engaged in the lucrative business,
including one who built a five-room house with his earnings, the
report said, quoting the China's Women's News.
   Sales of women also are prevalent in other counties around
Baoding city of Hebei, about 90 miles south of Beijing, the report
said.
   It told the tale of Wang Guaifa, 47, who lost both his daughter
and niece to kidnappers in Baoding in January.
   They were abducted after arriving at the Baoding railway station
by a gang of seven in two rickshaws. The gang robbed Wang and ran
off with the women, who were sold in Lianzhuang township of
Xingtang county for a total of $1,520.
   Police were informed of the abduction and found Wang's niece on
March 9. By the time they caught up with his kidnapped daughter she
had been sold three times.
   But according to the report, ``she refused to leave and the
villagers stopped police from taking her away.''
</TEXT>
