<HEAD>`Phantom's' Opening Night Draws Hollywood Celebrities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cybill Shepherd and Victoria Principal were
among the celebrities who turned out for the West Coast premiere of
the ``Phantom of the Opera'' at the Ahmanson Theater.
   Miss Shepherd arrived with her 9-year-old daughter, Clementine
Ford, for the musical spectacular created by Andrew Lloyd Webber.
   Cher, Tom Selleck, Dudley Moore, Patrick Swayze, Richard
Chamberlain, Gene Kelly and Sammy Davis Jr. also were expected for
the opening-night show, publicist Ann Abrams said.
   The big names also were invited to the Shrine Auditorium for a
post-performance gala with the cast, including Tony Award-winner
Michael Crawford, who plays the phantom, Ms. Abrams said.
   The ``Phantom'' is a tale of a disfigured musician's unrequited
love for a beautiful singer, set in a labyrinthine Paris Opera
House and staged with Webber's characteristic awesomeness.
   Ticket sales to the show, which opened in London in 1987 and New
York last year, have been so brisk in Los Angeles that the
production is expected to stay at least two years, Ms. Abrams said.
