<DOCNO> AP890601-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonBriefs     06-01 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Briefs,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Wants End to Cable-Reimbursement System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission says
Congress should abolish a 13-year-old copyright system which lets
cable television operators pay a percentage of their income to
retransmit over-the-air TV programs.
   The commission said cable TV companies should negotiate with
broadcasters and producers on a case-by-case basis for programs.
The decision was made public Wednesday.
   In 1976, Congress compelled broadcasters and program owners to
allow cable operators to retransmit their programs. In return for
this ``compulsory license,'' cable companies were required to pay a
specified percentage of their revenues to the U.S. Copyright
Office. The office's Copyright Royalty Tribunal decides how to
allocate the fees among broadcasters, program owners and entities
such as sports franchises.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Trying to Defraud Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California man has been indicted on charges
of conspiring to defraud the government by forging letters intended
to help a company that was bidding for federal contracts.
   Jeffrey A. Hertzig, 36, of Anaheim, Calif., was charged by a
federal grand jury with four counts involving conspiracy to defraud
the government, making false statements, perjury and aiding and
abetting, according to a statement by the General Services
Administration released Wednesday.
   He was accused of forging letters from a fictitious Bank of
America officer that said the bank would commit financial support
to the OAO Corp. of Greenbelt, Md., if it were awarded contracts by
the GSA and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, the
GSA said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Submarine's Hull Cracks Stem From Manufacturer's Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electric Boat officials say two cracks in the
hull of a nearly completed nuclear submarine can be traced back to
a failure of the steel's manufacturer.
   The Groton, Conn., submarine builder said Wednesday the cracks,
which company officials had described as ``quite severe'' in a memo
to lawmakers last week, went undetected by Navy and company
officials for five years.
   Electric Boat, a division of General Dynamics Corp., said
repairs have been completed and apparently would not impact on the
Sept. 30 commissioning date of the USS Topeka, a SSN-688 Los
Angeles class attack submarine.
   The steel maker, Armco Inc. of Parsippany, N.J., initiated
repairs, but ``did not completely eliminate the defect in this
plate when they made the repair,'' Electric Boat said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>DC Curfew Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia has dropped plans to
impose a curfew on teen-agers that was part of an effort to reduce
illegal narcotics sales and drug-related violence in the nation's
capital.
   Last week, U.S. District Court Judge Charles R. Richey struck
down a proposed city curfew law, ruling the measure violated
constitutionally protected freedom of association and free speech
rights.
   The curfew, aimed at keeping teens from congregating in the
district's notorious open-air drug markets, would have prohibited
anyone under 18 from gathering outside after 11 p.m. Sunday through
Thursday and after midnight on Friday and Saturday. The curfew
would have been lifted each day at 6 a.m.
