<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--BellyLanding     06-01 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Belly Landing,0154</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landing Gear Collapses; No One Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iowa Air turbo-prop plane slid up to 300 yards
on its belly when its its landging gears collapsed during a
landing, officials said.
   Two pilots and one passenger were aboard Wednesday's Flight 1523
for Benton Harbor, Mich. No injuries were reported.
   The plane had just left Midway Airport when the pilot noticed a
problem with the landing gear and returned, said Mort Edelstein, a
Federal Aviation Administration spokesman.
   When it landed, the landing gears collapsed, and the plane slid
up to 300 yards along the runway, said Chicago Aviation Department
spokeswoman Lisa Howard. It came to rest at the intersection of two
main runways, she said.
   Though runways for small aircraft were not affected, Midway's
two runways for large commercial flights were closed for two hours
until the twin-engine E110 turbo-prop could be towed away, she said.
</TEXT>
