<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OilRigFire     06-01 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Rig Fire,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three People Burned in Oil Rig Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENAI, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire broke out on an oil
rig in Cook Inlet, seriously injuring three of the 41 people
aboard, authorities said.
   The explosion occurred Wednesday on a Unocal Corp. Monopod
platform about 15 miles northeast of Nikiski, said Bob Anderson, a
company spokesman.
   The fire was extinguished in about 15 minutes, Anderson said.
   All safety mechanisms functioned and no oil was involved, said
Anderson.
   ``There was no spill,'' he said.
   Forty-one people were on the rig when the fire broke out, he
said. All but seven were evacuated by helicopter to Kenai, 10 miles
south of Nikiski. Those remaining aboard were investigating what
went wrong, Anderson said.
   The three injured workers suffered second- and third-degree
burns were were listed in serious condition at a hospital in
Anchorage, 70 miles northeast of Kenai, officials said.
   The rig, one of more than a dozen platforms in Cook Inlet, was
installed in 1966 and first produced oil in January 1967. The unit
equipped with living quarters for 54 people rises 354 feet from the
inlet floor.
   In 1987, a well blowout and fire turned a Cook Inlet oil and gas
production platform into a huge, gas-fueled torch. All 49 workers
on the Steelhead platform owned by Marathon Oil Co. and Unocal
escaped safely. Repair of the platform is continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
