<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonCamelot     06-01 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Camelot,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cast of Convicts Recreates the Round Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHIRLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Camelot it's not.
   Nevertheless, the prison in this pastoral town is staging a
production of the musical legend. The all-inmate cast has dubbed
themselves the ``Awesome Convict Players.''
   One Massachusetts Correctional Institution prisoner asked that
his parole be delayed so he could play the role of Sir Lancelot on
opening night Friday, officials said.
   During a dress rehearsal Wednesday, the cast proudly displayed
the scenery they had painted, the addition to the stage built in
the prison carpentry shop and the tunics and robes they sewed under
the tutelage of a volunteer costume mistress.
   ``I'm sure from the outside it seems funny because `Camelot' is
supposed to be a perfect world, and doing it in a prison is such an
irony,'' said Holly Ward, the 28-year-old director.
   But Ward, who is not an inmate, and her actors say prison
theater is therapeutic.
   ``Camelot is a way to reassess your dreams and maybe to live out
your dreams in some way,'' said one inmate who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The inmate, like others in the cast, wouldn't say what crime he
committed for his one-year sentence.
   The buildings at Shirley, 40 miles northwest of Boston, are used
as a minimum-security prison aimed at reintegrating inmates who are
soon to be released. Many are serving time for drug and alcohol
offenses, but some are finishing longer sentences for more violent
crimes.
   There are no bars, fences or dogs. Prisoners so close to
regaining their freedom rarely escape.
   Ward said her biggest problem is actors who keep being released
just when they've mastered their roles.
   ``We've been through three Arthurs and several Merlins and
several Mordreds,'' she said.
   Ward and Jim Kelley, the prison's community service director,
said they were stunned when inmate Gordon Benjamin decided to delay
his release so he could play the first knight of the Round Table.
Five performances are scheduled through June 10.
   Benjamin was not at Wednesday's rehearsal and did not return
telephone calls to The Associated Press.
   ``I've never seen a parole put off for this,'' Kelley said.
``That's major.''
   Ward began organizing inmate plays when she was a theater-arts
student seven years ago. She said she isn't quitting despite the
birth of her first child last fall.
   Several years ago, Ward directed ``Man of La Mancha'' at Norfolk
prison and persuaded the Broadway lead, actor Richard Kiley, to
attend. This time, she has invited Robert Goulet, who played
Lancelot in the film version of ``Camelot'' starring Vanessa
Redgrave and Richard Burton.
   She believes acting helps the inmates develop self-esteem and a
perspective on their own emotions.
   ``Some of them, I have to teach them how to cry,'' she said.
``Then I have to teach them how to stop.''
   The inmates said they love the romance, the costumes, the
chivalry and the story of King Arthur's betrayal and forgiveness.
   The man who plays the villain, Arthur's bastard son Mordred,
said he can relate to the character because he himself is an
illegitimate child.
   ``Camelot,'' which will cost less than $500 to produce, is
supported by a grant from Massachusetts Citizens Against the Death
Penalty, Kelley said. The cast will give performances for fellow
inmates, town residents, staff and state dignitaries, and on
closing night, for family and friends.
   ``Their families are so proud of them,'' Ward said. ``It's the
first time they can say, `I saw my son on stage' instead of `My son
the criminal, my son the prisoner.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-01 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EGG HARBOR TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This is not your ordinary
office plant.
   A persistent ivy vine that once climbed only the front of the
southern New Jersey township's building inspections office made its
way indoors about five years ago through a crack in the wall and
apparently found it a good growing environment.
   The vine now is in several offices, lining the perimeter and the
ceiling of the room it first entered and making its way up a dark
stairwell toward offices on the second floor.
   Workers have allowed the vine's offshoots to wind their way to
the fire inspections office and out to the customer service area
counter, where a sign proclaims, ``Yes! The ivy you see is real!''
   When it came inside, no one saw reason to prune it. In fact, the
employees marked its progress with small slips of paper.
   ``It broke through the bricks and came popping up one day,''
said secretary Pat Chatigny. ``I'm sitting here typing one day and
I looked up and saw the green coming out and we just decided to
tack it up and let it grow.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MARQUETTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Eisaman has found an unusual way to
harness the wind for sailing _ a kite.
   Eisaman, 55, plans to sail Lake Superior in a canoe using a kite
overhead to power him across. It's the only one of the Great Lakes
he hasn't navigated with a kite.
   ``No turning back, no second thoughts,'' he said. He intends to
begin sailing today and hopes to complete the 130-mile journey by
Friday.
   During a recent practice run, the 16-square-foot red, yellow and
blue kite soared high above the 15-foot canoe. ``If the wind blows
that way, you go that way. Just follow the wind,'' said Eisaman,
who writes technical manuals for computers with his wife.
   Only about a dozen people in the world regularly kite sail, said
David Culp, publisher of the Kite Sailing International newsletter.
   ``I know a lot of people think Dan Eisaman is just a nutty old
guy who's trying to get himself killed in a novel way,'' said Culp,
who uses a kite to try to set speed records for sailing. ``But he
knows what he's doing.''
   Eisaman said he averaged about 3 knots in sailing across other
lakes.
   ``People in power boats always ask me if I need a tow,'' he
said. ``When I say I'm fine, they look at me like I'm crazy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of Chevy's Cafe plans one last
bash before changing the eatery's name, under a threat of a
trademark infringement lawsuit by General Motors Corp.
   To commemorate the name change to Flip's Cafe, employees and
patrons will destroy a battered 1957 Chevy in the restaurant's
parking lot tonight with a sledgehammer.
   Owner Dennis Richards contends the name Chevy's was chosen
simply to convey a 1950s image. Portage is about 135 miles west of
Detroit.
   ``They sent us a letter the first week in April indicating that
they were going to sue us if the name wasn't changed,'' Richards
said of GM.
   Chevrolet spokeswoman Mary McElyea said the company has started
to get more protective of its name as a trademark. She said GM also
has contacted about 15 to 20 other restaurants nationwide that use
company trademark names.
   ``We got letters from stockholders and chapters of Mothers
Against Drunk Driving asking GM why they'd support establishments
that serve alcohol,'' McElyea said.
</TEXT>
