<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LongOverdueBooks     06-01 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Long Overdue Books,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>About 4,000 Missing Library Books Returned Anonymously</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of books whose absence was
undetected by librarians have returned, solving a mystery that
Brown County Library didn't know it had.
   Because the library has yet to complete an automated inventory
system, employees were unaware many of the books had left the
shelves without being checked out, library director Patricia La
Violette said.
   About 4,000 have been returned in a rush of deposits to night
book drops during the past three weeks. Hundreds were left during
the Memorial Day weekend.
   Ms. La Violette said the books began showing up after she got a
telephone call May 8 from a weeping woman. She said the caller
related her mother had died, leaving behind a large number of
stolen library books.
   Ms. La Violette said the woman did not identify herself. The
library declined comment about the book returns for several weeks
because it did not want to discourage the recovery, she said.
   Most of the books are romances, mysteries and popular novels.
Others are hardback non-fiction works.
   Ms. La Violette said more than half the books did not contain
the bar-code stickers used in the library's inventory system,
meaning they were taken before the coding system was established
four years ago.
   She said the library planned to request an electronic security
system even before the books began showing up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Pepper     06-01 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepper,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Services Scheduled Monday in Tallahassee for Pepper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Memorial services to honor the late
U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper were scheduled for his Miami district and
the capital of the state he represented in Washington for more than
40 years.
   Congress, meanwhile, formally accorded Pepper the honor of lying
in state today in the U.S. Capitol Rotunda, which has been granted
previously to only 26 Americans. His House colleagues paid tribute
to him as a ``national treasure'' and as ``Mr. Senior Citizen'' for
his work on behalf of the elderly.
   Pepper, 88, died of stomach cancer Tuesday at Walter Reed Army
Hospital in Washington.
   A viewing was scheduled at Central Baptist Church in Miami on
Saturday afternoon, followed by a memorial service Sunday
afternoon. Another viewing will be held in the rotunda of the old
state Capitol in Tallahassee on Sunday evening.
   Pepper will be buried Monday in Tallahassee's Oakland Cemetery,
alongside his wife, Mildred, who died of cancer in 1979.
   Gov. Bob Martinez urged the Legislature to name the state's new
Department of Education building in honor of Pepper.
   ``It would be fitting to name this important building in state
government after a man who, decade after decade, stood tall for the
interests of the people he served,'' said Martinez.
   Pepper's body was to lie in state in the nation's capital for
five hours this afternoon. A resolution approving the honor was
approved by the House, 397-0, on Wednesday. The Senate approved it
on a voice vote.
   ``He developed that innate human sympathy that identified with
the problems of people who are suffering,'' House Speaker Jim
Wright told the chamber before announcing his own resignation.
``Claude Pepper was a voice for the voiceless. He offered a helping
hand to the helpless.''
   Rep. Silvio Conte, R-Mass., recalled the scene when President
Bush went to Walter Reed last Thursday to present Pepper with the
nation's highest civilian award, the Medal of Freedom.
   ``Despite what was obviously a great deal of pain, Claude
apologized to the president and first lady that he couldn't stand
up,'' Conte said.
   ``He didn't have to stand up,'' Conte said. ``He was a giant.''
   Pepper was to be only the second incumbent member of the House
to lie in state in the rotunda. The first was Rep. Thaddeus
Stevens, R-Pa., in 1868. The last member of Congress so honored was
Sen. Hubert H. Humphrey, D-Minn., in 1978.
   He joins an honor roster that includes presidents and military
leaders and the unknown dead chosen to represent Americans killed
in four of America's wars.
   Martinez declined to comment on a date for a special election to
fill Pepper's seat until services are concluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
