<SECOND>BC-Japan-Markets,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Stocks Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged
Thursday, while the dollar finished lower againt the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
189.86 points the previous day, shed 285.40 points, or 0.83
percent, to finish at 33,981.35.
   The dollar ended trading at 142.52 yen, down 0.18 yen from
Wednesday's 142.70 yen close. The currency started higher at 143.20
yen but gradually fell while moving between 142.52 yen and 143.25
yen.
   Traders said the dollar's upward momentum was blunted slightly
by reported market intervention by Japan's central bank.
   Some traders said the Bank of Japan sold an estimated $400
million in two rounds of dollar-selling immediately after the
markets opening.
   Many market participants are waiting for the release of U.S.
employment figures for May, slated for Friday, another dealer with
the Bank of Tokyo said, speaking anonymously.
