<FIRST>r a PM-Wright-Hometown     06-01 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Hometown,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright's Resignation Disappoints Many Texans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the city Jim Wright
represented for 34 years expressed little surprise that he resigned
as House speaker, but expressed sorrow and fear about the loss of
political clout they will suffer.
   ``There's no question this is a tremendous loss for the
community. Anybody who knows anything of the American political
process knows the loss of the speakership is a major loss for this
area,'' said Mayor Bob Bolen, whose community has long counted
Wright as a major asset in attracting defense jobs.
   Stinging from an ethics investigation of his business dealings
and sales of a book, Wright told the House on Wednesday he would
resign by the end of June.
   People gathered around the televisions in an electronics shop at
a shopping mall to watch Wright's hourlong nationally broadcast
speech.
   ``I think it's horrible,'' said Lynn Bratcher. ``He's ... the
only one that has ever really done anything for anyone for Texas.
   ``I think it's a shame and disgrace that the news media has
challenged his integrity.''
   Staffers at Wright's office here said they listened to his
resignation speech, but refused to talk about it.
   ``All I can say is, the speaker has spoken, and he speaks for
us,'' said Larry Shannon, director of the office who with the
backing of two security guards turned reporters away.
   Inside, his staff appeared to be carrying on business as usual.
   At another federal office, workers turned on the radio and
cheered as Wright spoke.
   One woman yelled ``Touche!'' as Wright dismissed the House
ethics committee's charges that he violated congressional rules 69
times.
   But minutes later, they fell silent as Wright said, ``I give you
back this job ...,'' promising to give up the speaker's post and
then his seat sometime in June.
   At Bailey's Bar-B-Q across the street from the federal offices,
talk was about daily business, not Wright's problems. But patrons
gave varied responses when asked their opinions.
   ``In my opinion, it probably was the best thing for him,'' said
Deborah Frazier. ``He's had his day. I think he should resign to
save face.''
   ``I'm glad he's going because they need to get it all
straightened out,'' said Bruce Westrick. ``I just think he got
caught.''
   Ken Fowler said Wright got ``chopped up''by the media, adding,
``You can find something wrong in anyone, if you go looking for
it.''
   Some state politicians believe Wright's resignation could damage
Texas' fragile economic recovery that has become dependent on
billions of dollars in government contracts.
   Gov. Bill Clements, Texas' only 20th century Republican
governor, said the Fort Worth Democrat had represented the state
well.
   ``This is not a good day for Texas,'' Clements said. ``As
speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, Jim Wright proved to
be one of the state's most valuable assets and a great national
leader. He brought jobs and opportunities to Texas, and he always
remembered that his roots were in Texas.''
   In Weatherford, the ranching town about 30 miles west of Forth
Worth where Wright grew up and served as mayor in 1950-54, Mayor
Sherry Watson said his resignation was ``truly awful.''
   Officials said it may be impossible to rebuild the political
power or match the economic gain the region enjoyed from Wright's
34-year tenure and his leadership in the Democratic Party.
   Although Wright urged his colleagues against seeking retribution
on his account, Texas Democratic Party Chairman Bob Slagle said:
``Unless some substantial reciprocal gesture is made by
Republicans, I must confess that Jim Wright has a much more
charitable and Christian outlook towards this than I have.''
</TEXT>
