<FIRST>r a PM-NuclearSabotage     06-01 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Sabotage,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Environmentalists Arrested on Nuclear Sabotage Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Expands and updates item in PM-Washington Briefs, a0484</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities expect more arrests after nabbing a
radical environmental group's founder and three other people on
charges they conspired to sabotage two nuclear power plants and an
Energy Department bomb factory.
   The four, and possibly a few others who dubbed themselves the
Evan Mecham Eco-Terrorist International Conspiracy, were plotting
the undertaking when they were arrested Wednesday, the FBI and a
U.S. prosecutor said at a news conference.
   ``This investigation is continuing in Arizona and in several
other states, and additional arrests are anticipated,'' said David
Small, FBI supervisory special agent here.
   He declined to tell reporters when other arrests might be
expected, or how many.
   David Foreman, 42, who in 1979 founded Earth First! _ the
exclamation point is part of the name _ was arrested in Tucson on a
charge of conspiracy. He appeared before a federal magistrate and
was ordered held without bond.
   The three others appeared in Phoenix and were ordered held for
an appearance Friday in U.S. District Court.
   Mark L. Davis, 39, Marc A. Baker, 37, and Margaret Katherine
Millett, 35, all of Prescott, were charged with conspiracy to
sabotage a nuclear plant as well as destruction of an energy
facility, destruction of property used in interstate commerce and
destruction of government property.
   The FBI said Davis and Baker were arrested while trying to cut
down a utility pole supporting a power line that links an
electrical substation with two irrigation pumping stations of the
Central Arizona Project, a multibillion-dollar canal system
bringing Colorado River water to Phoenix and Tucson.
   The group, which took its name from the former Arizona governor
impeached last year, has claimed responsibility for criminal acts
in communiques to news organizations, the FBI said. The
organization's acronym is EMETIC, a medicine that causes vomiting.
   The conspiracy count against Foreman involved a plot to sabotage
the federal government's Rocky Flats Nuclear Weapons Plant near
Golden, Colo., and commercial nuclear power plants near San Luis
Obispo, Calif., and at Wintersburg, U.S. Attorney Stephen M.
McNamee said.
   He said EMETIC's first activity was believed to be a May 1986
raid in which someone threw metal-weighted ropes or copper cables
over 500-kilovolt transmission lines leading out of the Palo Verde
nuclear complex at Wintersburg, 50 miles west of Phoenix.
   Coconino County Sheriff Joe Richards said EMETIC took credit for
attempts in October 1987 and October 1988 to saw through a support
pylon at the Fairfield Snow Bowl near Flagstaff.
   ``This is a significant case. I think this is a significant
development in law enforcement; it was a very coordinated effort
over a long period of time,'' McNamee said.
   ``They're trying to make it a significant case,'' said Nancy
Zierenberg, an Earth First! member in Tucson.
   She declined to comment on the arrests but said Earth First!
adherents usually limited themselves to preservationist activities.
</TEXT>
