<FIRST>r a PM-JohnstownCentennial     06-01 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Johnstown Centennial,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Marks Centennial of Great Flood</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto; LaserGraphic NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oldest survivor of the Johnston flood
said she would just as soon forget it, despite the city's efforts
to commemorate the 100th anniversary of one of the nation's worst
natural disasters.
   ``You don't like to remember things like that too long,''
106-year-old Elsie Frum said Wednesday. ``You know you were there.
You wonder why.''
   Mrs. Frum was 6 when she and her family fled to a hilltop and
watched a wall of water roar through Johnstown on May 31, 1889,
killing 2,209 people.
   ``The sharpest memory I have of the flood is running from it,''
she said. ``My dad ran into the house and grabbed me and my
sisters.''
   Mrs. Frum and the only other known survivor, 100-year-old Frank
Shomo, were honored Wednesday evening at the city's annual Flood
Survivors' Banquet.
   Earlier in the day, thousands of residents and visitors attended
dedications, re-dedications and other events commemorating the
flood, the first and worst of three major floods to devastate this
city in the last century. Others occurred in 1936 and 1977.
   ``It's time to honor those who perished in the past,'' said
Mayor Herbert Pfuhl Jr. ``We're celebrating not a flood or a
disaster, but the resiliency of the community.''
   Johnstowners' determination was evident in the first hours after
the flood when they immediately began clearing debris and
rebuilding the city, said Richard Dill, director of centennial
activities.
   ``That's really the story of Johnstown,'' Dill said.
   Scores of people gathered in Grandview Cemetery in Westmont, a
mountain suburb above the city, for a prayer vigil at the graves of
nearly 700 unidentified flood victims.
   At 4:07 p.m., the time the waters slammed into the city,
hundreds gathered at the confluence of Johnstown's three rivers to
hear a modern diesel locomotive re-create the heroic dash by
Pennsylvania Railroad engineer John Hess, who steamed into the city
with his whistle tied down as a last-minute warning.
   Organizers had scheduled a moment of silence, with church bells
ringing as a cue, but it was interrupted by a Conrail freight train
passing through.
   Still, those present reflected on the disaster.
   ``I think somewhere in the back of everybody's minds there are
those 2,200 people who perished,'' said Chris Butcher, 24, of
nearby Williamsburg.
   Later, Pfuhl and Lt. Gov. Mark Singel lighted a torch that is
meant to become an eternal flame at the rivers' confluence.
   The National Park Service dedicated a $5 million visitors'
center at the site of the dam that unleashed the flood, and the
city re-dedicated the renovated Johnstown Flood Museum.
   The summer-long commemoration, under the theme ``A Triumph of
the Human Spirit,'' highlights the city's comebacks from disaster
and economic adversity.
   The flood occurred after days of rain when the earthen South
Fork Dam collapsed and unleashed 20 million tons of water from a
reservoir that was an exclusive summer resort for millionaire
industrialists Andrew Carnegie, Henry Clay Frick and Andrew Mellon,
among others.
   A wall of water up to 70 feet high barreled 14 miles down the
narrow, meandering Little Conemaugh River Valley, sweeping away
early steel mills, wood-frame homes and barns, livestock and people.
   In an hour, the flood thundered into this bustling city,
crushing scores of homes and downtown businesses in a vast
whirlpool that lasted 10 minutes.
   The city, then with about 10,000 people, suffered an estimated
$17 million in damage at a time the average weekly wage was $10. A
worldwide relief effort, led by Clara Barton and her new American
Red Cross, helped to rebuild.
   The nation's only worse natural disaster was a 1900 hurricane
that claimed about 6,000 lives in Galveston, Texas.
   Heavy rain in the Allegheny Mountains caused floods that killed
25 people 1936 and 80 people in 1977.
   Stung by declines in the steel industry, Johnstown's
unemployment rate peaked at 26.6 percent in 1983, at the same time
it had the nation's lowest crime rate.
   The city now has about 35,000 people, and the area's
unemployment rate had fallen to 6.6 percent in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
