<FIRST>r a PM-UnlicensedDropout     06-01 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unlicensed Dropout,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Vows to Test Anti-Dropout Law in Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old whose wife is pregnant
says an anti-truancy law has taken away his livelihood as well as
his license, so he plans to take the matter to court with the help
of his father.
   One attorney has predicted that if Michael Means and his father,
William, go through with their lawsuit, the ruling will set a
precedent.
   Under an education reform law passed by the West Virginia
Legislature last summer, students under age 18 who miss more than
10 consecutive days or have 15 unexcused absences must give up
their driving privileges. County school systems notify the
Department of Motor Vehicles of students who have dropped out.
   The measure was the nation's first anti-truancy law to include
revoking teen-agers' drivers licenses.
   ``The law is fair for 16-year-olds and for most people ...
people who are not married,'' said Means, who lost his job as a
Charleston gas attendant after his driving privileges were taken
away.
   ``But for many, I don't think it should be the same. If you
break the law, you pay like an adult, so why not be able to drive
like an adult?''
   Lawmakers in Wisconsin and California approved similar laws, but
Gov. George Deukmejian vetoed California's version. On Wednesday, a
Kentucky legislator introduced a similar bill in that state.
   ``Our first step will go through the circuit court to see if we
can't get this law declared unconstitutional,'' said William Means.
   Department lawyer Tom Madden said if Means and his son file the
suit, it will be the first court test of the law and will set a
standard.
   ``I think this might be a case of first impression. I don't want
to go out on a limb, but this may be the first case in the country.
It will definitely be the first time it reaches this stage in West
Virginia,'' Madden said.
   Means dropped out of Roosevelt Junior High School in Kanawha
County a year ago when he was in ninth grade. He and his wife,
Tonya, 16, are expecting their first child in the fall.
   Means got a license before dropping out and worked as a gas
station attendant. But he misplaced his license in October and had
to quit when the state wouldn't replace it because he was a
dropout. On Tuesday, the DMV affirmed its decision.
   ``There were supposed to be exceptions to this law,'' Means'
father said. ``My son is married, he's an expectant father with the
baby due in September. They have a house on their own, trying to
make it on their own.
   ``With the decision, I see no way for him to gain employment and
support his family. If this isn't an exception, I don't know what
is.''
   Madden said the law allows for hardship cases when the
``withdraw is beyond the control of the student.'' He said that
decision lies with the counties and not the deparment.
   Jim Simmons, associate superintendent of Kanawha County pupil
support services, said the county tries to help the students on an
individual basis.
   ``There was an opportunity in this situation for the student to
finish his education,'' Simmons said.
   Last year, 17.4 percent of West Virginia's high school students
dropped out and in Kanawha County, 14.8 percent left early.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
