<FIRST>r i PM-MineDisaster     06-01 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Disaster,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Dead, Eight Missing In Mine Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight miners were reported missing
after heavy rains triggered landslides at gold mining tunnels in
the southern Philippines. Officials said today that three people
were killed in a related fire.
   Mario Luis Jacinto, regional director of the Bureau of Mines,
said the incidents occurred Tuesday in the mining town of Mount
Diwalwal in Davao del Norte province, about 580 miles southeast of
Manila.
   Jacinto said the rains loosened soil in the area, causing 13
tunnels to collapse. He said 135 miners were able to leave the
tunnels but eight were reported missing.
   Several Manila radio stations and newspapers reported that as
many as 13 people died and 1,000 others were trapped in the
collapsed tunnels, but Jacinto could not confirm it.
   ``We talked to a number of survivors and residents in the area
but they said the number of missing could not be that high,''
Jacinto said.
   The Diwalwal mining area had occasionally been hit by cave-ins
but most went unreported because miners fear the government will
halt operations there.
   Almost simultaneous with the collapse, Jacinto said, mud caused
a charcoal pit in a blacksmith shop to tumble and ignited a
three-hour fire in a nearby housing area that burned 165 shanties
and 15 houses.
   The fire killed three people and injured nine, he added.
</TEXT>
