<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-01 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Plunge On Tokyo Market, Dollar Off Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices plunged today on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
while the U.S. dollar declined against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
189.86 points Wednesday, dropped 285.40 points, or 0.83 percent,
finishing the day at 33,981.35.
   The dollar closed at 142.52 yen, its lowest level of the day and
0.18 yen below its finish on Wednesday. The U.S. currency opened
higher at 143.20 yen and ranged up to 143.25 yen.
   Minori Takeuchi with Chemical Bank in Tokyo said trading was
``quite rough'' with wide fluctuations.
   ``The dollar started higher in Tokyo, but gradually fell as
investors sold it to buy Swiss francs,'' she said.
   The Swiss National Bank announced it will begin to use a
floating interest rate system, which market analysts saw as good
news for the Swiss franc.
   Ms. Takeuchi said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market to
slow the U.S. currency's rise early in the morning when the dollar
opened higher.
   Many Japanese investors also were cautious because of
speculation that West Germany may raise its discount rate, traders
said.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei index plunged in the afternoon
as concern spread over the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's
continuing problems in choosing a successor to Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita, dealers said.
   A group of young Liberal Democrats said today they would back
their own candidate for prime minister, despite the selection of
Former Minister Sousuke Uno by party leaders.
   A dealer with a major securities firm said speculation over a
possible additional hike in Japan's official discount rate also
discouraged market participants.
   Market analysts said the central bank might have to consider
another hike in the rate if the dollar keeps rising against the yen.
   On Wednesday the central bank raised its discount rate 0.75
percentage points to 3.25 percent.
   Trading was hectic with massive selling orders. Volume on the
market's first section was estimated at 1.6 billion shares, up from
Wednesday's 1 billion shares.
</TEXT>
