<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-01 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar had a mixed performance against other
major currencies today in slow early trading in Europe. Gold prices
fell.
   In Frankfurt, dealers said the market opinion was divided over
whether West Germany's central bank will alter its interest rates.
There was speculation the bank might float the West German Lombard
rate, now 6.5 percent, which would depress the dollar.
   ``People are preparing for the possibility that they might do
something with the Lombard rate,'' said Manfred Totzauer, a trader
at Citibank in Frankfurt. ``They could introduce something like the
special (floating) Lombard. But it's still all speculation.''
   On Wednesday the dollar fell in New York on speculation that the
U.S. Federal Reserve Bank and possibly other central banks were
selling dollars to rein in the American currency. A high dollar
makes U.S. exports more expensive.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar slid against the yen to close at 142.52 yen,
down 0.18 yen from Wednesday. Later, in London, the dollar
continued to fall and was quoted at 142.43 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.9801 West German marks, up from 1.9755
   _1.7102 Swiss francs, up from 1.7055
   _6.7185 French francs, up from 6.6855
   _2.2286 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2460
   _1,434.75 Italian lire, down from 1,443.00
   _1.2065 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2061.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5746 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5682 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $361.90 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $363.50. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $360.35 compared with $363.43 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.71 an ounce to close at a
bid $360.97.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.16 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $5.20.
</TEXT>
