<FIRST>r i PM-Shevardnadze     06-01 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shevardnadze,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>French, British Forces Could Complicate Bush Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze has
called President Bush's disarmament proposals basically positive,
but says he doubts an agreement can be reached within a year on
reducing troop levels in Europe.
   Bush has called for accord on the reductions within 12 months.
   Speaking to reporters at the airport before leaving for Moscow
on Wednesday, Shevardnadze said the presence of British and French
units in Europe could complicate the Bush proposals, the
conservative French newspaper Le Figaro reported today.
   ``I want to emphasize that the British and French forces in West
Germany represent 100,000 men and this creates an imbalance,'' he
said.
   Shevardnadze also said he was ``disappointed'' by the NATO's
declaration at its Brussels summit this week that it favors
delaying talks on reducing short-range nuclear missile arsenals in
Europe until a conventional arms accord is completed and put into
effect.
   During the North Atlantic Treaty Organization meeting, Bush
proposed a cut in U.S. and Soviet troops in Europe to 275,000 each.
This would mean a 10 percent reduction for the United States but a
reduction of more than half for the Soviets.
   Shevardnadze was in Paris to attend a human rights conference
and before leaving met with Foreign Minister Roland Dumas to
discuss the scheduled July 4-7 visit of Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to France.
</TEXT>
