<FIRST>r a PM-CottonClub     06-01 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cotton Club,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Says Slain Producer Feared Trouble From ``The Cotton Club''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slain producer Roy Radin was nervous and
expected trouble about ``The Cotton Club'' movie on the night he
vanished, according to the co-star of the old TV series ``Sanford
and Son.''
   Radin asked Demond Wilson to carry a gun and follow him to a
business dinner on the night of his disappearance, the actor
testified Wedneday.
   ``He said that there might be some trouble. He said that
something might happen to him as a result of his association with
the film thing ... `The Cotton Club,''' Wilson said.
   A month after his disappearance on May 13, 1983, Radin's
decomposing, bullet-riddled corpse was found in a dry riverbed 65
miles north of Los Angeles.
   Wilson testified at a preliminary hearing to determine whether
four people should stand trial for Radin's abduction-slaying.
   Radin, 33, a theatrical producer from New York, was trying to
make his mark in Hollywood. Radin was Wilson's personal manager and
was enmeshed in a deal with producer Robert Evans to finance ``The
Cotton Club.''
   Radin told Wilson to follow him as the producer headed for a
business dinner with ``important people'' at a swanky Beverly Hills
restaurant, Wilson said.
   ``He asked me to follow and just watch and see if anything
happened,'' Wilson said, adding later, ``He said if anything were
to happen he wanted someone there to observe it.''
   Wilson, who acknowledged he had a drug habit then, said he lost
Radin's limousine in traffic on Sunset Boulevard and never saw him
again.
   Under further questioning Wilson said he used cocaine, alcohol
and pills in 1983. Asked by an attorney whether he underwent a drug
rehabilitation program, he said: ``No, sir. I found Christ.''
   Wilson said he last saw Radin with a woman ``in a glitzy dress''
as they stepped into a limousine headed for dinner at La Scala.
   The woman has been identified previously as Karen DeLayne
Greenberger, a reputed drug dealer who is charged with three men in
the Radin murder.
   The prosecution contends Mrs. Greenberger arranged Radin's
murder after they fought about her share of profits from ``The
Cotton Club.''
   Mrs. Greenberger, who introduced Radin and Evans, is charged
with Alex Lamota Marti, William Molony Mentzer and Robert Ulmer
Lowe, former bodyguards for Hustler Magazine publisher Larry Flynt.
Lowe is fighting extradition in Maryland.
   Wilson was visibly nervous during his testimony and told the
judge at one point: ``I'm new at this. Please forgive me.''
   A defense attorney attacked Wilson's testimony, noting the actor
never before told anyone that Radin expressed fear.
   ``He was pretty fearful,'' Wilson insisted. ``There was a lot of
anxiety around him. ... It was not a fear that somebody's hands
were shaking. It's something that a friend knows.''
   Wilson said he was concerned enough to offer to call police, but
Radin declined and asked if he had a gun.
   ``He knew I carried heat and that was that,'' said Wilson.
``When he went out with me he was confident.''
   Wilson's former secretary has given a conflicting version of
these events, saying that Wilson and she saw Radin's limousine make
a right turn followed by a car full of men, but Wilson decided not
to stay with him.
</TEXT>
