<FIRST>r i PM-Tutu-DeathRow     06-01 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tutu-Death Row,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Says White Racist Killer Should Be Reprieved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu has called
on the government to reprieve all prisoners on Death Row, including
a white extremist sentenced to hang for killing seven blacks and an
Indian man.
   Speaking at a church meeting Wednesday night, the black Anglican
leader called for abolition of the death penalty and an amnesty for
the more than 200 prisoners on Death Row.
   ``I include even Barend Strydom, who is a child and product fed
on the hatred and contempt that are the logical consequences of
apartheid,'' said Tutu, referring to the 23-year-old former
policeman condemned in Pretoria Supreme Court last week.
   Strydom, who testified that he considered blacks to be animals,
shot and killed seven people and wounded 16 blacks during a
shooting spree on the sidewalks of downtown Pretoria in November.
   A week earlier, he killed one black woman and wounded another at
a squatter camp in what he described as a practice attack.
   In calling for reprieves, Tutu mentioned the so-called Upington
14 _ a black woman and 13 black men sentenced last week to hang for
complicity in the mob killing of a black policeman during township
unrest in 1985. Only one of the 14 was found to have contributed
physically to the death pf the policeman.
   ``It makes you shudder that we can sentence 14 people to death
at one fell swoop,'' said Tutu. ``That includes a lady of 60 years
of age.''
</TEXT>
