<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     06-01 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Rivals Put Forth Another Candidate for Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A faction in the governing Liberal Democratic Party
today offered its own candidate to succeed Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita after objecting to the choice of the party leaders.
   Legislator Shizuka Kamei said Ganri Yamashita, a former Cabinet
member and political foe of Takeshita's, would run against Foreign
Minister Sousuke Uno.
   On Wednesday, Uno, 66, agreed to take the job after leaders in
the scandal-tainted party decided he was the best person for the
job.
   But members of several of the party's major factions opposed Uno
because he is a senior member of the faction of former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone. It was during Nakasone's 1982-87 tenure
that the so-called Recruit scandal developed.
   ``This is the will of the people, who oppose the party's
decision on Mr. Uno's candidacy,'' Kamei said. ``We asked Mr.
Yamashita to stand for us, and he said he would.''
   The 68-year-old Yamashita said he accepted the offer to run.
   Share prices slumped on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, in part due to
nervousness about a split in the pro-business Liberal Democratic
Party, dealers said. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues shed 285.40 points, or 0.83 percent, to finish at 33,981.35.
   Yamashita represents the same constituency in Shiga prefecture
as Uno. He served as director-general of the Defense Agency under
Prime Minister Masayoshi Ohira in the late 1970's.
   Kamei's Liberal Progressive Alliance has 48 members in the Diet,
Japan's parliament. Kamei said he would have no trouble getting the
required 50 signatures to back Yamashita's candidacy and force a
vote between the candidates.
   Takeshita is resigning to take responsibility for the Recruit
scandal, which has stained the top ranks of politics, business and
the bureaucracy. The Recruit Co. is an information services
conglomerate that offered cut-rate priced shares to political and
business leaders, allegedly to win favors.
   Many of the Liberal Democratic Party's top leaders have been
deemed ineligible for the prime minister's job because they have
been linked to the scandal.
   Business leaders welcomed the choice of Uno, noting he gained
international experience as foreign minister since November 1987
and was untainted by the scandal.
   The Liberal Democrats need someone with an untarnished image to
boost their popularity before elections this summer for half of
parliament's upper house. It took more than a month to find such a
person after Takeshita announced on April 25 that he would resign.
   Party leaders first approached the party's Executive Council
chairman, Masayoshi Ito, 75, but he refused the job, citing poor
health and dissatisfaction with the party's handling of reforms.
</TEXT>
