<FIRST>r i PM-BarbaraBush     06-01 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barbara Bush,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Confesses Her Pie Crust Isn't So Hot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush confessed today that her pie crust
was nothing to brag about.
   During a relaxed visit to an adult education center in Brixton,
south London, the first lady visited a cooking class where students
were busy making strudel pastry, noisily slapping mounds of dough
on countertops.
   Stephanie Rees, an American teacher who has lived in Britain for
18 years, persuaded Mrs. Bush to try her hand at stretching some
dough.
   ``Notice, I washed my hands,'' Mrs. Bush said.
   ``Oooh, that feels wonderful,'' she said as she worked the
dough. ``This is sort of fun.''
   She said she had never made that kind of pastry.
   ``My pie crust is not one you write home about, you know what I
mean,'' Mrs. Bush said. ``I envy you. This is gorgeous.''
   While President Bush conferred with Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher at 10 Downing Street, Mrs. Bush spent 75 minutes touring
cooking, English-language and fashion design classes and visiting a
day care center at the Lambeth Institute's Strand Center.
   ``As you know, I am very interested in adult literacy and family
literacy,'' Mrs. Bush said. ``I am putting my focus in the United
States on family literacy.''
   ``This is a marvelous coalition of public agencies,'' she said.
``It's been a very exciting morning for me. Everything impressed me
about it.''
   The school's mostly primary education classes at the sprawling
red brick school attract about 2,000 students a week, two-thirds of
them from London's ethnic communities.
   Mrs. Bush wore a black and white polka dot and plaid outfit and
a three-strand pearl choker for her only solo appearance during the
Bushes' two-day stay in London.
   One fashion student, Icema Paschal, told Mrs. Bush she was
wearing a dress she had made especially for the occasion. The first
lady complimented Icema on her creation.
   In the day care center, toddler Cicely Convoy gave Mrs. Bush a
kiss and a basket of pink roses and carnations.
   Afterward, Ms. Paschal said, ``I think she's quite down to
earth, quite nice. She's quite a relaxed person.''
   Tutor Gulshan Ramzan said, ``It was wonderful. My students,
although mentally handicapped, they were so excited.''
   ``I applaud her enormously for coming here,'' said Neil
Fletcher, a council member of the Inner London Education Authority
who served as Mrs. Bush's guide. He criticized the government's
plans to abolish the authority, which will force the center to rely
on the local funds.
</TEXT>
