<FIRST>r a PM-CourthouseShooting     06-01 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Courthouse Shooting,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>1,000 Protest Ex-Officer's Manslaughter Conviction in Judge-Wife's
Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted only of manslaughter
for shooting his estranged wife, a judge, to death in her
courthouse chambers should get the stiffest possible sentence,
angry protesters said.
   A thousand people rallied Wednesday outside the county Hall of
Justice to protest the manslaughter conviction of former police
officer Clarence Ratliff in the death of District Judge Carol
Irons. Irons, who has been described as a supporter of victims of
family violence, was killed last October.
   On May 11, a jury acquitted Ratliff of first-degree murder,
which carries a possible sentence of life in prison without parole.
Ratliff, 53, had testified that he was drunk and upset over their
impending divorce and did not mean to kill Irons, who was 40. The
lesser charge of manslaughter carries a possible sentence of up to
15 years.
   But the jury also convicted the 21-year police veteran of
attempted murder for firing at two officers who tried to help Irons.
   ``We are outraged that the murder of a woman is considered less
serious than shooting at _ and missing _ two men,'' said one
protester, Dotti Clune. She described the jury's decision as a
``slap-on-the-hand verdict.''
   ``Carol Irons was not manslaughtered. She was murdered,'' said
another speaker, psychologist Sherry Redding.
   More than 1,000 letters have been sent to Kent County Circuit
Judge Dennis Kolenda, urging the maximum allowable prison term at
Ratliff's June 12 sentencing.
   Attempted murder carries a possible sentence of life in prison
with possibility of parole. But Michigan Attorney General Frank
Kelley has recommended that Ratliff be sentenced to 25 to 40 years
in prison because those sentenced to life can be paroled after 10
years and those who get 25 to 40 years generally serve at least 20
years.
   The protesters did not specify the sentence they want the judge
to give but said it should be the harshest possible.
   Kolenda said he was reading each letter.
   ``A judge has to walk a tightrope,'' he said after the rally.
``Some decisions must be made by the letter of the law and some
decisions must take into account community sentiment.''
</TEXT>
