<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     06-01 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Convicted Of Murdering British Soldiers in Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were convicted and
sentenced to life in prison today for murdering two British
soldiers who were beaten and shot after apparently straying into
the funeral of an IRA member.
   Lord Chief Justice Sir Brian Hutton recommended that Alex
Murphy, 31, and Harry Maguire, 29, each serve at least 25 years
before being eligible for release.
   Both men pleaded innocent, and neither was accused of firing the
shots that killed Cpls. Derek Wood, 24, and David Howes, 23, on
March 19, 1988. Police are continuing their investigation.
   Hutton presided over a 32-day trial in which army film and
television news videotapes were a key to the prosecution's case.
   The soldiers drove into the path of mourners at the funeral for
Kevin Brady. He was one of three Roman Catholics killed when a
Protestant, Michael Stone, opened fire at an Irish Republican Army
funeral March 16.
   The IRA, which is outlawed in Northern Ireland, has been
fighting a 20-year guerrilla war against British rule of the
province.
   TV film showed Wood and Howes surrounded by a crowd that
hammered their car and dragged them out.
   Film taken from an army helicopter showed the men then being
beaten, stripped and driven off in a black taxi. They later were
shot to death.
   Murphy wrestled one of the soldiers to the ground. Maguire was
seen helping get the soldiers into the taxi.
   Murphy also was shown standing near the soldiers in Penny Lane,
where they were shot. Maguire was seen getting out of the taxi,
before the gunmen arrived, and fighting with Howes.
   Wood was shot twice in the head. Howes was shot in the head at
close range.
   The unidentified gunman passed the weapon to another man who
fired a shot into Wood's body, then another at Howes' body.
   Murphy and Maguire, both of Belfast, were also convicted of
possessing a weapon, false imprisonment and causing grievous bodily
harm.
   The news film, confiscated from the British Broadcasting Corp.,
Independent Television News and Radio Telefis Eireann _ Ireland's
national network _ was supplemented by an anonymously photographed
video. Detectives said they examined a quarter of a million still
frames taken from 17 hours of tape.
   The trial was the first of five involving the soldiers' deaths.
Twenty-seven other men face a variety of charges ranging from
assault to kidnapping.
</TEXT>
