<FIRST>r a PM-BarricadedNuns     06-01 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barricaded Nuns,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letter From Rome Upholds Order for Barricaded Nuns to Leave Monastery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four nuns barricaded in their
monastery's infirmary will continue their eight-month protest
against liberalizations in their lifestyle despite a renewed call
from the Vatican to end the standoff.
   The Paterson Diocese announced Wednesday that Vatican officials
had rejected the nuns' appeal and again ordered them to leave the
building of the Most Blessed Virgin Mary of Mount Carmel.
   However, a spokeswoman for the nuns says they will not leave.
   The nuns fled to the infirmary on Oct. 4, saying they feared
eviction for protesting changes to their monastery, such as
introduction of television and sweets. Diocese officials said the
issue was the nuns' refusal to obey their prioress, Mother Teresa
Hewitt.
   Betty Sutton, spokeswoman for the nuns, said the letter from The
Congregation for Institutes of Consecrated Life and Societies of
Apostolic Life ordering the nuns to leave was an answer to a March
appeal. But an appeal filed in July 1988 on other issues remains
unanswered, and the nuns will not leave the monastery until it is,
she said.
   ``They're going to go on just the way they have been,'' Mrs.
Sutton said. ``There's still an appeal out there and they're still
going to keep waiting for an answer.''
   The nuns have said they were awaiting an answer from the
Apostolica Signatura, the Vatican's highest court.
   But in a separate letter to Bishop Frank Rodimer, bishop of the
diocese, Cardinal Achille Silvestrini, Prefect of the Apostolica
Signatura, said ``there is no recourse pending before this Supreme
Tribunal concerning'' the nuns.
   In letters from Rome to each of the women, the Congregation said
in its most recent ruling: ``The problem has been carefully
re-examined from all points of view. The good of your soul, the
safeguarding of the values of religious life, respect for the
established authority and the witness we have to render to the
Church, convinces us to confirm what has been decided.''
   The excerpt from the letter was made available by Timothy
Manning, spokesman for the Paterson Diocese.
   Manning said there has been no discussion on what to do with the
nuns if they again refuse to leave the monastery. The Carmelite
community could decide to remove them from their vows, he said.
   The vows of two of the nuns expired during the protest. A fifth
nun left the monastery March 19, citing health reasons.
</TEXT>
