<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka-India     06-01 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka-India,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Wants Indian Troops Out Within Two Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president said today he will ask
India to withdraw its peacekeeping troops from Sri Lanka by the end
of July.
   Also today, suspected Sinhalese extremists shot and killed a
senior police detective and set a bomb that killed a provincial
city council member.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who took office five months ago,
repeatedly has said he wants India's soldiers to withdraw, but his
announcement today was the first time he set a date.
   ``During my election campaign I pledged to ask the Indian troops
to leave. This pledge I will keep,'' Premadasa told a Buddhist
gathering at a temple in Battaramula, seven miles southeast of
Colombo.
   The first Indian force of 3,000 soldiers arrived in Sri Lanka on
July 30, 1987, under a peace plan signed by Indian Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi and Premadasa's predecessor, Julius R. Jayewardene.
   The contingent swelled to 70,000 as Indian troops tried to
disarm guerrillas from the Tamil Hindu minority, whose separatist
war against the Sinhalese Buddhist majority has claimed 9,000 lives
since 1983. An estimated 45,000 Indian soldiers are still deployed
in northern and eastern Sri Lanka, where most Tamils live and hope
to set up a homeland.
   ``I will shortly ask Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi to mark
the second anniversary by totally withdrawing the Indian army from
this country,'' Premadasa said.
   More than 700 Indian soldiers have died in the peacekeeping
campaign.
   Premadasa said Sri Lanka was grateful for the sacrifices made by
India, but he added: ``We will also be grateful if India agrees to
withdraw its troops from this country.''
   India has said from the outset of its involvement in Sri Lanka
that it had no plans to stay indefinitely. India joined the
conflict under pressure from its own powerful Tamil minority of 60
million.
   The 1987 accord led to a violent campaign by the militant
Sinhalese People's Liberation Front against the Sri Lankan
government, which it said made too many concessions to Tamils. The
ultranationalist Sinhalese have been blamed for 3,500 deaths in the
war.
   Sinhalese extremists today shot and killed police detective
Bennet Perera as his car passed through Ratmalana, 10 miles from
the city center, police said. Perera headed a special unit
investigating the ultranationalists.
   In the second incident today, Sinhalese militants threw a bomb
at the home of Leslie Ranagala, a governing United National Party
provincial city council member, that killing him and his guard.
   No group claimed responsibility for the killings.
   The Tamil guerrilla campaign grew out of the ethnic minority's
charges that the Sinhalese discriminated against them.
   Sinhalese, who form 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
dominate the government and military. Tamils make up 18 percent of
the island off southern India formerly known as Ceylon.
   Under Premadasa, the government has opened negotiations on
ending the civil war with leaders of the most powerful Tamil rebel
group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam. The militant
Sinhalese, however, have refused to particiapte.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
