<FIRST>r a PM-BestRejection     06-01 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Best Rejection,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Bullet Night' Brings out the Best in Job Rejection Letters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Gathering Place bar, a special
honor goes to the Northwestern University student whose job
rejection letter is most like a swift kick in the seat of the pants.
   On Wednesday, with graduation approaching, it was time to select
a champion for the Class of 1989 and top honors went to student
David Whitlock, 22, who became ``Whitelock'' in a form letter
rejection from E &amp; J Gallo Winery.
   And the letter was dated Jan. 8, about a month before he was
interviewed.
   ``If I had gotten the letter when it was dated, I could have
avoided the interview process all together,'' he said.
   Other finalists included chemical engineering student Stanley
Russell _ or ``Stanely,'' as Texas Instruments Inc. called him in
its zinger.
   Russell, 22, said that when he sent in his resume, the bad news
came right back in a Mailgram.
   ``They wanted to reject me so fast they couldn't wait to use the
regular mail,'' he said.
   A half dozen times this spring, the Senior Class Gift Executive
Committee put together ``bullet nights,'' where students got a free
cup of beer if they submitted a rejection letter. The holder of the
most humiliating specimen of the evening won a pitcher of beer.
   Wednesday night's event in the bar in the student union pitted
this year's previous winners against each other.
   Bullet nights put a pinch of humor into the depressing business
of being turned down for a job, and gave the senior committee a
chance to put the touch on students for donations for the class
gift to the university.
   While some of the letters were embarrassing or insulting, others
were polite and straightforward.
   Russell said he got a nice rejection letter after being flown
down to Atlanta for a second interview.
   ``They try to make it sound like they're at fault for not having
something for someone of your amazing abilities,'' he said.
   ``They'll tell you they'll keep your resume on file,'' Russell
said. ``It's a nice way of saying, `When we get the cafeteria up
and running and we need a dishwasher, we'll call you.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
