<FIRST>r a PM-BotchedBurials     06-01 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Botched Burials,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son of Funeral Director Convicted in Burial Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has found the son of a former
funeral director guilty of larceny for his role in helping bury a
body without a casket.
   Gary Wilks, 31, faces additional charges in a burial scandal in
which authorities found more than two dozen bodies buried without
caskets and vaults in Kentucky and Tennessee.
   Wilks was convicted Wednesday in Sumner County Court of larceny
by false pretenses in the burial of a man in 1988 without a vault
and casket paid for by the man's family. A vault is a metal or
concrete enclosure in the ground into which the casket is lowered
at burial.
   Wilks' father, Bobby, 53, director of the Barber Funeral Home in
Robertson County, pleaded guilty in Sumner County Court on May 17
to two counts of grand larceny by false pretenses in connection
with two other burials.
   The elder Wilks, who faces a maximum prison term of 12 years in
the Sumner County case, will enter pleas next week on 71 counts of
burial fraud in Robertson County.
   Gary Wilks, who faces two additional charges in Robertson County
in connection with improper burials there, will be sentenced July
14 on the Sumner County charge. He faces three to six years in
prison.
   Prosecutors described Gary Wilks as an apprentice funeral
director at his father's funeral home.
   Defense attorney Terry McNabb, who presented no witnesses,
argued that his client was being railroaded toward a conviction
because he is Bobby Wilks' son.
</TEXT>
