<FIRST>r i PM-Malawi-Refugees     06-01 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malawi-Refugees,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>20,000 More Fugitives Flee Civil War in Mozambique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELINDA HAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANGAMBIKA, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewed fighting in neighboring
Mozambique's civil war has led about 20,000 people to seek refuge
in already crowded camps in Malawi, officials say.
   Local authorities say the latest exodus raises to 652,000 the
number of refugees now in Malawi, a poor nation of 8 million people.
   Fighting between troops of the Marxist government and right-wing
rebels in Mozambique's 12-year civil war has intensified in the
past month, said Fletcher Zenengeya, a top official in President
Hasting Kamuzu Banda's office.
   ``We are very worried,'' he said. ``We thought the situation in
Mozambique had stabilized.''
   At least 1,800 Mozambicans recently fled to an isolated camp in
Changambika, near the western border, that already houses 9,000
people.
   Some of the arrivals said rebels of the Mozambique National
Resistance, or Renamo, stormed the government-occupied settlements
of Kapirizanja and Ntsakama in Tete province late last month.
   Government troops fired a few shots before fleeing into the
bush, pursued by the guerrillas, the refugees said.
   They said Zimbabwean troops based in Mozambique to guard
transport links helped recapture the settlements but most civilians
fled.
   ``Rebels looted our possessions and crops,'' said Gera Jazi, who
lived in Kapirizanja. ``Many houses were burned to the ground. Some
women, including my own daughter, were kidnapped to be used as
porters and wives by the rebels.''
   Relief officials said that after new fighting at Villa Nova and
Mutarara farther south in Mozambique's Zambezia province a week ago
about 500 refugees fled to camps in Malawi.
   Relief officals, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they
believed government troops faced increasing difficulties defending
remote rural settlements.
   The Malawi government, worried about crowding in camps, has
begun transporting new refugees to less populated areas. In Nsanje,
where vegetation has been stripped to build tens of thousands of
shelters, Mozambicans outnumber Malawians 3-to-2.
   Patrick De Souza of the U.N. High Commission For Refugees said
food supplies were low.
   ``We had made contingency plans for the new influx, but the
problem is that our supply pipeline is not functioning,'' he said.
``The groundnuts, maize and beans that donors promised have not
arrived in time.''
   No groundnuts, one of the main sources of protein for refugees,
have been delivered since December.
   ``As a result, malnutrition is now our biggest problem,'' said
Dr. Alice Brodel, head of the French relief organization Doctors
Without Borders.
</TEXT>
