<FIRST>r a PM-FalconChick     06-01 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Falcon Chick,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescued Chick Returned To Downtown Nest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state biologist rappelled down a
23-story downtown office building in the early morning fog today to
return a peregrine falcon chick to its nest on a narrow ledge.
   Thomas French, director of the state's endangered species
program, rescued the chick last week after viewers of a local cable
television company, which has kept a camera on the nest
24-hours-a-day, called to say the chick was having trouble
breathing.
   French said a tendon from a piece of meat had become tangled
around the chick's tongue and the chick was near death. It swiftly
recovered after the meat was dislodged by veterinarians at Tufts
Veterinary School, and had doubled its weight during its eight days
of treatment.
   As French perched on the narrow ledge on the 21st floor, with
the struggling chick in his hands, the mother falcon continually
dove at his helmet, at one point dislodging it. The helmet dropped
to the ledge and French quickly grabbed it, but his eyeglasses
ended up on the street hundreds of feet below.
   ``She's a fierce wild bird,'' French said. ``And she was just
trying to protect her nest.''
   The 2{-week-old chicks were the first of the endangered
predators to be hatched in western Massachusetts in more than 40
years.
</TEXT>
