<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru   06-01 0840</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0583,0863</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Denounces State of Agriculture, Says Ligachev Incompetent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to ADD formation of commission on Baltics;
moves up description of Ligachev. Pickup 13th pvs, `Ligachev became...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deputy in the new Soviet parliament today gave a
scathing review of the nation's agricultural system and said the
Poliburo member in charge of the vast network of state-run farms is
incompetent.
   It was the latest in a series of contentious speeches during the
inaugural session of the Congress of People's Deputies, and this
time Yegor K. Ligachev was on the receiving end.
   ``How could this happen?'' deputy Yuri D. Chernichenko asked of
Ligachev's appointment to head the Communist Party commission for
agriculture. The commission was created last year to marshal
official efforts to curtail chronic food shortages.
   Heads swiveled in the 2,250-member Congress toward where
Ligachev was sitting with other Politburo members, but the
white-haired Siberian sat impassively.
   Also today, Congress formed a commission to determine whether
the Kremlin absorbed the three Baltic republics by force.
   Decades of official Soviet doctrine maintain that the republics
_ Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania _ voluntarily joined the Soviet
Union in 1940, ending their existence as independent nations. But
secret protocols to the 1939 German-Soviet non-aggression pact
deeded control of the Baltic area to the Kremlin, and Soviet troops
moved in the next year.
   Chernichenko, a Moscow-based television broadcaster who
specializes in agriculture and rural life, ridiculed the
performance of the vast state-run farm sector, saying: ``How can it
be explained ... that the economy that produces five times more
tractors and 10 times more combine harvesters than the United
States produces only half as much bread?''
   Ligachev, as a member of the ruling Poliburo, would once have
been immune to such criticism from a parliamentarian.
Chernichenko's sarcastic swipes at him were in keeping with the
unprecedented tone of the congressional session, which began last
week.
   On Wednesday, Communist Party maverick Boris N. Yeltsin said
Soviets are worse off now than they were before President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's reforms, and he held Gorbachev responsible.
   The same day, the president of the Latvian republic, Anatoly
Gorbunov, proposed making the 15 Soviet republics sovereign states
in charge of their own resources and laws.
   Also Wednesday, deputy Yuri Vlasov, who won a weightlifting gold
medal in the 1960 Olympics, assailed the KGB secret police and
criticized Gorbachev's handling of ethnic unrest in Soviet Georgia.
   Such remarks were never heard in the old parliament, the Supreme
Soviet.
   Chernichenko repeated a question to the Congress he said voters
had asked at campaign appearances leading up to the March election:
   ``Why is this politically significant branch, the branch which
determines the future, ruled by a person who does not understand
anything about it and who failed in the field of ideology?''
   Ligachev became head of the agriculture commission after being
relieved of the ideology portfolio, the position that once made him
the No. 2 Kremlin leader.
   Ligachev noted last year that there was plenty to eat in the
Siberian region of Tomsk when he served there as party chief in
1965-83, but nothing in his background marks him as a specialist on
farming.
   He studied at an institute of aircraft building.
   In the past year, Ligachev and Gorbachev have placed different
emphasis on what must be done to ease shortages of meat, fruit,
vegetables and other foodstuffs. Gorbachev has promoted leasing of
state-held land to individuals as the chief way to increase farm
output.
   But Ligachev has said the giant state and collective farms, onto
which millions of peasants were herded during Josef Stalin's rule,
are the backbone of Soviet agriculture.
   Neither approach scored a clear victory when the party's Central
Committee decreed a set of agricultural reforms in March. The
policy-making body approved the leasing of farmland to peasants for
as long as 50 years, but also maintained state and collective farms.
   Asked about Chernichenko's remarks, Politburo member Lev N.
Zaikov, the Moscow party chief, told reporters: ``You can't just
take the podium, not knowing a person, and say such things.''
   Another Politburo member, Vadim A. Medvedev, said the party had
taken action to fix the problems with farms Chernichenko cited, but
he acknowledged: ``The farm problems are indeed very serious and
they give rise to stormy emotions and statements.''
   Medvedev told reporters Ligachev was unfairly singled out for
criticism because ``all members of the Politburo more or less take
on responsibilities for all questions. We all answer for
everything.''
   The inaugural session of the Congress was to have ended
Wednesday, but it appeared the open forum would last another week
unless presiding officers cut off debate.
   Gorbachev announced to the Congress late Wednesday that 469
deputies had signed up to speak; just 250 were heard in the first
six days of debate, which have been televised live to the nation.
   Gorbachev diplomatically suggested the time allotted each
speaker be cut by five minutes, to 10 minutes. Deputies responded
with a joint ``Nyet!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
