<DOCNO> AP890601-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--SpeedingPolice     06-01 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Speeding Police,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Unit Will Look For Speeding Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undercover police officers in unmarked
cars are going to be out on the prowl for traffic law violators _
police who speed.
   Sheriff Jim McMillan says he has received complaints about
officers speeding when there's no need.
   McMillan said officers caught speeding or violating other
traffic laws will have to have a good explanation or face
disciplinary action.
   Chief John Gordon of the patrol and traffic division said the
program has been used periodically over the past 10 years.
   ``We know police cars speed. If you're lying on the street
bleeding and waiting for an officer, you would want the officer to
speed,'' Gordon said. But he acknowledged that some speeding is
done without need.
   McMillan said he's after those who speed while on routine patrol.
   Gordon said offending officers will not get traffic citations,
but the discipline they receive may be more severe than a fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
