<FIRST>r a PM-RadcliffePresident     06-01 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Radcliffe President,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientist Will Be Next President of Radcliffe College</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Linda S. Wilson, a chemist and vice
president for research at the University of Michigan at Ann Arbor,
has been named the seventh president of Radcliffe College.
   Ms. Wilson, 52, takes over from Matina Horner, who steps down at
the end of this month after 17 years as president. Horner, 49, a
research psychologist, said she will take a sabbatical before
deciding what to do next.
   Ms. Wilson said she plans to concentrate on improving
undergraduate life, stressing the school's role in public policy
and focusing on its research.
   ``My challenge will be to develop effective strategies to
multiply (Radcliffe's) impact and to sustain its deep meaning for
the lives of women,'' Ms. Wilson said at a news conference
Wednesday.
   She offered no specifics when asked how she would make Radcliffe
stand apart from Harvard. Radcliff, a women's college, was founded
in 1879 as an annex of Harvard College but has moved in to become
half of Harvard.
   The two colleges' admissions offices merged in 1975. In 1988,
women comprised 41 percent of Harvard's 6,525 undergraduates.
   Before taking her position at the University of Michigan in
1985, Ms. Wilson was an administrator at the University of Illinois
in Champaign-Urbana.
   She was on the faculty at the University of Maryland and the
University of Missouri-St. Louis and has been a consultant to an
advisory panel to the National Institutes of Health and served as
an adviser to the National Science Foundation.
</TEXT>
