<FIRST>r a PM-CisnerosDeparture     06-01 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cisneros Departure,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Antonio Mayor Cisneros Leaves Public Life Quietly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Cockrell swearing-in to occur during meeting that begins at
2 p.m. EDT. No PMs lead planned.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Henry Cisneros quietly leaves City Hall
today after eight years, and admirers say that despite personal
problems that led him not to seek re-election, he won't stay in
private life forever.
   ``One way or another, he'll be back,'' said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
D-Texas. ``And we'll be the better for it.''
   Cisneros, 41, declined to seek a fifth two-year term after being
beset by highly publicized marital problems and the illness of his
son, now nearly 2. He plans to join a financial company in San
Antonio.
   ``I don't expect to try to remain a force in city government or
city politics,'' Cisneros said. ``I don't think you can be halfway
in or halfway out. You're either in or you're out, and I'm going on
to other things.''
   Cisneros cleaned out his office Wednesday, and his successor,
Lila Cockrell, was to be sworn in during an afternoon city council
meeting.
   The Ivy League-educated Cisneros has been one of the nation's
most visible Hispanic leaders and was at one time mentioned as a
potential Democratic vice presidential candidate in 1984.
   During his eight years as mayor, his city has grown to a
population of more than 900,000, making it the ninth largest in the
United States.
   Cisneros' latest victory as mayor was voter approval in January
of a public transportation tax to fund construction of the
Alamodome stadium, which he strongly supported. He has also been
credited with boosting tourism and helping bridge the gap between
the white business establishment and poor Hispanics.
   Though he has ruled out any early run for another office,
Cisneros has left his options open for the long run. In an
interview last fall after he announced he would not seek
re-election, he said he would concentrate on ``reading, reflecting
and writing'' in order to develop ``new and better ways to build
the future.''
   He said that at heart he is ``a public service-oriented person.''
   More recently, he said that he has ``no plan, no timetable, no
deadline, no office in mind'' for his political future.
   Cisneros' successor, Ms. Cockrell, was also his predecessor. She
served as mayor from 1975 to 1981 before deciding not to seek
another term. Now 67, she was elected to the mayor's office again
last month, beating six other candidates.
</TEXT>
