<FIRST>r a PM-Anti-SleepOrdinance     06-01 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anti-Sleep Ordinance,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Challenges Town's Anti-Sleeping Ordinance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union said
today it has asked a federal court to overturn a resort community's
ordinance prohibiting sleeping overnight in cars or on the beach.
   ``I liken it to a Southern speed trap. These people come into
town and innocently get caught doing something they didn't know was
illegal,'' said Steven Brown, executive director of the ACLU's
Rhode Island chapter.
   ``Vagrancy ordinances have routinely been struck down by the
courts as unconstitutional,'' he added.
   He said the lawsuit challenging the ordinance in Westerly was
filed in U.S. District Court on behalf of two Connecticut men who
were arrested last year, one for sleeping in his car at a beach
parking lot. The men paid the $20 fine to avoid a weekend in jail
and then complained to the ACLU, Brown said.
   The ACLU has received complaints over the years about the
ordinance, but an influx of complaints last year made the
organization decide to challenge the law, he said.
   Many of those arrested are young people who come to the beaches
for the day and cannot find motel rooms, so they choose to rest
before driving home, he said.
   ``These people are actually being safety conscious,'' he said.
   Westerly Police Chief Mark S. Champlin said about 300 people
were arrested during the summer for violating the ordinance.
   ``It certainly curbs our problems with break-ins and
vandalism,'' Champlin said. ``If we didn`t have the ordinance I`m
sure we would have chaos in the beach area.''
   ``I think it's a very strange assertion that waking people up
from sleep at 3 o'clock in the morning is a way to protect the town
from chaos,'' Brown said. ``This has nothing to do with protecting
order. It has to do with harassing tourists that get caught up in
this trap.''
   Town Solicitor Maureen Goldberg was not available for comment,
and no one else could say how long the ordinance had been on the
books, a secretary said.
   The ACLU challenged the ordinance as overbroad and vague and
said it improperly criminalized innocent conduct and was aimed at
out-of-state tourists.
   The ordinance prohibits sleeping in cars or outdoors anywhere at
night, including private property, except for people using trailers
at licensed campgrounds.
</TEXT>
