<FIRST>r i PM-US-CambodiaArms     06-01 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cambodia Arms,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Criticizes Reported U.S. Cambodian Arms Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's civil war will be prolonged
if the United States supplies arms to non-communist guerrillas in
the nation, Vietnam's state radio said today.
   A report in The New York Times on Wednesday said President Bush
is seeking congressional support for a covert program to provide
weapons to non-communist rebels fighting the Vietnamese-backed
government in Cambodia.
   ``This only stimulates a civil war ... prolongs the dispute and
runs counter to the common trend for an early peaceful settlement
to the Cambodian issue,'' Voice of Vietnam radio said.
   The radio said such a plan would go against agreements reached
during informal peace talks held in Indonesia between resistance
leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Premier Hun Sen of Cambodia.
   The Cambodian resistance is made up of Prince Sihanouk's forces,
the Khmer People's National Liberation Front and the communist
Khmer Rouge.
   Led by Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge ran Cambodia from 1975 through
1978, during which 1 million Cambodians died.
   The government was ousted by the Vietnamese invasion, but the
Khmer Rouge remains the strongest resistance faction with about
30,000 troops, according to U.S. Embassy estimates.
   Vietnam still maintains a military force in Cambodia but has
promised to withdraw all of its troops by Sept. 30.
   The Times quoted an unidentified State Department official as
saying arms supplies would help the non-communist forces hold their
own if the Khmer Rouge tried to seize control of Cambodia in the
future. State Department spokesman Richard Boucher on Wednesday
would neither confirm nor deny the report.
   He said in Washington that ``appropriate assistance'' would
strengthen the non-communist resistance and ``enhance its position
and that of Prince Sihanouk'' in his efforts to oust the
Vietnamese-backed government.
   The Bush administration was ``unalterably opposed'' to a return
to power by the Khmer Rouge, he said.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, recently wrote to Bush opposing lethal aid to
Sihanouk on the ground that it might fall into the hands of the
Khmer Rouge.
   China is the major supplier of weapons to all three resistance
groups.
   France will host an international conference on the future of
Cambodia in early August, a few weeks before Vietnam is scheduled
to withdraw its troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
