<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Paschal     06-01 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Paschal,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventor of Airwick Air Freshener</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ONECO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guy Sherman Paschal, a prolific inventor who
developed the Airwick air freshener and produced a wide variety of
other products, has died at the age of 87.
   He died of a stroke Sunday night at his home in Oneco.
   Paschal founded AirKem Co. in 1940 to market the Airwick product
developed primarily in his New York City basement as an industrial
disinfectant.
   ``We knew something was going on in the basement. We didn't know
quite what,'' said his son, Guy Paschal, of Purchase, N.Y.
   Paschal was president of the company until he moved to Florida
in 1943 and remained vice president for research and development
until 1951. The right to produce Airwick was franchised in the
early 1960s, and its products now are marketed by Airwick
Industries of Carlstadt, N.J.
   Paschal also developed a three-dimensional chess game
distributed by the Red Cross to military hospitals, an automatic
hen feeder for laying cages, a full line of food flavorings, a
low-calorie sweetener, an oven cleaner and a portable toilet, among
other things.
   He wrote a column for the Sarasota Herald-Tribune from 1961 to
1973 and hosted television and radio talk shows.
   He was survived by his wife, Melanie, a son, daughter, 10
grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
