<FIRST>r w PM-SpendingBill 1stLd-Writethru a0459 06-01 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate $3.3 Billion Spending Bill Would Drop Drug Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 5 grafs new with vote on drug amendment, picks up 3rd graf
pvs, At the.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate rejected an attempt today to
provide more money to increase federal prison space for drug
offenders as lawmkers debated a $3.3 billion domestic spending bill
and edged toward a confrontation with the House.
   On a 77-18 vote, the Senate turned down an amendment that would
have shifted $70 million from the Defense Department's drug
interdiction programs to monies used to increase space in federal
prisons.
   ``Prisons are in a deplorable condition today,'' said Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., who argued that the Pentagon was not going to spend
the money.
   But he was overcome by opponents who argued that the Defense
Department in fact planned to use the funds.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee gave unanimous approval
Wednesday to the overall measure, which includes $1.2 billion for
an assortment of veterans programs that are running short of funds,
including health care and cost-of-living increases in benefits.
   At the same time, the panel decided to remove $822 million that
the House had inserted for extra law enforcement agents, more
prisons, expanded counseling programs and a host of other efforts
aimed at illegal drug trafficking.
   The panel also rebuffed Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., who
proposed an amendment to provided $228 million for anti-drug
initiatives by transferring the money from Pentagon accounts.
   ``We told the American people we were going to be serious,''
DeConcini said of recent measures laying out federal drug
strategies without paying fully for them. ``We're a long way from
meeting that commitment.''
   But the panel voted against DeConcini 24-5, bowing to arguments
that President Bush might veto the bill if it included the
anti-drug funds.
   ``I don't want to see the committee do something here that puts
this bill in jeopardy,'' committee Chairman Robert Byrd told his
colleagues. Byrd had a private reason to avoid a veto.
   The Senate committee's bill includes $75 million for a 300-foot
radiotelescope that collapsed last November in his home state of
West Virginia. It also contains $6.6 million in subsidies for
airlines serving small communities, a provision favored both by
Byrd and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine.
   The bill includes $7.3 million for federal cleanup efforts in
Prince William Sound, Alaska, and orders the government to bill
Exxon for Coast Guard expenses in dealing with the March oil spill.
Both measures reflect membership on the appropriations panel of
Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska.
   When the House passed its version of the bill on a party-line
227-197 vote last Wednesday, GOP lawmakers supported Bush
administration arguments that the drug spending would boost this
year's deficit and could wait until 1990. Democrats reveled in
forcing Republicans to vote against tougher efforts against drugs.
   Like the House measure, the Senate bill provides $892 million
for the Guaranteed Student Loan program for college students; $423
million for state foster care programs; $342 million for the costs
of battling last summer's forest fires; $125 million for United
Nations peacekeeping operations; and $100 million for refugees from
the Soviet Union and elsewhere.
   Besides removing the anti-drug spending, the Senate measure
makes several other changes in the House legislation.
   It provides $225 million for the food stamp program, which has
had a heavier than expected caseload this year. The House bill
included no money for the program.
   It drops $127 million the House provided to $91 million for
workers whose jobs are lost because of foreign competition; reduces
the House's $88 million to $8.2 million for public housing
assistance; and removes $15 million the House provided for aid to
the homeless.
   The Senate measure provides $19 million, not financed by the
House, for the costs of keeping a weather satellite aloft.
   The Senate bill also eliminate a House provision allowing the
brewers of Rolling Rock beer a temporary exemption from a law
requiring a warning label on alcoholic beverage containers. The
beer is made in glass bottles with painted labels, and its producer
says it will take time to retool the labeling machines.
</TEXT>
