<FIRST>u w PM-PentagonExpansion     06-01 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon Expansion,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0594 to restore slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Drops Plans to Build Annex to Pentagon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has dropped plans to build a
$500 million annex to the Pentagon, according to Defense Department
officials.
   ``There is no current planning being considered on the Pentagon
annex,'' said Kenneth H. Evans, a member of a Defense Department
group being formed to oversee planning for the department's
facilities in the Washington area. Plans for an annex ``are being
held in abeyance,'' he said.
   Instead, the department plans to concentrate on renovating the
Pentagon, expanding Army facilities at Fort Belvoir, Va., and
consolidating and possibly relocating Navy offices currently in the
Crystal City section of Arlington, Va., he said.
   Evans spoke Wednesday to a group of local, regional and federal
officials at a meeting to review federal building projects in the
Washington area.
   After the meeting Evans declined to comment on whether budget
constraints or political opposition had helped scuttle plans for
the annex.
   Plans originally called for a 3-million-square-foot facility on
the Pentagon's south parking lot. The proposal met with strong
opposition from Arlington officials who said the county does not
have the road or utility infrastructure to support a complex of
that size. The Pentagon has about 3.7 million square feet of office
space.
   The size of the proposed annex was scaled back last year, to
about 1.8 million square feet. At that time officials said a study
of Defense Department needs was being considered by Congress. But a
master plan on the annex was proceeding.
   Now, even the master plan has been dropped. ``We are restudying
Pentagon development,'' said Linda Eastman, chief facilities
planner for the General Services Administration's national capital
region office.
</TEXT>
