<FIRST>r a PM-PoisonedBaby 2ndLd-Writethru a0613 06-01 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poisoned Baby, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0613,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Charged with Murdering Infant in Alleged Product Liability
Scam</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT judge's name to Hartel, sted Hertel.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH CHICAGO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple were arrested and charged
with murder for allegedly forcing their infant son to drink
sulfuric acid, and then claiming he was the victim of contaminated
baby formula.
   Shelia Smith, 26, and Ricky Irby Sr., 29, both of North Chicago,
were arrested Wednesday on murder charges, and prosecutors said
they will seek the death penalty.
   They were ordered held in lieu of $1 million bond each after a
brief hearing today in Lake County Circuit Court. Associate Judge
Harry Hartel set another hearing for Wednesday.
   The arrests and indictments came exactly five years after the
couple's 3-month-old son, Quinten Irby, was poisoned.
   The child lingered near death for more than two years with
severe burn scars on his mouth and trachea. He also had one lung
removed and was kept alive on a ventilator.
   ``He was unable to swallow, to breathe or to speak,'' said
Matthew Chancey, an assistant Lake County state's attorney.
   Quinten died at Children's Memorial Hospital in Chicago on Aug.
26, 1986, when he was 2{.
   Investigators believe the parents forced sulfuric acid down the
infant's throat on May 31, 1984, and then claimed he was poisoned
by contaminated baby formula.
   Irby filed a lawsuit in August 1987, charging negligence against
the baby formula maker, Abbott Laboratories of North Chicago, and
the grocery store where the formula was allegedly bought.
   The lawsuit claimed that the Similac with Iron formula the
couple gave to Quinten contained a ``foreign and dangerous acidic
and@or lye substance'' and was ``unfit for human consumption.''
   Irby withdrew the lawsuit a year ago.
   Investigators said they were suspicious of the parents early in
the case. Tests on the contents of Quinten's stomach found it to
contain high concentrations of a substance believed to be pure
sulfuric acid.
   But prosecutors were stymied when evidence that was in the
custody of the Illinois Department of Public Health was lost.
Chancey said this included an opened can of baby formula the
parents claimed was contaminated, an unopened can of formula, a
bottle and nipple, and a pair of pants that Irby claimed were
damaged by the contaminated formula.
   A break for prosecutors came last November when the U.S. Supreme
Court, in an Arizona case, ruled that accidentally lost evidence
does not preclude prosecution.
   ``After that decision came down, we decided to take another look
at this case,'' said Chancey. ``This is the type of case that never
leaves your mind.''
   A Lake County grand jury returned the murder charges Wednesday
following several weeks of testimony.
   Chancey said the state will seek the death penalty against Smith
and Irby because the boy was younger than 12 and the crime, under
Illinois statutes, ``was particularly brutal and heinous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
