<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0564 06-01 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0564,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Issues Computerized ID Cards in Gaza as Shamir Talks Tough</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 9th pvs, ``An army...'' to UPDATE with
marches by right-wing groups. Pickup 10th, ``The bank...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army began issuing computerized plastic
identity cards today to Palestinians in the occupied Gaza Strip as
part of a campaign to tighten control over the Arab population.
   The move coincided with a demand by Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir that the army adopt harsher measures to crush the nearly
18-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israel's occupation of
the Gaza Strip and West Bank.
   Shamir's spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir, confirmed reports that the
prime minister wants a tougher approach. ``If current measures are
not enough, we have to consider other measures,'' said Ahimeir.
   At least 10 Palestinians, most of them teen-agers, were wounded
today in clashes with troops in the occcupied lands, Arab hospital
officials said.
   Since the uprising began in December 1987, at least 503
Palestinians have been killed, most of them by army gunfire.
Twenty-two Israelis have also died in the violence.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, five Palestinians were shot and
wounded when soldiers broke up a protest march by about 200
chidlren. Troops chased marchers into the city's narrow alleyways,
Arab reports said.
   The protesters carried outlawed Palestinian flags and banners
reading: ``No alternative but the Palestinian state,'' the reports
said.
   In the Gaza Strip, five Palestinians were reported shot and
wounded in clashes with soldiers.
   An army official confirmed that five Palestinians were wounded
in Nablus in what he described as clashes with stone-throwers. He
said he was checking reports of five wounded in Gaza.
   Meanwhile, Jewish extremists waving Israeli flags and singing
Hebrew songs marched through Jerusalem's Arab sector under heavy
police guard today to mark the 22nd anniversary of Israel's capture
of the area in the six-day war.
   At one point in the march through the walled Old City, police
fired tear gas at Arab youths after stones and a bottle were
dropped from a rooftop, causing no injuries. Some of the marchers
had pistols tucked into their belts.
   Hundreds of Palestinians watched the procession silently. One
Arab woman shouted ``Salam,'' or ``peace,'' to a Jewish woman, who
responded with: ``Get out of here. This is our country.''
   The Bank of Israel, meanwhile, said the uprising cost Israel
$630 million in export losses last year, including $280 million in
lost tourism.
   The Jerusalem Post newspaper quoted the bank's governor, Michael
Bruno, as saying the uprising slowed economic growth and created a
climate of uncertainty that deterred foreign investment.
   Also today, Israel rejected charges by the human rights group
Amnesty International that the army violated the rights of
non-violent opponents of the occupation who are being detained
without trial in administrative detention.
   More than 1,000 Palestinians are being detained without charges.
   ``People are being held because of violent activities, not
because of their ideas,'' said a Shamir aide, Avi Pazner. ``Israel
does not use administrative detention lightly.''
   In the Gaza Strip, the army launched a campaign today to
restrict the entry of Palestinians to Israel.
   Palestinians wishing to enter Israel must apply for plastic
cards with a magnetic strip ``like the one you use in a bank,''
said a senior military official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He would not confirm or deny Israeli media reports the cards
would be run through a computer whenever Palestinians pass army
checkpoints separating Gaza and Israel.
   Palestinians convicted of ``serious security or criminal
offenses'' will be denied the computerized identity cards, the
military official said. He said he expected about 1,500 Gaza
residents would be refused them.
   Women and children under the age 16 are exempt from the new
requirement and can continue to enter Israel with their old
Israeli-issued identity cards, the official said.
   He said he expected 70,000 to 80,000 Gazans to apply for the new
cards, mainly so they can keep their jobs in Israel. At least
50,000 Gazans work in Israel.
   The cards are part of an army effort to ``improve our ability to
supervise and control entry from Gaza into Israel,'' the official
said, adding that similar cards might be introduced in the West
Bank.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin has said such restrictions are
intended to persuade Palestinians to accept Israel's peace plan,
which calls for elections in the occupied lands. The Palestine
Liberation Organization has rejected the plan because it does not
provide for eventual statehood.
   The Jewish West Bank settlement of Ariel has amended a decision
to issue tags reading ``alien worker'' to Arabs working in the
community of 8,000.
   The introduction of the tags led to charges of racism, and
raised comparisons with the yellow Star of David that Jews were
forced to wear in Nazi Germany.Under new regulations, all visitors
to Ariel, including Jews, must wear the tags, said Dorit Shalit, a
city employee.
</TEXT>
