<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Arrest     06-01 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Arrest,0449</SECOND>
<UNK>Police Arrest Leader of British Embassy Sit-In</UNK>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black labor leader who
encamped at the British Embassy in March to protest police
restrictions was arrested today for violating them, authorities
said.
   Donsie Khumalo, a regional official of the Congress of South
African Trade Unions, was one of six black activists who staged a
26-hour sit-in at the embassy on March 29-30 to protest
restrictions placed on them after they were released from detention.
   In the course of the sit-in, police said, Khumalo violated the
restrictions, which require him to report twice daily to police,
confine him to his home at night and limit his political activities.
   Similar restrictions have been placed on hundreds of detainees
released in recent months after being held without charge under
state-of-emergency regulations.
   Khumalo was released a week before the sit-in after joining a
widespread hunger strike. He and the other activists were
embittered by the British Embassy's refusal to let them stay inside
the building or use its toilets and telephones.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, the largest and one
of the most militantly anti-apartheid labor federations in the
country, issued a statement demanding Khumalo's release. It said he
was taken to court today and ordered held without bail until a
court appearance on Aug. 30.
   Government officials have indicated that the state of emergency,
declared on June 12, 1986, will be renewed next week for a fourth
year.
   The labor federation demanded that the emergency be lifted and
denounced the restrictions as ``cruel persecution ... of people who
have spent months, sometimes years in detention.''
   It also said it planned a three-day protest starting on Monday
in the southeastern city of Pietermaritzburg. The labor federation
said police there have failed to stop factional violence between
federation allies and followers of Inkatha, a more conservative
Zulu political organization.
   Emergency regulations prohibit general strikes, but most
protests organized by anti-apartheid groups in recent years have
consisted of supporters not going to work or school.
   The labor federation said it decided to stage the protest after
the death early today of Jabu Ndlovu, a shop steward for a
metalworkers' union whose house was attacked and burned on May 21.
   Mrs. Ndlovu's husband and one of her daughters were killed in
the attack, and she had been hospitalized since then for treatment
of burns.
   Her home was burned after she complained at a news conference
about allegations of collaboration between Inkatha and police.
   Police have said they take no sides in the conflict, which has
claimed nearly 2,000 lives in Natal Province since late 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
