<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Justice-Leaks 1stLd-Writethru a0460 06-01 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Justice-Leaks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Prosecutor Looking Into News Leaks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New throughout with more details of leaks investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A career federal prosecutor is assigned to
investigate news leaks that the FBI is investigating allegations
against a half-dozen prominent Democratic officeholders, the
Justice Department said today.
   The career Justice Department prosecutor will conduct
interviews, take sworn statements and could seek polygraph
examinations to determine who is responsible for the unauthorized
disclosures of information, spokesman David Runkel said today.
   ``If we knew who the leakers were today, clearly it would be the
attorney general's intention to dismiss them,'' Runkel said. Such
leaks are against Justice Department policy and may also violate
federal law, he said.
   At least two FBI agents have also been assigned to the
investigation to conduct interviews, Runkel said, adding that it
would be ``premature to say'' where the investigation would lead.
   Runkel said the career government prosecutor from the
department's criminal division, whom he declined to identify, would
investigate leaks leading to stories about investigations or
preliminary inquires involving Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas; Reps.
Tony Coehlo, D-Calif.; William H. Gray III, D-Pa.; Gus Savage,
D-Ill.; Walter Fauntroy, D-D.C., and Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh first ordered the investigation
last week following a story in the Los Angeles Times that the FBI
was conducting a preliminary inquiry of investments by Bradley and
Coehlo, the House majority whip who announced his resignation
Friday.
   Stories this week that the FBI was conducting preliminary
inquiries of allegations involving Wright and Gray, the
fourth-ranking House Democrat, prompted charges from House
Democrats that the Republican-run Justice Department was
responsible for politically inspired leaks.
   Leaks leading to stories that the Justice Department was
investigating allegations that Fauntroy, the District of Columbia's
non-voting delegate, hired Savage's son for a non-show job are also
part of the investigation, Runkel said.
   Runkel denied the suggestion that the leaks were coming from top
officials on Thornburgh's staff, saying: ``I don't believe that's
the case, based on people I've talked with.''
   But the chairman of the House Judiciary Committee and two top
Democrats on the panel charged that the leaks were politically
inspired.
   ``It appears to us from these articles that persons in the
Department of Justice are using leaks for political purposes
against House Democrats,'' said the letter from Chairman Jack
Brooks, D-Texas and Reps. Don Edwards, D-Calif. and Robert W.
Kastenmeier, D-Wisc.
   ``Nothing could be more destructive of the criminal justice
process and run a greater risk of hampering the work of the
department's career criminal investigators than the appearance that
information about the existence of investigation is being used for
political advantage,'' the letter said.
   In a separate letter to Thornburgh, Gray, who is seeking the
post of majority whip being vacated by Coehlo, questioned why the
Justice Department waited ``until the eve of Democratic leadership
changes'' to send FBI agents to his home on Memorial Day. The
agents told Gray they were investigating at least one of his
employees.
   Jon Plebani, Gray's staff director, said Wednesday: ``Every
employee who works for Bill Gray comes to work and does work. He's
a very demanding boss.''
   The Justice Department, responding to Gray's complaint, said
Wednesday that Thornburgh had ordered an investigation of leaks
over the past week.
   In their letter, Brooks, Edwards and Kastenmeier told Thornburgh
that ``unless you take clear and aggressive steps to stop these
leaks we will have to conclude that they have your support.''
   Rep. David E. Bonior, D-Mich., who is one of Gray's opponents in
the race to succeed Coelho as whip, also chastised the Justice
Department.
   ``The American people are fed up with the effort to use
innuendos and rumors to discredit our public officials,'' Bonior
said. ``We must stop this destructive politics of character
assassination.''
   On Wednesday, Runkel described Thornburgh as ``disturbed by
leaks that have come out of the department concerning matters which
have led to news stories on members of Congress.''
   ``If there is some attempted interference here in the actions of
the House Democratic Caucus it is of concern to us,'' Runkel said.
</TEXT>
