<FIRST>r i PM-MineDisaster 1stLead-Writethru a0514 06-01 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Disaster, 1st Lead-Writethru, a0514,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Dead, At Least 21 Missing In Mine Disaster</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE death toll and number missing, CORRECT
that only 165 homes burned. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landslide caused by heavy rains
collapsed tunnels of a gold mine and started a fire in a remote
mining region. Authorities said at least 11 people were killed and
21 trapped in the mine.
   Officials said at least nine other people were injured and 165
homes were destroyed in the blaze that followed Tuesday's disaster
in the mining town of Mount Diwalwal, 580 miles southeast of
Manila, officials said. Earlier, officials reported that 180 homes
burned.
   Mario Luis Jacinto, regional director of the Bureau of Mines,
said at least 535 prospectors escaped before 13 of the 27 tunnels
in the mine collapsed. He said 21 miners were believed missing.
   But Crispina Abat of the Civil Defense said there were no
reliable figures on the number of people in the mine at the time.
She said there was confusion over the numbers of missing.
   Two miners were killed by falling timber and two others
suffocated in a nearby shaft, Jacinto said. He said three trapped
workers located Tuesday were also presumed dead after rescuers
failed to contact them Thursday.
   The landslide also caused a charcoal pit in a blacksmith shop to
tumble and ignited a three-hour fire in a nearby housing area that
burned 165 shanties. The fire killed four people and injured nine,
Jacinto added.
   Mining officials declared the tunnels danger zones in July but
gold prospectors ignored the advice, according to Lt. Col. Nelson
Estares, a local police chief.
   Jacinto said the rains had loosened soil in the area, causing
the landslide. ``Rescue operations are being hampered by ground
movements still occurring in the area,'' he said. The heavy rains
continued, he said.
   Jacinto said miners reported seeing cracks on the walls of the
shafts five and a half hours before the collapse and had time to
leave the tunnels.
   ``Most of the workers came out, but there were others who were
hardheaded and refused to leave,'' Jacinto said.
   The Diwalwal mining area has occasionally been hit by cave-ins,
but most went unreported because miners fear the government will
halt operations there.
</TEXT>
