<FIRST>r i AM-Khomeini     06-01 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khomeini,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khomeini Leaves Hospital Bed For An Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, recovering
from surgery to stop intestinal bleeding, was allowed out of his
Tehran hospital bed for an hour Thursday, Tehran radio reported.
   The 86-year-old revolutionary leader also was permitted to go
outside in an open area around the hospital, according to the
report on the state-run radio.
   He met with relatives and close friends while he was outside and
performed his midday prayers there, the radio reported.
   It did not say whether he was in a wheelchair or walked when he
was allowed out of bed for the first time since he underwent
surgery May 23 after doctors discovered internal bleeding in his
digestive tract.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Khomeini's medical team
as saying that his ``general condition is very satisfactory, and we
expect quick and complete recuperation.''
   Tehran Television reported Khomeini suffered a ``slight heart
complication'' Saturday. It gave no details, but said the condition
had been ``relieved'' by Sunday.
   Iran's main opposition group, the Iraq-based Mujahedeen Khalq,
or People's Holy Warriors, said Khomeini had suffered a heart
attack after the operation. The claim could not be independently
confirmed.
   Iranian TV on Monday broadcast footage it said was taken after
surgery, showing Khomeini in his hospital bed being coaxed by two
relatives to eat a few spoonfuls of soup, while his grandson
scampered about the room and his 43-year-old son, Ahmad, sat nearby.
   Khomeini's personal physician said the revolutionary patriarch
was in excellent condition and was one of ``history's exceptions.''
Khomeini has been reported ailing since he suffered a heart attack
in 1986. Since then he has rarely been seen outside his home in the
north Tehran suburb of Jamaran.
</TEXT>
