<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Deputy     06-01 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Deputy,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Progressive Deputy Meets The People</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri N. Afanasyev, Moscow historian and
progressive communist, is learning what it means to be a People's
Deputy.
   Arriving at the new Soviet parliament with a mandate won in the
first contested elections in 70 years, Afanasyev has used national
TV to bring the concerns of progressives to millions.
   During breaks in debate at the Congress of People's Deputies, he
rushes from the Kremlin to meet voters and students eager to know
what is going on in the corridors and cloakrooms not shown on
television.
   Hundreds of Muscovites jammed into a sweltering, decrepit
lecture hall Wednesday to hear Afanasyev field questions for an
hour about the work of a Congress that has riveted the nation.
   Already well-known in Moscow and to progressive intellectuals
across the country for his activities with Memorial, a group formed
to chronicle Josef Stalin's purges and remember their victims,
Afanasyev shot to national fame when he took the Congress floor
Saturday.
   A professor rather than a politician, he offered no political
program. But in less than 10 minutes, he delivered a speech that
captured the widespread sense of disappointment with the Congress'
election of deputies to its new legislature, the Supreme Soviet.
   He said an ``aggressively obedient majority'' in the parliament
had elected a ``Brezhnev-Stalin Supreme Soviet.'' The phrases
instantly entered the popular lexicon, recurring time and again in
heated discussions of the Congress around Moscow.
   ``His speech was the turning point of the Congress,'' said one
Moscow mathematician.
   On Wednesday, Afanasyev indicated that even many of his fellow
progressives had been offended by his description of the new
legislature.
   But he was still forthright in voicing many radical demands,
winning his strongest round of applause from the audience when he
said, ``Of course this Congress should take power into its hands''
and ``release the party from its right to make powerful decisions.''
   The party's ruling Politburo and Central Committee should
continue to decide party matters, he added swiftly, but ``powerful
decisions should be taken by the Congress.''
   Afanasyev, a ruddy-faced man in his 50s, told the crowd at the
history institute where he is rector that he was surprised to
receive support for his views when he met voters in Noginsk, about
25 miles east of Moscow, on Sunday, when the Congress was not in
session.
   The voters were more enthusiastic about getting the Congress to
change the political structure than in its solving day-to-day
consumer problems, he said.
   Afanasyev, a member of a group of progressive Moscow deputies,
said the fledgling organization is slowly gaining support from
deputies representing other areas of the country.
   Despite his harsh remarks, he remains devoted to th work of the
Congress.
   ``The Soviet people pinned so many hopes _ all their hopes, the
future of their children _ on this Congress,'' Afanasyev said.
``This is the body of deputies we must trust'' to change the
country.
</TEXT>
