<FIRST>r a PM-BridgeCollapse     06-01 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underwater Search Begins For Victims of Bridge Collapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police divers today began searching the Great
Miami River for victims and clues to last week's bridge collapse
that killed up to five people.
   Only one diver would go down at a time and would stay only about
one minute because of concerns about the river's strong current and
low visibility, said Frank Weikel, a spokesman for the Hamilton
County Sheriff's Department.
   Authorities believe that as many as five people died in the
rain-swollen river after two vehicles fell in when a temporary
bridge over U.S. 52 collapsed during rush-hour Friday.
   Just one victim has been found so far. Authorities today
identified a woman's body that was found Tuesday, about five miles
downriver, as that of a 52-year-old suburban Cincinnati woman. The
woman's daughter is among the missing.
   One police diver made several exploratory plunges into the river
Wednesday at the site, 12 miles west of Cincinnati at Miamitown.
Investigators hope the divers can help find the remaining victims
and clues to why it fell.
   National Transportation Safety Board personnel investigating the
collapse are especially interested in obtaining the steel bridge
support that failed, said Jean Fasone, head of the NTSB
investigative team.
   She said that pressure from Miamitown merchants, who feared
losses when an aging bridge that is being replaced was closed,
prompted the county to select a time-saving design for a one-lane
temporary bridge. The temporary bridge opened in December and was
scheduled to be in use for about a year.
   Engineers have suggested that the strong current from the
flooded river, plus the pounding from tree trunks and other debris,
prompted the collapse. But a full-scale engineering investigation
has been postponed until the river's level drops.
   Ms. Fasone said her team probably will be on site through this
weekend, but won't have its report completed for about six months,
she said.
</TEXT>
