<DOCNO> AP890601-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     06-01 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Gets Polite Reception at Start of Scandinavian Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lutherans in this nation of only 27,800
Catholics welcomed Pope John Paul II politely Thursday as he began
a tour of Scandinavia, where the Protestant Reformation vanquished
Rome four centuries ago.
   He described himself as a brother and friend in making the first
visit by a pope to the overwhelmingly Lutheran region. Sparse
crowds and reservations voiced in some quarters were expected to
make it one of the most unusual of his 42 foreign tours.
   John Paul arrived from Rome on a cloudy Nordic spring day that
later turned rainy. Awaiting him at the airport were a few
well-wishers and a line of dignitaries led by Prime Minister Gro
Harlem Brundtland.
   The pope gave assurances of his intentions and emphasized that
Norway's 1,000-year-old Christian tradition was common ground in a
region that outlawed Catholicism until the last century.
   ``Standing here on Norwegian soil, I am fully conscious of the
special significance of this occasion,'' he said, speaking in
English. ``For the first time ever, a bishop of Rome, a succcesor
of the Apostle Peter, has come to Norway and to the Nordic
countries.
   ``I come, not as the representative of a political or national
interest, but as a witness of the Gospel and of our Lord Savior
Jesus Christ, as a brother deeply concerned with the well-being of
his brothers and sisters in every part of the world.
   ``I come to Norway as a friend, full of esteem and love for its
noble people and its millenary Christian heritage.''
   Norway is the first stop on a 10-day tour that also includes
Iceland, Finland, Denmark and Sweden. They have only 197,000
Catholics among them, less than 1 percent of the population.
   Vatican officials have said John Paul's aim is to spread a
message of Christian ethics in a highly secular region, boost the
morale of the few Catholics and strengthen relations with the
Lutheran church.
   One of Norway's 11 Lutheran bishops refused to attend any
meeting with the pontiff. The Lutheran church in Denmark has
insisted he not speak at a prayer service in Copenhagen next week.
   Scandinavian attitudes on family and sexual issues differ
sharply from Roman Catholic teaching, which forbids divorce,
abortion and contraception. A leading Oslo newspaper, the tabloid
Dagbladet, published a caricature Thursday depicting John Paul's
miter in the shape of a condom.
   In what Roman Catholic officials described as an unusual gesture
to counter questions about the visit, King Olav V took John Paul to
the balcony of the 19th century royal palace to greet about 1,000
people. Usually the king takes only royal guests with him for such
appearances.
   The crowd applauded politely and children waved red and white
flags of John Paul's native Poland.
   ``Welcome to Norway. I am extremely glad to see you in our
country,'' the king said when John Paul arrived for a 30-minute
audience.
   Later, the pope celebrated Mass in a drizzle on the parade
ground of a 14th century fortress. State-run TV estimated the crowd
at 10,000-12,000, including Polish refugees who raised Solidarity
banners.
   In his homily, John Paul said the purpose of his visit was to
``encourage a serious reflection on the flight from God and from
higher moral values which is typical of secularized society.''
   He was fully aware of the resistance to his visit by some
Lutherans.
   ``The church and I personally are undertaking an ecumenical
meeting,'' he told reporters on the flight from Rome. ``Certainly,
not all the the Lutheran bishops share this ecumenical path, as,
sometimes, some Catholics also have trouble with it.''
   John Paul is fond of skiing and was asked if he intended to do
any in Scandinavia. He replied:
   ``I've been told that the best solution for ecumenism and for
the rapproachment of the churches would be if the pope, the king of
Sweden or the king of Norway could go skiing together.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Drought     06-01 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Legislation Likely Any Time Soon, Senate Ag Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is not likely to pass drough relief
legislation any time soon, the chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee predicted Thursday.
   ``We have a winter wheat problem,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy,
D-Vt., adding that there was no indication the early spring drought
caused problems with other crops.
   ``I'm very concerned about winter wheat,'' he said. ``But I
don't want to move until we see about present crops.''
   Despite heavy rains in recent days, winter wheat production is
expected to be mostly fair to poor, the Agriculture Department said
this week.
   In Kansas, the wheat looks poor to very poor, the department
said. Harvesting of the crop is under way in California, Georgia,
Oklahoma and Texas, while the wheat is still growing elsewhere.
   Winter wheat is planted in the fall and begins to sprout in
early spring, but shortage of spring rain, particularly in Kansas,
has devastated the crop.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., has introduced legislation that would
extend the 1988 drought relief law to this year's winter wheat
crop, but no further action has been taken on the bill.
   Leahy said he would ask Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter to
brief members of the Agriculture Committee and other senators
interested in drought legislation soon.
   Yeutter, touring Iowa drought areas earlier this week, cautioned
against overreaction. ``We have to be careful we don't overestimate
the problems and respond in a way that just isn't called for under
the circumstances,'' he said.
   ``We don't know that there is a drought,'' Sen. Rudy Boschwitz,
R-Minn., said Wednesday. Both he and Leahy made their comments
after a news conference on an unrelated topic.
   Both senators mentioned the speed at which Congress acted to
pass drought legislation last year and said action should be slower
this time.
   ``We will take appropriate steps, but we won't act
precipitously,'' said Leahy.
   ``I don't anticipate legislation coming up on the agenda right
away,'' he said.
   The House Agriculture Committee last week passed drought
legislation that would extend the 1988 law to many crops besides
winter wheat. The bill has not been voted on by the full House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
