<FIRST>r i AM-BarbaraBush     06-01 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Breaks Into `I'm a Little Teapot'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush chose the appropriate country to
break spontaneously into a rendition of ``I'm a Little Teapot,''
gestures and all.
   Mrs. Bush was inspired by a colorful paper teapot thrust at her
by an eager child during the first lady's only solo appearance in
tea-loving Britain.
   Mrs. Bush visited a day care center as well as classes in
cooking, English-language and fashion design during a 75-minute
visit to the Lambeth Institute's Strand Center, an adult education
school. It is in Brixton, the poor south London area hit by
anti-police riots four years ago.
   ``Do you know it?'' asked Mrs. Bush, as she sang the classic
English nursery rhyme about a teapot, short and stout. The first
lady shaped a spout with her left arm.
   Education Secretary Kenneth Baker, who accompanied Mrs. Bush on
the outing, smiled encouragingly. The 3-year-old children, perhaps
too young, looked bewildered.
   The school's classes, mostly in primary education, attract an
average of 2,000 students per week to courses of varying length.
Some 65 percent come from ``ethnic communities,'' according to the
Education Department.
   ``I am putting my focus in the United States on family
literacy,'' Mrs. Bush said.
   Mrs. Bush called the Strand Center ``a marvelous coalition of
public agencies.''
   In the cooking class, students who hope to become caterers and
chefs were making strudel pastry, noisily slapping mounds of dough
on the counters.
   ``My pie crust is not one you write home about; you know what I
mean,'' Mrs. Bush said as she worked the dough herself. ``I envy
you. This is gorgeous.''
   One fashion student, Icema Paschal, told Mrs. Bush she was
wearing a dress she had made especially for the occasion, and the
first lady complimented her on it.
   Afterward, Ms. Paschal said about the first lady: ``I think
she's quite down to earth, quite nice. She's quite a relaxed
person.''
   Gulshan Ramzan, a special needs tutor, said, ``It was wonderful.
My students, although mentally handicapped, they were so excited.''
   ``I applaud her enormously for coming here,'' said Neil Fletcher
of the Inner London Education Authority. He took the opportunity to
attack the government's plans to abolish the authority, which will
force the center to rely on local government funds.
   Riots broke out in Brixton in September 1985 after a woman was
accidentally shot by a policeman during a raid on her home.
Hundreds of rioters set fire to buildings and looted stores.
</TEXT>
