<FIRST>r w AM-Jenkins-Leadership     06-01 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jenkins-Leadership,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jenkins Battling Gephardt for House Majority Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Richard Gephardt called to inform Ed
Jenkins he had decided to run for House majority leader instead of
seeking the presidency in 1992, the Georgia congressman didn't miss
a beat.
   ``I said I've made the same decisions,'' Jenkins recalled with a
laugh as e discussed his campaign against Gephardt, a Missouri
Democrat, for the job that's expected to come open next week when
Rep. Tom Foley of Washington is elected to replace Jim Wright as
speaker of the House.
   Jenkins, who is serving a seventh term in the House,
acknowledges he cannot match the national reputation Gephardt, who
also is a seven-term congressman, achieved with his 1988 bid for
the Democratic presidential nomination.
   But the secret ballot election of a majority leader by the House
Democratic Caucus is very different from a presidential campaign,
and Jenkins insists he's in the race to win.
   ``A lot of people have written me off in the press, but this is
not a popularity contest,'' he said in an interview Wednesday.
   Jenkins began lining up support last week for an expected
majority leader race against Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the
majority whip. But Coelho's surprise announcement Friday that he
was resigning rather than face an ethics investigation of his
personal finances freed Gephardt to jump into the race.
   ``He wasn't my choice of a person to run against,'' Jenkins said
of Gephardt, who built his presidential campaign largely with the
support of House Democrats. ``But I didn't feel at that time I
could back away. And I feel this thing is doable.''
   While Gephardt quickly lined up commitments from many of the
House Democrats who supported his presidential bid, Jenkins said
he's been pleasantly surprised at the willingness of his Democratic
colleagues to listen to his message.
   ``I really believe that if the Democratic Party wants to
eliminate ... the gradual loss of middle-income people, we've got
to make the leadership broad enough that we have a conservative or
a moderate at the table helping to make policy,'' he said.
   ``I am very good at building coalitions,'' he added. ``If I had
three months on this, regardless of how popular Gephardt is, I
would beat Gephardt.''
   Jenkins' main disadvantage is that he starts with only a small
base of support. There are only 55 Southern Democrats in the
259-member House Democratic Caucus, and Jenkins said he has to hold
that base if he is to have any chance at all.
   But even if he doesn't win, and Jenkins is not willing to
concede that possibility, he said his campaign at the very least
will help open doors for other Southern Democrats in the House.
   ``I might pave the way for somebody to be (House Democratic)
caucus chairman, or I might pave the way for good committee
assignments for other Southerners,'' he said.
   Jenkins said he hopes his campaign will demonstrate that
Southern Democrats are ``no longer sitting back, they want to play
in this game, they want to be a part of the party, they want to
broaden the party, and they insist upon broadening it.
   ``It's no longer going to be a party perceived to be just for
liberals,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
