<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Queen     06-01 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Queen,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Samples Splendor of Palace and Smiles At Queen's Command</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush had lunch with Queen Elizabeth II
on Thursday, sampled the splendor of Buckingham Palace and smiled
for the cameras at her majesty's command.
   The royal event began with a glitch over the delayed opening of
Barbara Bush's car door, but by the time lunch ended 30 minutes
behind schedule there were smiles all around and the queen told the
president: ``I hope to see you again soon.''
   When the presidential limousine pulled up to the palace's
red-carpeted Grand Entrance, Bush jumped out. But nobody opened
Mrs. Bush's door until the queen, frowning and shaking her head,
raised her voice and said: ``Open it.''
   A U.S. Secret Service agent complied immediately and Mrs. Bush,
wearing an emerald green dress, emerged smiling as though nothing
had happened.
   It was the Bushes' first taste of British royal hospitality and
the queen and her husband, Prince Philip, brought out one of
Britain's biggest tourist attractions _ the 2nd Battalion Scots
Guards in their red tunics and bearskin hats.
   The president arrived at Buckingham Palace from talks with Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher at her Downing Street residence.
Escorted by Philip, he inspected a 100-strong honor guard mounted
by the Scots Guards after their band played the U.S. national
anthem.
   ``That was so beautiful,'' Bush told his hosts. ``I have never
heard `The Star-Spangled Banner' being played better.''
   Then he added hastily: ``with all respect to the Marine band.''
   Both couples then went inside, chatting animatedly as they
walked through a few of the palace's 600 rooms on their way to
cocktails with the 30 other luncheon guests.
   Between cocktails and lunch, the Bushes and their royal hosts
slipped out for a quick look at the mainly 17th century Dutch
masterpieces in the palace picture gallery.
   ``It's just us. It's very quiet,'' Bush said in a joking
reference to the cocktail hubbub he left behind.
   As they approached photographers, the queen, wearing a blue and
white striped silk dress, told Bush with a grin: ``Smile.'' He
obeyed.
   Luncheon was served in the ivory and gold Music Room overlooking
the 45-acre palace garden. The magnificent domed room with 18 blue
and gilt columns has been used for many royal christenings
including those of Prince Charles, the heir to the throne, and
Charles' heir, Prince William.
   Flanked by the queen and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Bush
sat down to a meal of smoked salmon mousse, duck with honey and
brandy sauce, broad beans, asparagus and potatoes, artichoke salad
and mango ice cream.
   The three wines included two which the queen served Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his wife Raisa when they lunched
together at Windsor Castle in April. They are an Alsatian white
Gewurztraminer Dopff 1983 and the queen's private port, Royal
Vintage 1955.
   Buckingham Palace said the queen's choice of wines was
``coincidence.''
   The guests included Mrs. Thatcher's husband Denis, Secretary of
State James Baker III, his British counterpart Sir Geoffrey Howe,
Terry Hands, artistic director of the Royal Shakespeare Theater,
and Charles Wilson, editor of The Times of London.
   When former President Reagan went to Buckingham Palace just a
year ago for tea with the queen, a U.S. television reporter shouted
questions to him, breeching accepted behavior at formal royal
occasions.
   To avoid a repetition, reporters at the entrance were made to
stand behind a sound-proof glass screen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ShortTakes Bjt   06-01 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Short Takes, Bjt,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Video Booths Sell Stardom for Mom, Dad and Junior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just plunk down $6 to $10 and step into ``Short
Takes,'' a video version of the old bus station photo booth, then
unleash your talents to produce a job resume, birthday greeting _
even a ``Dear John'' letter.
   ``I bumped into a guy at a party last night. He had just come
back from a visit in Mississippi and instead of a thank-you note,
he sent a video,'' said Bruce Goldstein, 41, a Minneapolis
entrepreneur and real estate developer, who's starting the service.
   The idea for ``Short Takes'' emerged last year, when Goldstein
and his wife, vacationing in Florida, paid $80 to record a birthday
tape instead of flying to Texas for a friend's party.
   Their 7-minute birthday spoof said: ``It's 83 degrees, the sun
is shining and we're on the Atlantic Ocean. You're a great guy,
Gil, but you ain't that great.''
   ``They rented a VCR and played it at the party. It was a
smash,'' said Goldstein.
   A month later, Goldstein read about a man who had designed a
video booth used in a California mall. Goldstein bought the patent
rights, jazzed up the design and went to market as Short Takes Inc.
   ``The pop-up cards they now have can retail from $5 to $9,''
said Goldstein. ``The growth in that specialty greeting card market
is so huge, I was convinced that people would spend $6 to $10
spontaneously'' on a video.
   So far, about 20 booths have been set up in bars, malls and
colleges in Minneapolis, Los Angeles and New York's South Street
Seaport. Goldstein said he's received inquiries about the booths
from around the country.
   ``It's a lot of fun,'' said Karen Munoz, who emerged _ laughing
_ from a Seaport booth with Michelle Davila. ``It's very
embarrassing if you do something stupid, though.''
   The women tried the booth Tuesday, liked it, and came back again
Wednesday.
   The first time was extemporaneous: ``We were busy laughing and
joking,'' said Ms. Munoz. The second time, they read ``news from
New York'' for friends in Virginia.
   Both women said they'd be back. Ms. Davila wants to send one to
her grandmother.
   The price varies, depending on the area. The 10-minute recording
tape, complete with mailer, is either issued by the machine or sold
at a nearby counter. It costs $16,000 for a tape-vending booth;
$14,000 if the tapes are sold separately, such as in a card shop.
   Goldstein's not just president of the company; he also uses the
machines.
   ``The other night, my wife and I sent a 10-minute tape to her
aunt in California. We brought our new baby into the booth with
us,'' said Goldstein. ``I had to put in the eight bucks _ I didn't
even get a discount.''
   Goldstein hopes for a video offspring to be used in maternity
wards. The projected name: ``Babytakes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-TV     06-01 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-TV,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Latest Battleground Between Solidarity, Gov't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Solidarity has plastered Poland with
campaign posters, the union faces tougher competition in promoting
its candidates on state television, where authorities still command
he airwaves.
   Solidarity receives 45 minutes of airtime weekly for its own
program, while the government has been using daily newscasts and
scores of special programs to promote its candidates.
   The union was assured access to state TV under the April 5
accords that legalized it in exchange for opposition support of
Poland's most democratic elections since World War II. The vote
will be held this Sunday.
   Problems with ``Studio Solidarnosc,'' as the opposition's TV
program is called, began almost immediately after Solidarity won
access to the one branch of the mass media where authorities still
had absolute control.
   First, according to Solidarity TV expert Kazimierz Zorowski,
authorities moved the show back a half-hour from the agreed-upon
time of 10 p.m. _ a late hour in a country where many people rise
early to commute to work.
   Attacks in the official press accusing Solidarity of overly
aggressive campaign tactics began after the first show May 9 in
which union spokesman Janusz Onyskiewicz told voters how to choose
Solidarity candidates and eliminate official ones.
   On May 23, authorities yanked a show containing a discussion of
human rights by a group of lawyers running on the Solidarity ticket
saying it ``violated limits which may not be crossed.''
   And viewers who tuned in at the scheduled 10:30 p.m. time
Tuesday to see Solidarity's program featuring a popular comedian
were treated to 18 minutes of unscheduled coverage of an election
rally with Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski. Solidarity's show
followed.
   ``I think it's a kind of panic on the part of the government
side,'' said Jacek Moskwa, secretary of the Solidarity Citizens
Committee that is organizing the union's campaign efforts.
   The government has defended its use of television.
   ``In the current world, state authorities must have at their
disposal a state television, which is their basic instrument of
contact with the society,'' said former government spokesman Jerzy
Urban, a veteran propagandist who last month was named the head of
the department of radio and television.
   In the last month, a group 20 journalists and technicians fired
from their jobs in state TV for pro-Solidarity sympathies after the
December 1981 martial-law crackdown have worked non-stop to create
programs from scratch.
   Authorities provided Solidarity with one camera and a crew, and
allows the union to work out of a room in the state broadcasting
complex. Despite the cramped quarters, the team isn't complaining.
   ``We haven't had any technical problems so far, said Zorawski,
who analyzes the content of both Solidarity and official programs.
``There is a big interest in our programs even though there isn't a
great interest in election campaign coverage in general.''
   The Solidarity shows mix light moments and strong doses of voter
education.
   Stevie Wonder was shown singing with campaign workers in Warsaw
election headquarters and Yves Montand charmed striking students at
Warsaw University.
   The shows also explain the complicated voting process. Each
voter will receive several cards with candidates whose affiliation
won't be indicated on the ballot. In order to choose a candidate, a
voter must cross off the other names.
   Two shows had long segments of well-known union activists
telling voters to remember Solidarity candidates and simply cross
out the rest.
   Since the instructions are consistent with election regulations,
there is little authorities can do except mount a counteroffensive.
   After Tuesday's program, an official commentator blasted
Solidarity for advising voters to reject official candidates who
helped negotiate the ``round-table'' agreements that led to the
elections.
   Although authorities dispose of hours of time each week,
official programs have shown little flair. Many of them simply
feature interviews with candidates whose party affiliation often is
unclear.
   Under an agreed-upon formula, state TV devotes 23 percent of its
election coverage to Solidarity-backed candidates.
   For instance, seven minutes of the daily half-hour show called
``Election Studio'' are produced by Solidarity crews and feature
the opposition's candidates being interviewed or speaking to voters.
</TEXT>
