<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Editorials     06-01 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Editorials,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Papers Praise Bush Disarmament Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European papers offered President Bush unstinting
editorial praise for his disarmament proposals at the NATO summit
this week, but many noted that he only acted after Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev dominated the public opinion stage with his
proposals for several months.
   The dailies hailed Bush's call for speeded-up negotiations
between NATO and the Warsaw Pact to slash conventional weapons
arsenals in Europe, as well as his compromise with West Germany to
negotiate eventually with the Soviets on cutting short-range
nuclear missiles.
   ``The agreement constituted an important step toward maintaining
NATO's unity in a moment when all Europe's defense strategies have
entered a period of profound revision,'' was the opinion of Spain's
El Pais.
   ``As such, perhaps the most important result of the Brussels
summit is that it served to ratify that the Bush administration,
after an excessively long period of indecision, has actively
incorporated the logic of disarmament begun by (Bush's)
predecessor.''
   The independent Belgian daily Le Soir, which before the summit
predicted it could end in ``disaster,'' commented:
   ``George Bush, the chief actor in this success ... brilliantly
took the lead of a reunited alliance which adopted a new program of
defense, disarmament and political action, with as main goal the
will to overcome the division of Europe and Germany.
   ``... In his first big foreign policy move, George Bush scored a
real master stroke,'' it added.
   In Amsterdam, the left-leaning Dutch de Volkskrant said ``the
image of George Bush as a president lacking a vision on the
development of the peace and disarmament process in Europe must be
corrected.''
   ``In an almost astonishing manner, Bush has succeeded in
averting painful failure at the summit. He has restored unity
within NATO and has shown himself as the leader of the western
alliance for the first time.''
   London's The Times, an independent daily, wrote that Bush ``has
proved an important point this week _ that he can change up a gear
when the international going demands it.''
   ``The main reassurance for the prime minister (Margaret
Thatcher) and for Britain must be that, at a time of approaching
crisis, the `drifting presidency' became a `directed presidency.'
   The Financial Times, also an independent British daily, said
Bush ``will be justified in looking back at the NATO summit as his
first important foreign policy success. After all the
procrastination of the past few months, Mr. Bush has regained the
initiative for NATO in the arms control debate and negotiations
dominated hitherto by Mr. Mikhail Gorbachev.''
   ``Arbeiderbladet'' of Oslo, which represents the ruling Labor
Party of Norwegian Prime Miniuster Gro Harlem Brundtland, praised
Bush for showing ``promising signs as president in his way of
handling the relations with Europe.''
   The Swiss independent paper ``Basler Zeitung'' wrote:
   ``The criticism of the U.S. president has somehow been unfair:
George Bush, as one knows, never was a man of bold visionary
proposals, he is a pragmatist through and through, reacting rather
than initiating policies.
   ``Bush's strength resides in that last point. He knows how to
wait, and when he reacts, he is usually well-prepared.''
   But a note of dissent was struck by another independent Swiss
daily, Le Matin, which said Bush ``has undoubtedly committed the
sin of excess optimism here. ... This charm operation runs the risk
of rapidly getting bogged down in the details of the Vienna
negotiations'' on reducing the conventional arsenals of NATO and
the Warsaw Pact.
</TEXT>
