<FIRST>r a AM-People-Global     06-01 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Global,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Broadcast Designed To Raise Environmental Consciousness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World leaders, environmentalists and
entertainers including Elton John, Sting, Herbie Hancock and Diana
Ross will appear on a global television show Saturday to heighten
awareness of environmental issues.
   The five-hour program, ``Our Common Future,'' will originate
from New York and pick up satellite feeds from London, Moscow,
Australia, Brazil, Tokyo and other locales.
   Organizers said the program will be broadcast to 100 countries.
   It is to feature recorded messages from world leaders such as
President Bush, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar,
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, Indian Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi, Chinese Premier Li Peng and Zimbabwean Prime Minister
Robert Mugabe.
   Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland will be host of
the program, being produced by the Swiss-based Centre for Our
Common Future and Uplinger Enterprises Inc. of Washington.
   Mrs. Brundtland was chairwoman of a U.N.-appointed commission
that spent three years gathering testimony and information to
compile a report on development and the world's environment.
   The report, also called ``Our Common Future,'' was an appraisal
of changes needed throughout the world to use available natural
resources in ways that ensure that future generations could do the
same.
   Organizers said Saturday's program is not a fund-raiser.
   Instead, they say, it is a consciousness-raising spectacle,
designed to take advantage of the world's growing concern over
environmental issues such as ozone depletion, global warming and
tropical rain forest destruction.
   Executive producer Hal Uplinger, who also produced the Live Aid
global benefit for African relief in 1985, said the program would
be available to 90 percent of the television sets in use throughout
the world.
   Sustainable development involves merging the world's needs to
develop economically and improve living standards for all its
people with protecting its resources and the environment for the
future.
   ``I think it's a very important event,'' Uplinger said. ``The
purpose is to get people to think about it and get involved.''
</TEXT>
