<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--AuctionRecord     06-01 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Auction Record,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christie's Reports Auction Record for Chinese Painting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14th-century painted Chinese handscroll was
sold at auction Thursday for $1.87 million, more than triple the
previous record for a Chinese painting, Christie's auction house
said.
   ``The Imperial Autumn Hunting Party'' was purchased by My Humble
House of Taipei, an Oriental artifacts dealer, said spokeswoman
Doris Athineos. The price included Christie's 10 percent commission.
   The scroll, which Christie's said was ``most likely executed by
a Chinese artist working in the Mongol court,'' is nearly two feet
wide and 40 feet long. It shows the Yuan emperor and his hunting
party on a hilly landscape.
   The previous auction record for a Chinese painting was $539,000
for Zaho Meng Fu's ``Thousand Character Poem,'' Ms. Athineos said.
</TEXT>
