<FIRST>r a AM-CashSeized     06-01 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cash Seized,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Seeks Return of Money Seized, Seeks Damages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man found with $69,950 in his luggage at an
airport is trying to get they money back from authorities, along
with $50,000 in damages.
   Lt. Peter J. Misko, leader of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's
Drug Enforcement Unit, said deputies searched John L. Taylor Jr.'s
bag March 15 at Mitchell International Airport after it was singled
out by drug-sniffing dogs. They seized the cash, gave him a receipt
and let him fly home to Los Angeles. He was not charged with any
crime.
   ``The drug dogs hit right on the money, so we know whoever was
handling the money was handling drugs,'' Misko said.
   Taylor's attorney, Alvin R. Ugent, said his client contends a
deputy ``jerked the dog's head'' toward the suitcase. Ungent said
Taylor, 51, said the money was working capital for a company he
owns that sells ventilation equipment.
   Ugent filed a claim Wednesday against the county and Sheriff
Richard E. Artison, seeking return of the money and damages.
   Misko said the money was turned over to the federal Drug
Enforcement Administration. The government can seize assets when
officers have probable cause to believe the assets are connected to
illegal drug trafficking, said Kelly Snyder, agent in charge of the
Milwaukee DEA office.
