<DOCNO> AP890601-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 6thLd-Writethru a0664 06-01 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0664,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cristiani Takes Office, Calls For Talks With Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Cristiani calling for talks
with the rebels. Pickup 5th pvs, ``Cristiani said... TRIMS thereafter to
tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Cristiani
took over from Jose Napoleon Duarte today and promptly offered to
open talks with guerrillas who have been fighting the government
for nine years.
   During his inaugural address, Cristiani said: ``The process of
dialogue will not be simple, but we are willing to initiate it
immediately.''
   Cristiani, whose right-wing political party has been linked to
death squads that have killed thousands of civilians, said: ``We
are not asking for anyone's surrender, but neither will we endure a
terrorist war against the economy and against the people.''
   It was the first transfer of power from one elected head of
state to another in El Salvador.
   Soldiers patrolled the capital and roads were deserted after
Marxist guerrillas, who recently threatened to make the country
``ungovernable,'' ordered a ban on transportation and set off bombs
to protest the inauguration.
   Cristiani, whose political party is blamed for poor living
conditions of the peasants who make up most of El Salvador's
population, said:
   ``Our government will be based fundamentally on the principles
of liberty, honesty, legality and security.''
   Cristiani said he was taking office after ``a long period of
anguish and need'' in El Salvador. The roots of El Salvador's
problems are old, he said, ``but ... sharpened by internal and
external forces.''
   Cristiani, 41, a U.S.-educated coffee grower, was elected March
19. Voter turnout was the lowest in a decade, which was partly
attributed to a ban on traffic ordered by the rebel Farabundo
National Liberation Front, which has been fighting a nine-year war
with the U.S.-backed government.
   Cristiani's right-wing Republican National Alliance, or Arena,
was founded in 1981 by a cashiered army major and alleged
death-squad kingpin, Roberto D'Aubuisson. He still is hailed by
stalwarts as the party's ``maximum leader.''
   Death squads are blamed for up to half the 70,000 deaths in the
civil war, but D'Aubuisson and Arena deny any connection to the
squads.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher today praised the
transfer of power, saying it reflected the ``strong commitment of
the people of El Salvador to democracy.''
   More than 6,000 people attended the ceremony. They included
delegates from 36 nations, including the United States.
   Ricardo Alvarenga Valdivieso, president of the Legislative
Assembly, placed the presidential sash on Cristiani, who then took
the oath of office.
   The guerrillas have heralded Cristiani with nightly 21-bomb
salutes, blowing up power lines and utility poles at a pace
unmatched in recent years. They threatened to make the country
``ungovernable.''
   Officials at the state power company said guerrillas bombed
transmission towers Wednesday night, knocking out power in 90
percent of the country.
   On Wednesday, the rebels called an indefinite traffic ban, and
bus dispatchers said it was a success. Most of the country's 5.5
million people rely on buses to get around.
   This morning, streets in the capital were empty.
   The transport ban has been a favorite tactic of rebels, who
threaten to shoot at or set fire to cars or buses on the roads.
   Also Wednesday, troops in the capital seized a cache of rebel
weapons. Police said they netted 350 Soviet rifles, 300 sticks of
dynamite and 1.5 million bullets.
   El Salvador is the most densely populated country in the Western
Hemisphere. Infant mortality, contaminated drinking water,
illiteracy and lack of roads and electricity plague its many
peasant farmers.
   The Salvadoran economy would be virtually bankrupt were it not
for the $1 million per day in economic and military aid provided by
Washington. U.S. officials have expressed concern about an eventual
rise in illegal detentions, torture and summary executions under
Arena.
   Cristiani's first hurdle is convincing Salvadorans and the
international community that he is in charge as he claims to be.
But Arena opponents, and even some party insiders, say Cristiani is
a front man.
   Arena in its early days was a political branch of the landed
elite _ those who made fortunes growing and exporting coffee,
cotton and sugar cane in a semi-feudal system that left the vast
majority in poverty.
   The pillars of that system have been eroded in five years of
reformist Christian Democratic government. Duarte, though he failed
to end the war and promote prosperity, is generally credited with
having begun the foundation of incipient democracy.
   Politically motivated killings are far fewer than when Duarte
took office in 1984. Non-combatant leftists can now organize labor
unions and express themselves politically at considerably less risk
of being killed.
   Duarte, who is dying of liver cancer, is concerned his efforts
on behalf of democracy will be undone.
   ``There may be differences between Cristiani and D'Aubuisson as
individuals, but they both support a totalitarian project and they
both favor an economic policy that benefits the rich,'' he told The
Associated Press on Monday during a farewell cocktail at the
Presidential Palace.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
