<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     06-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Government Hunger Strike Enters Second Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-government hunger strike at
Seoul's Roman Catholic cathedral entered its second week Thursday
with protesters vowing to continue the fast until police admit they
killed a student leader.
   Dozens of hunger strikers outside Myongdong Cathedral shouted
slogans against President Roh Tae-woo. The fasters were blocked by
lines of riot police outside, while hundreds of other protesters
rested or engaged in discussions in the compound.
   In the eastern provincial capital of Chunchon, about 500
rock-throwing students fought riot police who lashed out with
bamboo sticks. At least 10 students and police were injured, the
South Korean news agency Yonhap reported.
   Dissidents and radical students have staged protests to denounce
the government over the death of Lee Chol-kyu, a student whose body
was found May 10 in a reservoir outside the southern city of
Kwangju.
   Dissidents contend police tortured and killed Lee. The
opposition-controlled National Assembly launched a parliamentary
investigation into Lee's death Thursday and dispatched lawmakers to
Kwangju.
   A government report has concluded Lee slipped and fell into the
reservoir after fleeing a police roadblock. Prosecutors said they
found no evidence of torture.
   Student leaders said 436 students and dissidents were fasting
Thursday at the cathedral. Since about 300 students began the
hunger strike May 25, 14 had been hospitalized, with more joining
the fast this week, the leaders said.
   Thousands of riot police have maintained tight security around
the church and on nearby roads, turning away students.
   On Wednesday, police arrested about 600 students who tried to
march to the cathedral. Most of the arrested students had been
released after questioning, police said.
   Students said the cathedral protest is based on the same tactics
used by Chinese students in protests in Beijing.
   Radical student leaders have been trying to switch to peaceful
protests after six riot troopers were killed May 3 in a campus
clash. The deaths triggered public outrage.
   On Thursday, prosecutors indicted 69 students on charges related
to the killing of the police officers.
</TEXT>
