<FIRST>u a PM-CancerBoy 2ndLd-Writethru a0633 06-01 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cancer Boy, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0633,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Surrenders With Cancer-Stricken Son</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with wife released from jail,
husband given 10-day suspended sentence, child returned to city custody;
Picks up 15th graf, `Mandel said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose wife was jailed after he took their
4-year-old son from a hospital where he was undergoing
court-ordered treatment for leukemia surrendered with the boy
today, police said.
   Family Court Judge Leon Deutsch gave David Pagan a suspended
10-day sentence, released his wife, Migdalia, and placed their son
back in the custody of child welfare authorities.
   Deutsch gave the parents unlimited visitation rights at the
hospital but said they must be accompanied by a city or hospital
official to prevent them from removing Darian Pagan again.
   Pagan, 36, took his son from the Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Hospital sometime Sunday, police said. The boy was undergoing
court-ordered treatment for leukemia.
   Darian was hospitalized Friday under an order from Deutsch that
was requested by the city's Child Welfare Administration because
hospital officials said the boy was not getting the treatment he
needed.
   Mrs. Pagan was jailed the last two nights on contempt of court
charges for refusing to tell the court where her husband and child
were.
   Pagan walked into Family Court around noon today. The husband
and wife appeared before the judge. The child was in the
courthouse, but not in the courtroom.
   The couple's attorney, Steven Mandel, said the father had
removed the child from the hospital and was taking him to the
Anderson Medical and Tumor Institute, which is affiliated with the
University of Texas in Houston.
   He did not say how far the two had traveled or what prompted
their return.
   Speaking of the parents, the judge said: ``They have violated
the order of the court and potentially harmed the child. They may
well have placed this child in jeopardy.''
   After giving Pagan the 10-day suspended sentence, he added,
``The mother has been punished. I will order her released.''
   Mandel said that when hospital officials went to the city
agency, doctors said Darian was in ``imminent danger'' if he did
not receive a radical form of radiation and chemotherapy.
   The parents were upset because no such treatment was
administered between Friday, when the boy was admitted, and Sunday,
when he was taken from the hospital, Mandel said.
   The Pagans are Jehovah's Witnesses, a religion that opposes
blood transfusions. Mandel said their religion did not play a part
in the court case.
   He said the child had received much medical care and treatment
for leukemia since he was diagnosed at age 2.
</TEXT>
