<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Strikes     06-01 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Strikes,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikes Black Out TV; Threaten to Disrupt Trains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at the state-run Spanish television
began a 24-hour strike for better pay Thursday, cancelling
programming for only the second time since broadcasting began in
1956.
   Thousands of rail passengers, meanwhile, braced for a one-day
strike Friday at the state-controlled rail system as its 63,000
employees continued a long-running battle with management for
better pay.
   The strikes formed part of a six-month battle for higher pay by
employees of state enterprises who oppose the Socialist
administration's efforts to keep pay increases moderate to contain
inflation that is running at a 6.7 percent annually.
   A rail spokeswoman guaranteed service on four international
routes _ Madrid-Paris, Barcelona-Paris, Barcelona-Bern,
Switzerland, and Barcelona-Geneva _ as well as 19 night trains to
and from major provincial capitals.
   On Friday, between 50 percent and 75 percent of regular commuter
trains would be in service and only during rush hours, the railway
said.
   Television union official Joaquin Aguilar said Thursday the only
broadcasts would be four, 20-minute news segments, followed by
obligatory public service campaign spots for the June 15 European
parliamentary elections and an hour of children's cartoons.
   The only previous 24-hour TV strike in Spain came Dec. 14, when
Socialist and Communist unions carried out a general strike to
pressure the government of Socialist Prime Minister to make a
leftward shift away from inflation-fighting economic austerity
policies to greatly increase social spending.
</TEXT>
