<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Salvador-Arms     06-01 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Arms,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Criticizes Cuba on Captured Equipment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday the capture
of ammunition alleged to have been supplied by Cuba to leftist
guerrillas in El Salvador contradicts Cuba's stated support for the
Central American peace process.
   Deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said that among the items
seized by government forces on Tuesday was 1 million rounds of
ammunition bearing stamps indicating they were made in Cuba.
   The cache was found following a tip from a captured member of
the FMLN guerrillas. It was described by Salvadoran military
leaders as the largest cache of insurgent weapons ever captured.
   The discovery, Boucher said, ``belies Cuba's assertion of
support'' for regional peace agreements that reaffirm the principal
of non-interference in the internal affairs of Central American
nations.
   Boucher said the cache also included 283 Soviet AK47 assault
rifles, hundreds of other Soviet bloc weapons and material for the
manufacture of explosive devices, including 892 one-pound blocks of
TNT.
   ``These weapons were to be used to commit terrorist acts against
the people of El Salvador,'' Boucher said.
   Other officials, asking not to be identified, said the captured
FMLN guerrilla had told Salvadoran authorities that the weapons
were sent from Nicaragua to El Salvador on refrigerated trucks.
   The officials said that such transportation was used presumably
to minimize the possibility that the explosive devices would
detonate in the hot weather.
   While the ammunition appeared to be of Cuban origin, the point
of departure of the other equipment was not clear, the officials
said.
   They added, however, that past patterns have been that the
weapons are sent to the rebels from Cuba by way of Nicaragua.
   As Boucher spoke, Aldredo Cristiani was sworn in to a five-year
term as president of El Salvador, succeeding Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   Boucher said the United States continues to support the
consolidation in El Salvador of a democracy in which ``security
flows from respect for human rights, the rule of law and equitable
development.
   ``We applaud President Cristiani's firm commitment to these
goals,'' he said.
   Indiana Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., a former chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee, headed the U.S. delegation to
the inaugural.
   Vice President Dan Quayle plans a visit to El Salvador and three
other Central American countries later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
