<DOCNO> AP890601-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1953EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-QuayleTrip     06-01 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle Trip,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Off to Latin America _ Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle will visit Central
America this month, on a four-day trip to show administration
support for the newly elected president of El Salvador and rally
opposition to Panamanian ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega, Quayle's
office said Thursday.
   The June 11-14 journey will include stops in Guatemala,
Honduras, El Salvador and Costa Rica.
   Quayle is to meet with the presidents of those countries, as
well as political opposition and military leaders. He will also see
leaders of the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, said his press secretary
David Beckwith. He declined to say where that meeting would take
place.
   The trip will be Quayles's second to El Salvador, following a
visit in early February in which the vice president sternly linked
continued U.S. aid to a commitment by government and military
leaders to crack down on human rights violations.
   Since that visit, the election of Alfredo Cristiani as president
has created new worries on Capitol Hill because of ties between
Cristiani's party, Arena, and past death squad activity.
   Cristiani's inauguration Thursday sparked leftist violence in El
Salvador and a spate of protests across the United States by
activists opposed to continued U.S. aid.
   But Quayle's visit is meant to demonstrate U.S. support for
Cristiani and the intention to give him a chance to make good on
his promise to uphold human rights and seek a negotiated settlement
to the country's bloody rebel war.
   Quayle is expected to underscore the human rights message again,
but without the stern lecture he gave military generals on his last
visit.
   Quayle's discussions regarding Panama may be colored by the
upcoming report of an Organization of American States delegation
that visited Panama.
   The team of diplomats from Trinidad, Guatemala and Costa Rica
recently returned after four days of futile talks aimed at finding
a solution to the political crisis stemming from May 7 elections
that were widely seen as rigged by Noriega.
   They make their formal report to the OAS on June 6, as a beefed
up U.S. military presence in Panama and harsh anti-Noriega rhetoric
have resulted in no visible signs that Noriega is on the way out.
   Quayle will encourage U.S. allies in the region to stick with
the United States in its anti-Noriega effort, Beckwith said.
   He also is expected to discuss the Central American peace
process aimed at ending the rebel war in Nicaragua.
   The Contra troops, encamped inside Honduras near the Nicaraguan
border, are being sustained with U.S. non-military assistance until
Nicaraga hold elections next February.
   The Bush administration has committed to the diplomatic route in
Nicaragua while watching to see whether that country's leftist
government will fulfill its promises of democratic reforms.
   Quayle's earlier visit to El Salvador, on the first foreign trip
of the Bush administration, was to highlight U.S. attention to the
region and to warn El Salvador that the new U.S. president expected
enforcement of human rights standards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
