<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Cyprus-US     06-01 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cyprus-US,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Resigns For Health Reasons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Bill K. Perrin has
resigned for health reasons and will leave Cyprus in summer for
treatment in the United States, the U.S. Embassy said Thursday.
   The embassy did not disclose the nature of his ailment, nor what
day he would leave.
   Perrin, 51, returned to Nicosia a week ago from consultations in
the United States, where doctors advised him that it would be
``unwise to continue his official mission in Cyprus,'' an embassy
statement said.
   It quoted Perrin as saying: ``I regret that for health reasons,
I will not be able to serve my government in Cyprus as long as I
have wished.''
   ``I trust that the people of Cyprus will give the same genuine
support to my successor when that person is named by President
Bush.''
   The White House has not yet named the successor, the embassy
said.
</TEXT>
