<DOCNO> AP890601-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-People     06-01 1031</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1072</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dylan will return to his home state
this summer for RiverFest, a 10-day festival of music along the
banks of the Mississippi River.
   Born in Duluth and raised in Hibbing, Dylan got his start
singing in coffeehouses near the University of Minnesota in 1959.
But he has performed locally only three times since _ at the
Minneapolis Auditorium in 1965, the St. Paul Civic Center in 1978
and the Metrodome in 1986.
   Other scheduled performers in the festival to be held July 28 to
Aug. 6 include blues-rockers Stevie Ray Vaughan and George
Thorogood, rapper Tone Loc, and rock bands Cheap Trick and Joan
Jett and the Blackhearts.
   But festival promoter Randy Levy said Dylan undoubtedly will be
the star attraction: ``Let this festival be known as the one that
brought Bob Dylan home.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve pianists _ including one from
the United States _ have been named semifinalists in the eighth Van
Cliburn International Competition.
   After five days of preliminary competition, the top 12
performers were named Thursday from a field of 38 pianists
representing 19 countries.
   Those selected and the countries they represent are Jean-Efflam
Bavouzet, France; Elisso Bolkvadze, Soviet Union; Pedro Burmester,
Portugal; Angela Cheng, Canada; Jose Carlos Cacarelli, Brazil;
Kevin Kenner, Baltimore; Lin Hai, People's Republic of China;
Benedetto Lupo, Italy; Kayo Miki, Japan; Alexander Shtarkman,
Soviet Union; Aleksei Sultanov, Soviet Union; and Tian Ying,
People's Republic of China.
   Each semifinalist played two 25-minute programs for an
international panel of 15 judges to make the cut.
   Semifinal competition begins Friday and concludes Tuesday, when
jurors narrow the field to six. The winner will be named June 11.
   The top prize is $15,000 cash, plus recording and performing
contracts valued at more than $200,000.
   The competition is named for Fort Worth pianist Van Cliburn and
has been conducted every four years for 27 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Bush, son of President George Bush
held unofficial talks Thursday with Thailand's Foreign Minister
Siddhi Savetsila on trade issues.
   Traveling with several businessmen from Florida, where he is a
prominent Republican Party figure, Bush is exploring business and
investment opportunities in Thailand.
   The team had a private luncheon with Siddhi and Deputy Prime
Minister Pong Sarasin. Siddhi told reporters they discussed trade
and economic frictions between the United States and Thailand.
   The United States may implement trade penalties against Thailand
for its alleged failure to respect American intellectual property
rights.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Lorrie Morgan was
appointed to administer the estate of her late husband, singer
Keith Whitley, and a judge ordered an inventory of Whitley's
outstanding recording royalties.
   Whitley, who died May 9 of an alcohol overdose, left no will,
according to a Probate Court petition filed by Morgan, under her
legal name of Loretta Lynn Whitley.
   The petition said the late singer owned real estate worth more
than $100,000, which will automatically go to his wife as the
surviving joint owner.
   Morgan, a member of the Grand Ole Opry, estimated the value of
her husband's personal property at more than $80,000 and the gross
value of Whitley's estate at $50,000. She said she and the couple's
two children are Whitley's only heirs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei Sakharov and his wife Yelena Bonner
have accepted an invitation to visit Norway later this month, the
Royal Norwegian Council for Scientific and Industrial Research,
said Thursday.
   Sakharov was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 while still
branded a dissident. His wife was permitted to accept the prize on
his behalf in Oslo.
   Both the Council and the Norwegian Nobel Committee have
frequently invited the couple to visit Norway after Sakharov was
allowed to leave the closed city of Gorky, where he spent several
years in internal exile.
   The couple plan to leave Moscow on June 15 and visit the
Netherlands and Britain before arriving in Oslo on June 26 or 27.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees at Riverside Hospital chose
Kenny G to perform at a special concert and the saxophonist
rewarded them with a special musical preview while they worked.
   Offered the choice of a dinner or a show, hospital employees
opted for a show and selected Kenny G over Ray Charles, Johnny
Cash, the Statler Brothers, Frankie Avalon, dancer Gregory Hines
and others. The hospital hired him to perform Wednesday night at
the Ohio Theater in a concert for employees and their families.
   Kenny G also performed for several patients at the hospital and
stopped by the nursery to serenade 1- and 2-day-olds.
   ``After he played he said, `That's all right, you guys you don't
have to stand,' '' said Erie Chapman, the hospital's president and
chief executive officer.
   ``I think it was a thrill for the atients and the people taking
care of them,'' Chapman said. ``You almost feel like it (music) has
a healing effect itself.''
   Chapman said he did not know how much the hospital paid for
Kenny G's one-hour performance, but it would cost about the same as
dinner for 3,000 people _ about $30,000.
   The hospital's employee recognition program was scheduled to be
held before the concert. In the program, employees receive awards
for years of service and other accomplishments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean Harris, killer of ``Scarsdale Diet Doctor''
Herman Tarnower, says she is remorseful about his death.
   ``Remorse has become an appendage to me,'' Ms. Harris told
Independent Network News in an interview this week at the Bedford
Hills Correctional Facility in Westchester County.
   ``It's like another skin and I live in it and I always will,''
said Ms. Harris, 66.
   She said she feels ``terrible, terribly sorry. You don't throw
it off.''
   Ms. Harris said Tarnower could have prevented his death by
talking to her calmly when she confronted him about a love affair.
Instead, she said, he called her ``crazy'' and hit her in the face.
She then shot him to death.
   Ms. Harris was sentenced to 15 years to life in prison in March
1981. She has appealed twice to Gov. Mario Cuomo for clemency,
without success.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
