<FIRST>r a AM-People-Strawberry-Simon     06-01 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Strawberry-Simon,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carly Simon, Darryl Strawberry Get Kids' Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY62</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Carly Simon and slugger Darryl Strawberry
greeted squealing fans Thursday as they were honored in a Central
Park ceremony for their commitment to helping children.
   The creator of such hits as ``You're So Vain'' said standing
next to the Mets star had a special significance for her.
   ``As an 8-year-old or 10-year-old, while my friends were
dreaming of being movie stars, rock stars or whatever, my goal was
to hit one over the center field fence,'' she said, adding that
Jackie Robinson was her childhood idol.
   ``Any time you have a dream, don't imagine it's an impossible
dream,'' Ms. Simon told the group of about 100 children gathered at
a park playground.
   Ms. Simon and Strawberry were among the adults and children
getting community service awards from the Association to Benefit
Children, a group that helps poor, handicapped and AIDS-stricken
youngsters.
   Strawberry, who had traveled overnight after an extra-inning
game on the West Coast, shook some hands and posed for pictures,
but didn't give a speech.
   Ms. Simon donated the proceeds from the first show at her new
art gallery in Manhattan to the children's group, according to Jim
Hart, an ABC volunteer. She also has acted as a spokesperson for
the group from time to time.
   Strawberry was honored ``mostly because he's very important to
these kids _ a hero, particularly to New York City children,'' said
Hart. He will do some unspecified work on behalf of the
organization in the upcoming year, said Hart.
</TEXT>
