<FIRST>u w PM-SpellingBee 2ndLd-Writethru a0620 06-01 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spelling Bee, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0620,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spelling Bee Goes Into Its Last Rounds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with fifth round; picks up 6th graf, The opening.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After five rounds and 832 words, the field of
contestants in the 62nd National Spelling Bee was narrowed today to
18 girls and 16 boys, of whom 10 have taken part in the national
competition before.
   The winner was scheduled to be named after the final round later
in the day.
   Among those remaining in contention was Lisa M. Edwin of Dwight,
Ill., one of the six 10-year-olds who were among the 222 who began
the competition on Wednesday. The youngest entry in the bee, Lisa
Ishimaru of Sacramento, Calif., was eliminated earlier in the day.
   The competition is open to students who have not reached their
16th birthday or passed beyond the 8th grade.
   Of the surviving contestants after the fifth round, three were
competing at the national level for the third time: Scott Isaacs,
14, of Englewood, Colo.; Kanika Bahl, 13, of Beavercreek, Ohio, and
Robert Pryor, 12, of Washington. Seven others were making their
second appearance.
   Lisa, the daughter of a state tax auditor in Sacramento, left
out the ``e'' in ``yeomanry'' and joined 70 older competitors on
the sidelines as a result of the fourth round. Earlier, she had
correctly spelled ``mountebank,`` ``blolly'' and ``reflorescence.''
   Yeomanry means a body of small landowners or a troop of soldiers.
   Lisa walked from the stage with a solemn face, but showed no
sign of dismay such as a visible slump or headshake, as some of the
other losers did.
   The opening day's competition winnowed a field of 222, the
largest in the history of the event, to 151, including Lisa, a 4th
grader who studies the violin.
   Although she is the only 9-year-old in this year's bee,
competing with youngsters up through age 15, she is not the
youngest in the history of the event. Iris Liu of Muncie, Ind., was
a few weeks short of her 9th birthday when she competed in last
year's field of 200. But she lost out on the first day, stumbling
over the word ``waywiser.''
   By the end of three rounds, 601 words had been spelled, compared
with 485 last year.
   The one tense moment of the day came when Susan Bonner, 11, a
6th grader from Fort Necessity, La., spelled ``scordatura'' so
softly that it took the judges five minutes to figure out she had
spelled it wrong.
   Susan sat nervously in a front seat as the judges played and
replayed a tape recording. Then they rang the bell, indicating a
mistake. She had used a ``t'' instead of a ``d'' in the word, which
means tuning an instrument to produce a special effect.
   In one of the few quips injected into the serious business of
spelling, Angela Martin, 14, of St. Petersburg, Fla., borrowed a
line from the television show ``Wheel of Fortune'' and exclaimed,
``Oh, God, can I buy a vowel?'' when she was given the word
``boulevardier'' to spell. Even without any such help, she spelled
it right.
   Those eliminated in the first day's spelling included three
13-year-olds who were competing in the bee for the second time.
Travis P. Tharp of Pensacola, Fla., misspelled ``pluricellular,''
Ana M. Gordan of Manchester, N.H., stumbled over ``inumbrate'' and
Cheryl D. Frye of Woodstock, Va., went down on ``wokas,'' a plant
that grows wild in the West.
   Four of the six 10-year-olds in the competition were eliminated.
Malinda Shepherd of Burnsville, N.C., was tripped up by
``seriatim,'' Cheryl Klein of Peculiar, Mo., by ``rhizotomy,''
Laura Nawojchik of Leesburg, Va., by ``bijouterie'' and Emily J.
Banwell of Alamo, Calif., by ``floccose.''
   Also in the competition at the start were 24 who are 11, 45 who
are 12, 89 who are 13, 55 who are 14 and two who are 15.
   Nearly 9 million students participated at the local level in
contests sponsored by Scripps Howard newspapers in 13 cities and by
205 other daily, weekly and Sunday newspapers.
   The winner will receive a cash award of $1,500. Other prizes are
$1,000 for second, $750 for third, $500 for fourth, $400 for fifth,
$300 for sixth, $200 for seventh through 10th, $100 for 11th
through 20th, and 202 prizes of $50 each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
