<DOCNO> AP890601-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PresbyterianChurch     06-01 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Presbyterian Church,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Starts Third Century Trying to Regain Moral Clout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Presbyterians are coming to
historic Philadelphia to elect a new moderator to lead the fight to
reverse the church's membership decline.
   The 622 official delegates to the General Assembly of the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) will attend sessions beginning Tuesday
and running through June 14. A pre-assembly symposium begins Friday.
   The Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) traces its origins to the First
Presbytery founded in Philadelphia 283 years ago. Then a number of
colonial churches, some formed as early as 1683, banded together to
form the denomination in the first General Assembly held here in
1789.
   Presbyterian membership grew to a high of more than 4 million in
the mid-1960s, then began to fall to today's 2,938,830 members in
11,573 churches. Dwindling membership is a problem shared generally
with all the long-standing denominations.
   The Rev. C. Kenneth Hall, of Butler, Pa., current church
moderator and presiding officer for the 201st General Assembly,
believes the church needs to reclaim the powerful voice it once
exerted on social, economic and political issues if it wants to
buck the trend.
   ``Our church is determined to turn this thing around, which is
why at our last Assembly we established evangelism as one of our
priorities, and over the next five years we are going to commit $15
million to bring in new members,'' he said.
   Two men and two women face election Wednesday to succeed Hall as
moderator.
   They are the Rev. James Johnson Jr., 61, pastor of the First
Presbyterian Church, Columbus, Ga.; the Rev. Joan Salmon Campbell,
51, associate executive for mission programs in the Philadelphia
Presbytery; the Rev. William Skinner, 56, pastor of the First
Presbyterian Church, Sioux City, Iowa, and Ms. Agnes Wilson, elder
in the Second Presbyterian Church, Sumter, S.C.
   Also on the agenda is a proposal to increase annual per capita
dues 16 cents to $3.55. The church budget is currently $11.6
million.
   Opening Friday is the three-day ``Continue the Journey, A
Symposium on the Future.''
   Keynoter Roger Heyns, former chancellor of the University of
California at Berkeley, will discuss developments in science,
economics, the arts, education, politics and technology and how
they will shape the church's future.
   Presenters include West Germany's President Richard von
Weizacker on global politics; Maxine Singer, president of the
Carnegie Institution of Washington, on biology and health; the Rev.
Patricia McClurg, president of the National Council of Churches of
Christ in the United States, on religion; Shigekuni Kawamura,
president of Japan Ink Chemical Industry, on business and the
world's economy; Margaret McKenna, president of Lesly College, on
education and entertainer Steve Allen, on communications.
   Because of the bicentennial flavor of this year's meeting, a
number of social events are being planned for the 10,000 delegates,
alternates, their families and church members expected.
   Among the activities will be a week-long ``Gift to the City''
work on a low-cost housing project. Members of about 30
Presbyterian churches will contribute over 1,200 hours of labor and
some $100,000 to five groups for low-cost housing to poor
Philadelphians.
   ``Although a one-week effort cannot solve Philadelphia's housing
crisis it can make a major impact,'' said Chairman George
Hollingshead Jr., associate pastor of suburban Bryn Mawr
Presbyterian Church. ``This project is also intended to be a model
for future Presbyterian national meetings in other cities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
