<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--India-Jets     06-01 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--India-Jets,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Jets Damaged When Hangar Collapses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ceiling of a hangar collapsed at an
air base southeast of New Delhi, damaging eight Indian air force
Mirage-2000 combat jets, it was reported Thursday.
   Two of the French-built planes were damaged beyond repair and
six others suffered extensive damage in the air force's biggest
peacetime accident, according to Defense Ministry sources quoted by
the Indian Express.
   Damage to the Mirages, purchased in 1985, was estimated at $175
million.
   Defense Ministry spokesman T.G. Nallamuthu confirmed the
accident but insisted the damage to the jets was minor.
   The newspaper said at least four people working inside the
hangar were injured in the accident last week at Gwalior, 170 miles
southeast of New Delhi. It did not give the exact day.
   The 115,000-man Indian air force has 701 combat aircraft,
including 40 Mirage-2000s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
