<FIRST>u i AM-SovietGeorgia     06-01 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Georgia,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Reveals Party Communications About Georgia Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet leadership, stung by accusations of
complicity or coverup in a bloody military assault on Georgian
demonstrators in April, took the extraordinary step Thursday of
revealing secret cables about it.
   ``This is the original,'' Vice President Anatoly I. Lukyanov
told the hushed Congress of People's Deputies, holding up a cable
in which the Georgian Communist Party chief told the Kremlin of the
bloodshed at a pro-independence demonstration six hours after it
happened.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the deputies Wednesday the
cables established the need for a commission to investigate the
matter.
   He was responding to charges by Yuri Vlasov of Moscow that
Gorbachev must know who was responsible for the order to clear
Rustavelli Prospekt in Tbilisi, capital of the Georgian republic.
   Other deputies have said a high official must have known in
advance of the assault. They demanded the official be identified.
   The Kremlin response emphasized the new parliament's power to
demand explanations of government actions. The public reading of
three cables to Moscow from former Georgian party leader Dzhumber
Patiashvili was an unprecedented revelation of documents
traditionally kept secret.
   Soldiers dispersed thousands of pro-independence demonstrators
in Tbilisi at 4 a.m. April 9, and 20 civilians were killed.
   Lukyanov, reading from the documents to the silent hall, said
Patiashvili cabled Moscow at 8:50 p.m., seven hours before the
assault, saying the situation was tense but under control.
   ``There is no need for any kind of extra, extreme measures from
the Central Committee of the Communist Party or the government,''
he read.
   The next cable, at 10:25 a.m. April 9, told Moscow authorities
of the casualties, Lukyanov said. That appeared to support
statements by Gorbachev and other officials that they learned of
the attack six hours after it happened.
   ``These are the events as they developed,'' Gorbachev told the
deputies Wednesday. ``We have to follow these events to their roots
and clear it up, take it to the Supreme Soviet and make whatever
decision is necessary in this case.''
   The 2,250-member Congress established its own commission to
investigate.
   Col. Gen. Igor Rodionov, who commanded the soldiers in Tbilisi,
told reporters the cables were authentic. Rodionov, also is a
deputy, had a bitter exchange with Patiashvili during the Tuesday
session about responsibility for the deaths.
   Patiashvili said Rodionov and other military officials told a
meeting of leaders in Tbilisi they had orders from Moscow to stop
demonstrations that had gripped the city for almost a week.
   On Thursday, Rodionov said the cables to Moscow accurately
reflected the situation in Tbilisi at the time, but the situation
deteriorated into a ``pure orgy, with anti-Soviet slogans ...
appeals to overturn the government, appeals to exterminate
communists and those who were opposed to them.''
   A Georgian commission has accused the military of a ``planned .
.. massacre'' using shovels, clubs and chemical substances.
   Rodionov told reporters Thursday the victims in Tbilisi were
crushed to death, not killed by soldiers. He denied chemicals were
used.
   ``The version about gas was needed to create a picture of
violence _ not a picture of resistance but a picture of violence
against a holiday atmosphere, where people were singing, dancing
and praying,'' he said.
   He said he would be satisfied with any national investigating
group but did not trust the Georgian commission, which circulated
its report at the Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
