<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1723EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador Bjt   06-01 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rightist Assumes Salvadoran Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rightist Alfredo Cristiani
assumed the presidency Thursday and pledged to rescue the nation
from its nine-year civil war and poverty.
   The 41-year-old businessman, leader of the Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, offered Marxist-led guerrillas
immediate dialogue on ending the war, but he made it clear he would
not negotiate government policy or share power.
   ``In this moment of assuming leadership, we are the enemies of
no one,'' Cristiani said. ``We are not asking for anyone's
surrender.
   ``But we also cannot permit that social harmony be achieved
through violating the law. We have sworn to uphold the constitition
and the law, and that we will do.''
   The guerrilla group Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front
said on its clandestine radio: ``Arena means war, poverty and
totalitarianism.''
   El Salvador's civil war has killed an estimated 70,000 people,
most of them civilians.
   Cristiani's inauguration ceremony was held at the capital's
international fairgrounds before about 6,000 people.
   The presidents of Guatemala, Costa Rica and Honduras attended,
and 33 other countries sent delegations. The U.S. delegation was
headed by Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind.
   Electricity for the ceremony had to be provided by generators
powered by gasoline and diesel because guerrilla sabotage overnight
left 90 percent of the country, which is about the size of
Massachusetts, without power. The rebels have vowed to make the
country ``ungovernable.''
   Cristiani's 45-minute inaugural speech was a tribute to free
enterprise and what he believed conservative economic policy will
do to revive the nation's economy.
   But he also promised ``a judiciary more effectual each day, and
ever greater respect for human rights.''
   The U.S. government has supported the Christian Democrats, the
party of outgoing president Jose Napoleon Duarte, and has expressed
concern about an eventual rise in human rights abuses under Arena.
   Arena was founded in 1981 by former army major and alleged
death-squad kingpin Roberto d'Aubuisson, who is still hailed by
stalwarts as the party's ``maximum leader.''
   Rightist death squads are blamed for more than 20,000 deaths in
the early 1980s. D'Aubuisson and Arena deny any connection with the
squads and say Arena, because of its nationalism, has been
slandered by Christian Democrats, the foreign press and human
rights organizations.
   Cristiani dedicated several minutes of his speech to the rights
issue in an apparent attempt to allay fears.
   D'Aubuisson was hailed with thunderous applause and chants of
his surname twice during the ceremony. He responded a beaming smile
and a raised clenched fist.
   Cristiani decried the corruption perceived as rampant in the
administration of Duarte and promised his government would be based
on ``liberty, honesty, legality and security.''
   Duarte, who is dying of cancer, sat impassively on the dais next
to Cristiani before he took the oath and received the presidential
sash.
   Francisco Merino, 37, was sworn in as vice president.
   Corruption, as well as Duarte's failure to end the war and
improve the economy, contributed to Arena's landslide victory in
the March 19 presidential election.
   The Christian Democrats nationalized banks and the crop export
business. Cristiani promised to return both industries to the
private sector.
   But he said Arena has no intention of rolling back an agrarian
reform program that has during the past decade redistributed a
third of the nation's arable land.
   ``Marxist war has no future in El Salvador,'' Cristiani said.
``We will work for understanding with all sectors of society. The
FMLN is one of those sectors and we will pursue immediate contact
with them.''
   Cristiani also said he would create a ``national emergency
program'' to create productive jobs. He did not give specifics.
   Half of the working class does not have full-time jobs.
   Cristiani said particular attention would be paid to the
``poorest of the poor'' and peasant farmers, who make up just more
than half of the population of 5.5 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
