<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-GOP-Ethics 2ndLd-Writethru a0711 06-01 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GOP-Ethics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0711,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican Image Makers Try to Exploit Democrats' Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Brown comment, inserting 3 grafs after 11th graf,
But Rep.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican image makers are moving quickly to
exploit the ethics problems of House Democratic leaders, urging GOP
lawmakers to use them as an argument the Democrats have held
control too long.
   ``Power tends to corrupt, absolute power corrupts absolutely,''
says a briefing paper circulated quietly among Republican
congressmen Wednesday as Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, prepared to
resign.
   The quote from Lord Acton, the 19th century historian, was
accompanied by repeated hints that the answer to the ethics mess
could be a switch from Democratic dominance in the House to
Republican control.
   ``The resignation of two of the top three Democrats in the House
is the bitter fruit of 35 years of Democratic control of that
body,'' said the paper designed to arm GOP lawmakers in the war of
words raging over House ethics.
   It suggested that they say the Wright resignation, only days
after Majority Whip Tony Coelho said he would leave the House
rather than prolong the ethics issue in an expected investigation
of his financial dealings, represented ``a genuinely sad moment in
our nation's history.''
   But it also suggested the Republican House members, who will be
up for re-election next year, give their version of who was at
fault.
   ``Democrats would have the news media and the American people
think that Wright and Coelho's fall has to do with `ethical
McCarthyism' and character assassination,'' said the paper. ``This
is absolutely false. Jim Wright and Tony Coelho's falls were
character suicides.''
   The paper was issued by the National Republican Congressional
Committee, which raises money, prepares statements and videos, does
polling and research and other projects aimed at helping House
Republicans polish their political image. House Democrats and both
parties in the Senate maintain similar committees.
   Committee spokesman John Buckley said he wrote the paper on
Tuesday and it was intended primarily for the eyes of GOP
congressmen. ``Obviously, it wasn't intended to be provided to a
reporter,'' he said.
   House Democratic leader Thomas Foley of Washington, who will
take Wright's place as speaker, called for conciliation Thursday.
   But Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., said of the atmosphere in the
House, ``Democrats are trying to act with restraint ... but there
comes a time when people are going to push back, and push back
awfully hard.''
   In New York, Ronald H. Brown, chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, used a commencement address at Hunter College
to chastise the GOP, though he made no mention of the congressional
committee's paper.
   ``Republican operatives are happy to leave the world of idealism
and progress behid for the cynical world of sound bites and media
manipulation. Not content with the negative ads they used to
cheapen the 1988 presidential campaign, they want to debase all
politics now. Ideas and actions just get in their way,'' Brown said.
   ``Democrats have led the charge for ethics legislation and
campaign finance reform,'' he said. ``Time after time, we proposed
reform legislation. Time after time Republicans fought it.''
   The GOP paper was similar in some ways to dozens of others
turned out by the committee but in this case it documented the
partisan tone that has saturated the debate over House ethics.
   It summarized allegations against Coelho, but did not tackle the
more tangled specifics that led to Wright's resignation.
   It merely advised Republican congressmen to say that the next
speaker ``must address the very real need for reform in the
House.'' Then it returned to its main point: ``The Democrats in the
House have grown arrogant with their unchallenged power.''
   ``Why did two prominent, intelligent members of the Democratic
leadership get into this bind?'' it asked. ``Because there may hae
been a feeling of invulnerability. When you can absue the rights of
the minority ... for as long as they have, there could well be a
feeling that you can do what you want, ethics be damned.''
</TEXT>
