<FIRST>r w AM-JapanFighter     06-01 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan Fighter,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Plans Action on Bill to Restrict FSX-Japan Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Rules Committee cleared the way
Thursday for floor action on a bill to restrict the $6 billion FSX
fighter deal with Japan.
   Under a rule adopted by the panel on a voice vote, the House is
scheduled Tuesday to take up a Senate-passed resolution sponsored
by Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., that sets conditions for
coproduction of the FSX, an advanced version of the U.S. F-16.
   Byrd's measure would prohibit transfer of critical American jet
engine technology to Japan and also would bar Japan from selling or
transferring the FSX or its technology to a third country.
   The Bush administration has voiced strong opposition to the
resolution, saying it would infringe on the president's
constitutional powers to conduct negotiations with foreign nations.
   The House also will consider a substitute measure approved by
the House Foreign Affairs Committee and sponsored by Rep. Stephen
J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the panel's Asian and Pacific
affairs subcommittee.
   Solarz's measure would make two major changes in the Byrd
resolution:
   _On critical engine technology, changing the flat prohibition to
an expression of congressional sentiment that such technology
should not be transferred and giving the House and Senate a chance
to veto the arrangement if a transfer were approved.
   _On sale of the FSX or its technology to a third country,
removing the ban but setting up a mechanism for Congress to
disapprove such a sale if the president were to approve it.
   In addition, the House will consider a non-binding
sense-of-Congress resolution sponsored by Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon,
R-N.Y., expressing disapproval of the FSX agreement.
   Under the deal, General Dynamics would join with Japan's
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to codevelop and coproduce the FSX for
deployment by Japan in the late 1990s. General Dynamics is
headquartered in St. Louis, but most of the FSX work would be done
at its F-16 plant in Fort Worth, Texas.
</TEXT>
