<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     06-01 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Guerrillas Kill 10 Suspected Drug Addicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas killed 10 alleged drug
addicts in a small city in Peru's cocaine-producing jungle,
officials said Thursday.
   The 10, all young men, were killed before dawn Wednesday in
Tarapoto, a town of 35,000 people about 450 miles north of Lima at
the edge of the coca-growing region.
   The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement had distributed leaflets
in Tarapoto two weeks earlier announcing its intention to ``clean
up'' the town.
   The leaflets warned prostitutes, thieves, drug addicts and
homosexuals that they had 15 days to leave town or be killed. The
period elapsed on Tuesday.
   Eight of the victims were found together near the city cemetery,
each shot in the head, a city official said in a telephone
interview.
   The other two were found in the same area by a police patrol
later Wednesday, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity for security reasons.
   The men were said to have attended a party together Tuesday
night.
   The Tupac Amaru band is a pro-Cuban group that surfaced in 1984
and operates separately from, and in competition with, the Shining
Path, a larger Maoist guerrilla movement.
   The Tupac Amaru guerrillas usually engage in urban sabotage
against property and have been considered less violent than the
Shining Path. It began as an urban guerrilla organization, but in
the last two years has expanded into rural areas.
   Estimates of the size of the group range from 500 to 1,500. A
government military patrol near the highland town of Jauja killed
68 Tupac Amaru guerrillas in late April.
   More than 14,000 people have been killed since the Shining Path
began its insurgency in 1980.
</TEXT>
