<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseLeadership 1stLd-Writethru a0674 06-01 0989</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Leadership, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Says ``I Feel Liberated,'' but Leaving Bitterness Behind</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates and reorders thruout with Wright interview, comments
from Gingrich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright proclaimed himself
``liberated'' Thursday after his announcement he will resign from
Congress, while there were clear signs his leaving wouldn't end the
partisan bitterness that focused on his ethics case.
   Wright put the best face on his departure, blaming not only
Republicans for his downfall but also his own inner drive to do too
much too quickly, ``to make things happen in the way that you
believe in.''
   In a lengthy interview, he never suggested he had done anything
wrong.
   His likely successor, Majority Leader Thomas Foley of
Washington, was talking of ways to calm the fractious House and
cool vindictiveness left over from the Wright ethics case.
   ``I think we can turn this mood that has somehow affected the
institution a bit recently back to a strong and healthy one,'' said
Foley, who is virtually certain to be chosen speaker by Democratic
colleagues Tuesday when Wright relinquishes the job.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., was considered the favorite to
replace Foley as majority leader later on, but Rep. Ed Jenkins,
D-Ga., was also seeking fellow Democrats' support.
   Four prominent Democrats were working their House precinct for
the No. 3 spot, now held by Rep. Tony Coelho of California, who
said last weekend he will resign rather than face likely ethics
charges concerning his own financial dealilngs.
   The four: Reps. William Gray of Pennsylvania, David Bonior of
Michigan, Beryl Anthony of Arkansas and Henry Waxman of California.
   While Foley talked of peace, there was evidence a recent
eye-for-an-eye atmosphere was far from gone.
   Republicans circulated a private briefing paper advising their
colleagues on how to best use Wright's problems. In the favorite
argument of GOP Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia, Wright's chief
accuser, the paper contended the Democrats have problems because of
their 35-year tenure in control of the House.
   ``The Democrats in the House have grown arrogant with their
unchallenged power,'' the paper stated, suggesting that exploiting
ethics matters might be a way to help the GOP regain majority
status.
   John Buckley, a spokesman for the National Republican
Congressional Committee, said the GOP was ``fully prepared to take
advantage of the revelations about Democrats,' but he denied there
was any special campaign-style effort to dig up new dirt on the
opposition.
   House members said Thursday that Wright's resignation
announcement had relieved tension, but some also said it was being
replaced by anger _ much of it aimed at Gingrich.
   ``It's a World War I mentality, where anyone who sticks his head
out of the trench might get it shot at next,'' said Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif.
   Gingrich's case is likely to be the next to go before the ethics
panel. He is accused of putting together a partnership to promote a
book he wrote, a venture which employed his wife, and of violating
limits on outside income and prohibitions on receiving gifts over
$100 from people with a direct interest in legislation.
   The issues are strikingly parallel to the Wright case. Gingrich
denies any wrongdoing.
   The Georgian, who had kept silent since hearing Wright's
resignation speech, said Thursday that he had held his tongue at
first because ``I was so angry at the tone of his speech and some
of the things he said.''
   He said Wright's condemnation of ethics accusations and
investigations as ``mindless cannibalism'' was ``an insult to the
ethics committee and every decent person in the House. ... It was
not mindless, it was very serious.''
   Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind., the senior GOP member of the ethics
committee, said he expected the panel still to act next week on
motions made by Wright's lawyers to dismiss the most serious
charges against him. He, too, said he resented Wright's comment.
   ``We're doing our job,'' he said. ``If a member has done wrong,
it's got to be investigated. I do not consider myself
cannibalistic. I resent that comment. ... I'm not going to be
intimidated.''
   Wright, meanwhile said ``I feel liberated'' and planned to ``do
a lot of things I enjoy in life and have been postponing _ to read,
reflect and be with friends in a leisurely setting.''
   He said he planned to do some writing, and some speaking ``if
invited.''
   And he said he hoped his resignation would lead to ``an
abatement of the stridency and the pettiness which has grown up
like weeds in our garden.;;
   In an interview in his office, Wright dated his misfortunes from
Nov. 13, 1987, when he attended a meeting between Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega and Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo in Washington.
   ``From that moment there was nothing but hostility from the
administration,'' Wright said. ``There was a determination on the
part of certain people in the other party to see to it that I was
removed.''
   He said he made up his mind to resign last weekend.
   ``It had come to me ... that it would be unreasonable to expect
to prevail upon the members of the (ethics) committee to see that
they had been in error,'' Wright said. ``Short of an all-out,
harsh, bitter fight on the House floor, it would be unrealistic to
expect a complete exoneration, which is all I was interested in. So
I decided that's one of those things I can't change.''
   During his time as speaker, he said, ``I was probably obsessed
with the notion that I had a limited period of time in which to
make my mark on the future. That was one of my attitudes, perhaps a
failing.''
   He said, ``There has to come an end, there must come an end'' to
the use of ethics as a political weapon. ``Do I believe that's
going to happen overnight because I said it? No, I do not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
