<FIRST>r w AM-China-Wheat     06-01 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Wheat,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Buys Additional 100,000 Metric Tons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporters report that China has bought
an additional 100,000 metric tons of soft red winter wheat, raising
its total tonnage for the new marketing year to 850,000, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Previous purchases for delivery in the year that began June 1
were announced earlier this week and last. In April, China bought
300,000 tons of wheat under the Export Enhancement Program, which
is a government subsidy that discounts the purchase.
   The Agriculture Department estimated the price of the
non-subsidized 550,000 tons of wheat to be about $82.5 million.
   During the last marketing year, China bought 8.3 million metric
tons of wheat, said a department statistician, who noted that the
recent purchases were large for so short a time period.
   Exporters are required to report to USDA export sales of 100,000
metric tons or more of one commodity to a single customer on a
single day.
</TEXT>
