<FIRST>x w AM-IntelligentPhones     06-01 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Intelligent Phones,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY BIZ</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: networQ, 2nd graf, is CQ</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robards, Haley Signed Up To Sell Bell Atlantic Telephone Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Jason Robards and author Alex Haley are
going to try to persuade Bell Atlantic customers they need
``intelligent'' telephone services that can tell them who's calling
before they answer and automatically dial whoever called while they
were in the shower.
   Beginning this week, Robards and Haley will be featured in an
advertising campaign in which they extoll the virtues of Bell
Atlantic's ``Intelligent networQ'' of phone services for businesses
and homes, Bell Atlantic said Thursday.
   The system can display the number of a caller before you answer;
dial back that caller who hung up before you were able to reach the
phone; and screen out people you don't want to talk to. It also
will give customers distinctive rings for certain calls and have as
many as three different telephone numbers ring on one phone.
   ``It will change the way people live and do business by making
communication simpler and easier,'' Christopher E. Clouser, Bell
Atlantic's vice president for corporate relations and advertising,
said of the advanced communications system. ``To convey this
revolutionary concept to consumers we chose two well-known and
well-respected communications experts _ a noted author and an
actor.''
   Haley wrote the book, ``Roots,'' while Robards has had a long
motion picture, television and stage career.
   Bell Atlantic is not the first company to offer these so-called
class services, and to date the public has not rushed out to
embrace them.
   Bell Atlantic's New Jersey subsidiary, New Jersey Bell, began
making such services available in early 1988 but has signed up only
2.4 percent of its 1.3 million customers, The Wall Street Journal
reported last month.
   The newspaper said Southwestern Bell began testing the services
last July in Muskogee, Okla., but despite a heavy promotional
campaign signed up only 7 percent of its customers.
   An earlier generation of custom services have had some success.
After more than a decade, 28.8 percent of Bell customers have call
waiting, 10 percent have call forwarding, and 7.4 percent have
three-way calling.
   Critics say answering machines essentially screen calls or
identify or block unwanted calls. But the phone companies say their
way is easier and more efficient.
   Philadephia-based Bell Atlantic is the parent company of New
Jersey Bell, Bell of Pennsylvania, Diamond State Telephone serving
Delaware and the Chesapeake and Potomac Telephone Cos., which serve
Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland and Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
