<FIRST>r a AM-KermitTrial     06-01 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kermit Trial,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberations Begin in Trial of W.Va.'s Biggest Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<UNK>By KELLY P. KISSEL ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury deliberations began Thursday in
the bank robbery trial of two men, one of whom is also accused of
murdering a gang member to keep him from testifying.
   John P. McCoy, 43, of Slaters Branch, and David Doyle Moore, 27,
of Lovely, are accused of robbing the Matewan National Bank branch
at Kermit on Jan. 3, 1987, making off with $286,000 in what was
West Virginia's largest bank robbery. The pair also is charged with
threatening federal witnesses.
   McCoy is also charged with shooting to death Russell M. Davis,
who was allegedly part of the robbery gang, because he talked to
investigators.
   U.S. Attorney Michael Carey said in closing arguments that
testimony linked McCoy to the robbery, the threats and the death of
Davis.
   Carey said Moore stole the getaway car, took part in the robbery
and went with McCoy to make threats against at least one witness.
   ``You will find that they're not only guilty beyond a reasonable
doubt. They're guilty beyond any doubt,'' Carey said.
   That account was rebutted by defense attorney Roy Hampton,
appointed last Monday to represent McCoy, who previously had
refused government help.
   Hampton said the key government witness, Harold D. ``Boonie''
Runyon, lacked credibility and had changed his story since talking
to the grand jury in an attempt to avoid Kentucky's electric chair.
   Runyon pleaded guilty two weeks ago to killing Davis on a
mountaintop in Kentucky. He charged that McCoy killed Davis with a
shot to the head after Runyon had shot Davis three times in the
back, and testified he had helped bury another man in a separate
incident in Kentucky.
   ``Mr. Runyon was involved in another murder. This is the kind of
person the government is asking you to believe,'' Hampton said.
   J. William Curtis, representing Moore, said the government made
a mistake in its opening argument in saying that it would prove his
client stole a vehicle for the getaway.
   ``He's guilty of no more than being friends with John P.
McCoy,'' Curtis said.
   A jewelry store operator said Moore purchased more than $2,000
in jewelry the afternoon of the robbery, but Curtis said the
jeweler's recollection was wrong. Other witnesses in the trial said
Moore also bought a used car the day of the robbery.
   The trial in federal court began last week under tight security
because of the alleged threats against witnesses. The courtroom
halls were lined with a metal detector, an X-ray machine and a
handful of federal agents.
   The jury was given the case Thursday afternoon and the judge
immediately recessed proceedings until Friday morning.
</TEXT>
