<DOCNO> AP890601-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sugar     06-01 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sugar,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Rules U.S. Violated International Trade Rules on Sugar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international panel has backed an
Australian charge that the United States violated trading rules by
limiting its imports of sugar, the office of U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills said Thursday.
   Last week Ms. Hills cited Japan, Brazil and India as
unreasonably limiting exports from the United States. She acted
under a new U.S. trade law, with the approval of President Bush.
   Christina McCowan, a press officer for Ms. Hills, said the
ruling on sugar will come up at a meeting in Geneva, Switzerland on
June 21. The scene will be a meeting of the council of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), which is an international
organization as well as an agreement.
   GATT permits restrictions on imports only if the importing
country restricts its own production in the same proportion. It is
considered unfair for the limit on imports to be used just as a way
to protect the importing country's own industry or farmers.
   ``We've been increasing our production while cutting our
imports,'' said Tom Hammer, president of the U.S. Sweetener Users
Association.
   American users of sweeteners and sugar exporters in other
countries say the price of sugar in the United States is kept
unreasonably high by government action to protect a small number of
U.S. farmers. The U.S. government last year raised its price to 23
cents a pound. Raw cane sugar sells at about 11 cents a pound on
the world market.
   Hammer said U.S. imports of sugar have been reduced from $1.1
billion worth in 1982 to about $400 million last year. Quotas
specifying how much sugar may be sold in this country are
distributed among 38 countries, including Australia.
   Canada, Argentina and the 12 countries of the European Economic
Community joined Australia in filing a complaint last year. The
panel that ruled against the United States consisted of Poland,
Uruguay and Hong Kong.
   Under GATT rules, the United States or any of the other 96
member governments in the organization could block acceptance of
the sugar panel's ruling. In recent years, however, the United
States and Japan have accepted some adverse rulings. The United
States has been in the forefront of a successful movement to
tighten the system for settling disputes under GATT.
   In two other pending cases the administration has accepted an
adverse ruling but no change has been made in the practises
complained of, because Congress had not acted to change the law.
   GATT rules also call for the country found in violation to offer
compensation to the country whose exports have been restricted.
Compensation usually takes the form of a reduced tariff in the
country found at fault on other goods of the complaining country,
or some measure that also increases the complaining country's
exports.
</TEXT>
