<FIRST>r w AM-GrayInvestigation     06-01 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gray Investigation,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michel Joins Democrat Gray in Protesting Leaks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel asked the
attorney general Thursday to ``weigh very carefully'' Democratic
Rep. William Gray's request for an independent counsel into leaked
information leading to stories that Gray is under federal
investigation.
   Michel, sounding as angry as Gray about the leaks, wrote
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, ``I must believe that you are as
upset as I am over any improper disclosure of information.''
   Gray, the fourth-ranking Democrat who is running for the No. 3
majority whip's position, also continued on the offensive in
denying reports that he had had any absentee workers on his payroll.
   Government sources, speaking only on condition they not be
named, said there is a preliminary inquiry into allegations of
employment practices and expenditures on Gray's staff, including
allegations that the lawmaker hired a ``ghost'' employee.
   ``There are and were no `ghost', `no-show' or `absentee'
emplouyees on my House or committee payrolls,'' said Gray, who was
chairman of the House Budget Committee prior to the current
congressional session.
   Gray has asked Thornburgh to appoint an independent counsel to
investigate the leaks ``and the motivations of this so-called
investigation arranged to occur just as I was seeking a leadership
position in the Democratic Party.''
   He called Thornburgh's promise to have an in-house
investigatiion ``insufficient.''
   Gray also gave reporters affidavits from all his employees, who
provided details on the work they do for Congress.
   Michel, R-Ill., told Thornburgh he was ``very dismayed'' to hear
news reports of allegations against Gray, ``which were apparently
based on information from the Justice Department investigators and
the office of the U.S. attorney in Philadelphia. It is just hard to
imagine anything more irreponsible.''
   He said if there ``is the slightest doubt that a complete
investigation cannot be completed, then I urge you to weigh very
seriously the request you apparently have for an independent
investigation.''
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel said, ``We have
confidence that this matter can be investigated here in this
department.''
   ``Previously, the attorney general has made known his views of
independent counsels to the point of suspending the order which
would have, ironically, provided for the appointment of independent
counsels for some of these matters that have been subject of
leaks,'' Runkel said.
   Runkel was referring to an order issued by Thornburgh's
predecessor, Edwin Meese III, mandating appointment of independent
counsels for investigations of members of Congress.
</TEXT>
