<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0752 06-01 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0752,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputies Say Soviet Version of Baltics Is a Lie</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to include background on German-Soviet pact.
Mihhail cq in 15th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another attack on official history, two
deputies told the Soviet Congress on Thursday the Baltic republics
were taken by force and the approved version that they joined the
Soviet Union voluntarily is a lie.
   Other stinging commentary during the session included an attack
on Poliburo member Yegor K. Ligachev, who was accused of being
incompetent to run Soviet agriculture and end chronic food
shortages.
   Dissident historian Roy Medvedev took the podium during
nationally televised debate and said the official version of Soviet
absorption of the three Baltic republics in 1940 was not true.
   ``Up to now, in our history books, we have said Estonia, Latvia
and Lithuania voluntarily joined the Soviet Union and that it was a
popular revolution, there was no violence and it was a declaration
of free will,'' he told the deputies.
   That, Medvedev said, was ``a lie.''
   Many deputies reacted with noisy anger and denials. Then
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev declared his support for an
investigation of the allegations, and the 2,250-member Congress of
People's Deputies assented without a vote.
   Gorbachev also implied the Hitler-Stalin pact of 1939, which
doomed Baltic sovereignty, might be a forgery.
   He said neither the Soviet Union nor West Germany possesses an
original. ``There are copies _ of what I do not know,'' Gorbachev
said.
   One cause for skepticism, he told the assembly, is the fact that
Vyacheslav Molotov's signature on the copy is in German rather than
Russian. Molotov, then foreign minister, negotiated the
non-aggression treaty with his German counterpart, Joachim von
Ribbentrop.
   Latvian deputy Jemma Skulma said later the original is not
needed to prove the Soviets used force. ``I was there,'' the
graying artist said.
   Gorbachev said he did not believe Baltic charges _ with which
Western historians agree _ that Nazi dictator Adolf Hitler and
Soviet dictator Josef Stalin divided Poland and gave the Baltics to
the Soviet Union in a secret part of the agreement.
   He said he supported an investigation ``because the Baltics are
in turmoil discussing these matters, and it is doubted that there
was a desire of the people to join the Soviet Union.''
   It is a burning issue in Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia, where
tens of thousands of people were deported and died in the 1940s and
1950s. Mass movements in the republics are using Gorbachev's
reforms to press for independence.
   The United States never recognized the Soviet takeover of the
Baltic states and still accredits their old embassies in Washington.
   Behind the scenes, economist Mihhail Bronstein of Estonia said
Gorbachev offered his support to Estonia's economic plan to
legalize small-scale private property and give itself control of
its industry and resources.
   During the session, heads swiveled toward Ligachev as deputy
Yuri D. Chernichenko took the podium and began his scathing
assessment of Ligachev's performance as head of a new party
commission on agriculture. Ligachev, a conservative who is
considered a rival to Gorbachev, sat impassively with other members
of the ruling Poliburo.
   Such remarks were never heard in the old parliament, the Supreme
Soviet, which even party leaders and parliamentarians now admit was
a mere rubber-stamp body.
   ``Why is this politically significant branch, the branch which
determines the future, ruled by a person who does not understand
anything about it and who failed in the field of ideology?''
Chernichenko asked.
   Ligachev was named head of the commission in September after
being relieved of the ideology portfolio, the position that once
made him the No. 2 Kremlin leader.
   Nothing in Ligachev's background marks him as a specialist on
farming. He attended an institute on aircraft construction.
   Because of the nation's dependence on imports of consumer goods
and food, it has the reputation of an ``international sponger,''
said Chernichenko, a television commentator who specializes in
agriculture and rural issues.
   Expensive projects in a deficit-ridden economy also were a
common complaint Thursday, and some of Gorbachev's reforms came
under attack.
   Deputy Vitaly Kanishev received wild applause when he said new
private cooperatives ``not only get their hands into our pockets,
they undress us and want to kill us too.''
   ``How much does the maintenance of 18 million bureaucrats cost,
and the war in Afghanistan, support for Cuba, Nicaragua,
Ethiopia?'' asked deputy Vasily Belov. ``How much is the space
program? How much are our grandiose festivals, Olympic games,
various forums?''
   Nearly 50 deputies led by populist Boris Yeltsin and economist
Gavril Popov proposing increasing the minimum pension to 80 rubles,
or $121, a month.
   They also called for a system of guaranteeing of food products
at state prices to retirees, invalids and families with incomes of
less than $106 a month per person.
   The inaugural session of the Congress was to have ended
Wednesday, but more than 500 people were still seeking the floor
Thursday, and the state broadcasting authority said it would
continue its live broadcasts of the proceedings next week.
</TEXT>
