<FIRST>r w AM-US-Thailand     06-01 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Thailand,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Presses Thailand on Workers in Libya</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is continuing to press
Thailand about repatriating some 270 of its citizens who work at a
Libyan chemical weapons production plant, State Department sources
said Thursday.
   So far, the Thai government has refused to take action on the
U.S. requests, which have been made over the past several months.
   ``We've made our concerns known through the appropriate
officials ... and not at a low level,'' said the official, who
spoke on condition of not being identified by name.
   There are estimates that between 25,000 and 75,000 Thais work in
Libya. Workers from many Asian nations have sought employment in
the Middle East, where they can obtain higher-paying jobs than in
their homelands.
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has threatened action against
other Thais in Libya if the workers at the chemical plant leave.
   The plant has been identified by U.S. officials as the largest
single chemical weapons facility in the Third World.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher, asked about the
matter, said the United States has often expressed its concern
about the plant, and ``called on all nations to ensure that their
firms and individuals are not contributing to the Libyan chemical
weapons program.''
   ``The Royal Thai government is well aware of our views on this
issue and is aware, as many other governments are, of our serious
concerns about the presence of workers at Rabta, including Thai
workers,'' Boucher said.
   The spokesman refused to confirm that there have been repeated
U.S. requests of late on the matter, saying only, ``We've had
discussions with the Thai government, as well as other governments,
and we hope that the Thai government and other governments will
continue to take action to deny foreign support to this plant.''
</TEXT>
