<FIRST>u a AM-ListArrest 1stLd-Writethru a0734 06-01 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-List Arrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0734,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect in 1971 Murders Arrested, FBI Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `A preliminary...,' with 7 grafs to UPDATE
with details from List's arraignment, FBI search for him. Picks up penultimate
graf, `Westfield's former...' SUBS 4th graf, `On or...,' to clarify that
neighbors saw light bulbs burning out.' ^By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who has been a suspect since 1971 in
the shooting deaths of his wife, mother and three children was
arrested Thursday, less than two weeks after the show ``America's
Most Wanted'' featured the case.
   John List, 63, who had been living under an assumed name, was
arrested without incident at his job in Richmond, Va., said FBI
agent Terry T. O'Connor of the bureau's Richmond office.
   List, who has been working as an accountant under the name
Robert P. Clark, was positively identified through fingerprints,
O'Connor said. He was charged with five counts of first-degree
murder and was being held at the Henrico County Jail. U.S.
Magistrate David G. Lowe scheduled a bond hearing for Monday.
   On or about Nov. 9, 1971, List is believed to have shot and
killed his mother, wife and three children at his Westfield, N.J.,
home, authorities allege. The bodies were not discovered until Dec.
7, 1971, after neighbors saw light bulbs burning out in the house
and summoned police. The neighbors had presumed the Lists were on
vacation when they hadn't seen them for a month.
   List left a five-page letter confessing to the murders of
Patricia, 16, John Jr., 15, Frederick, 13, his wife, Helen, 45, and
mother, Alma, 85. All had been shot with a 9mm automatic or a
.22-caliber pistol.
   After the slayings, investigators found that List had two
mortgages on his house, was failing as a financial consultant and
had been siphoning money from his mother's $200,000 savings account.
   As many as 20 FBI agents worked on the case. There were numerous
leads, but authorities said the trail went cold six years ago.
   But since the case was featured May 21 on Fox-TV's ``America's
Most Wanted'' program, the FBI received more than 200 tips,
including one that said a man named Bob Clark who resembled List
was living in Midlothian, a Richmond suburb, O'Connor said.
   After receiving the tip, FBI agents went to List's home and
questioned his wife, whom he met at a Lutheran church event in the
Denver area in 1977 and married four years ago. Her name was being
withheld.
   ``She has been very cooperative,'' said John C. McGinley, head
of the FBI's Newark office. ``She was unaware of his background.''
   McGinley said agents determined Clark was their man because,
like List, he had a scar behind his right ear.
   A man at the accounting firm of Maddrea, Joyner, Kirkham &amp; Woody
said List worked there as a staff accountant.
   ``He was a nice fellow, almost too nice to be true,'' said the
man, who would not reveal his name. ``He even had a Fraternal Order
of Police sticker on his car.''
   At his arraignment, the former fugitive spoke in a low, husky
voice as he asked Lowe for a court-appointed attorney. The
magistrate refused the request, noting that List earned $2,000 a
month as an accountant and had about $1,200 in a bank account.
   List later retained an attorney, Joel G. Clarke of Richmond.
``He can't talk to anybody,'' Clarke told reporters outside the
jail.
   Westfield's former police chief, James Moran, said he expected
List to be caught only after the case became nationally known
through television or newspapers. Moran said he still carried a
wanted poster of List with him.
   ``I'll gladly tear it up now,'' he said.
</TEXT>
