<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     06-01 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Says Police Organized, Instructed Assassination Team</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-described African National
Congress guerrilla testified Thursday that police recruited ANC
defectors, put them in small units and sent them on missions to
kill suspected members of the ANC.
   In other developments on Thursday:
   _Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other anti-apartheid church leaders
asked foreign bankers to refuse to reschedule South Africa's debt
payments unless the white-dominated government makes major
political concessions. An interim debt agreement expires on June
30, 1990, and South Africa faces payments of at least $8 billion by
1991 unless new terms are established.
   _Black labor leader Donsie Khumalo, who staged a 26-hour sit-in
at the British Embassy on March 29-30 to protest restrictions
placed on him by police, was arrested Thursday for violating those
restrictions, police said. They said that during the sit-in,
Khumalo did not report twice daily to a police station, was not at
his home at night, and did not restrict his political activities.
   At a highly publicized terrorism trial at Cape Town Supreme
Court, Bongani Jonas testified that he heard of two
police-recruited assassination units, known as the Askari group, or
the A-Team, after he was shot and arrested by an A-Team member near
Cape Town on Sept. 17, 1987.
   He said A-Team members boasted they carried out killings of
suspected ANC members in Botswana and black townships outside Cape
Town.
   Jonas testified that after he was arrested, police interrogated
him for hours, periodically jumping on his leg that had been
fractured by a bullet.
   He said A-Team members were among the interrogators and tried to
recruit him to the police unit, saying he would receive a house if
he joined.
   Jonas said he pretended to cooperate because he feared the
authorities would kill him. He said he told police he would join
the A-Team and testify against 14 suspected ANC members accused of
bombings in Cape Town.
   But when Jonas was called as a state witness in April, he
refused to testify, saying he remained loyal to the ANC, the
outlawed guerrilla group trying to undermine the white-dominated
government.
   ``The struggle for freedom is the law of nature, and to act
against the law of nature is to act against God himself,'' Jonas
told the court Thursday. ``That I will never do.''
   The 14 defendants include men, women, blacks, whites and people
of mixed-race. One white defendant is the daughter of a top-ranking
university administrator.
   Jonas has not been charged in the case. He testified Thursday to
explain why he decided not to serve as a state witness.
</TEXT>
