<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-01 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Roll Through Upper Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain fell from Oklahoma and Louisiana to northern Indiana
on Thursday as thunderstorms developed along a broad cold front
stretching from Texas across the lower Great Lakes.
   A heat wave, meanwhile, toppled temperature records along the
East Coast.
   Thunderstorms were scattered from western Oklahoma and
north-central Texas across northern Illinois to northern Ohio on
Thursday afternoon.
   Hail as big as golf balls and torrential rains fell in northern
Indiana, flooding expressways and campgrounds, knocking out power
to thousands of residents and pushing rivers and streams beyond
their banks.
   Flash flood watches also were posted in southern Lower Michigan
and northern Ohio.
   Thunderstorms brought showers from eastern Texas to the central
Gulf Coast. The Southeast had widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms, while sunny skies prevailed in the West and
north-central states.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT
included more than an inch at Tinker Air Force Base in Oklahoma
City, eight-tenths of an inch at Lafayette, La., and South Bend,
Ind., and seven-tenths of an inch at Houston.
   Temperatures reaching or breaking records for the date included
98 in Baltimore, 94 in Greer, S.C., 94 in Newark, N.J., 95 in
Raleigh, N.C., 95 in Richmond, Va., and 92 at Washington-Dulles
International Airport. Huron, S.D., tied its low for the date of 36
degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 98 degrees at Fort Belvoir,
Va. The low for the nation Thursday morning was 24 degrees at
Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Friday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms across much of the nation east of the Rockies, with
showers and thunderstorms most likely from Oklahoma to Ohio and
West Virginia. The West was expected to have fair to partly sunny
skies.
   Temperatures were predicted to reach the 90s in the Southwest
deserts and from the Rio Grande Valley of Texas to the southern
Atlantic Coast, and the 70s from New England to the upper
Mississippi Valley and from the northern and central Plains to
Washington. Highs elsewhere were expected in the 80s.
</TEXT>
