<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-01 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Will Ask Indian Troops to Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa said
Thursday he will ask India to withdraw its troops next month, two
years after they arrived to disarm Tamil guerrillas under an
agreement to end the ethnic civil war.
   ``I would like to see the last of the Indian troops leave Sri
Lanka by the end of July,'' he told a Buddhist gathering at a
temple in Battaramula, seven miles southeast of Colombo.
   The first Indian soldiers arrived July 30, 1987, hours after
Premadasa's predecessor, Junius R. Jayewardene, and Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi signed the peace accord.
   Its purpose was to end years of rebellion by Tamils seeking an
independent homeland. The war began in 1982 and has claimed 9,000
lives.
   India became involved because it is the major power in the
region and has a Tamil population of about 60 million.
   The number of Indian soldiers grew from the initial 3,000 to
70,000 as confrontations increased with Tamil militants who did not
accept the peace agreement. An estimated 45,000 Indian soldiers
remain in northern and eastern Sri Lanka, where most Tamils live.
   More than 700 Indian soldiers have been killed.
   ``India's action to call back the peacekeeping force during the
next two months will be considered as a favor,'' Premadasa said.
``I have no doubt that India will do so.''
   Since assuming office five months ago, Premadasa has repeatedly
said he wants Indian soldiers to withdraw, but had not set a
timetable.
   Referring to a summit of seven South Asian nations scheduled for
Colombo later this year, Premadasa said Sri Lanka cannot host such
a meeting ``when a foreign army is operating in the country.''
   He said Sri Lanka was grateful for the sacrifices made by India,
but ``we will be also grateful if India agrees to withdraw its
troops from the country.''
   From the outset of its involvement, India has said it had no
plans to remain in Sri Lanka indefinitely.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, make up about 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people and claim discrimination by the
predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese majority. Premadasa is Sinhalese,
as was Jayewardene.
   The most powerful rebel group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, backed out of the peace agreement and continued the
guerrilla war. Premadasa opened negotiations with the Tigers after
offering them amnesty and seats in Parliament.
   Sinhalese radicals oppose overtures to the Tamils and embarked
on their own campaign of violence soon after the peace accord was
signed.
   Police said Sinhalese militants killed six people Thursday in
three separate attacks. Among the victims were Bennet Perera, chief
of a special police unit investigating Sinhalese radicals, and his
chauffeur.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
