<HEAD>Bush Nominating Former Movie Star as Envoy to Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has selected Shirley Temple Black,
America's best-know child actor in the 1930s and 1940s, as the new
ambassador to Czechoslovakia, the White House said Thursday.
   Ms. Black, 61, has held a number of government posts since her
Hollywood days. She was ambassador to Ghana from 1974 to 1976.
   She also served as White House chief of protocol in 1976-77 and
as special representative to the United Nations in 1969-70.
   The nomination, which will require Senate confirmation, was
announced here during a two-night stop by Bush on a European tour.
   In other personnel action, Bush said he will nominate:
   _Timothy B. Atkeson to be assistant administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency for international activities. He
currently is a partner in a Washington law firm.
   _C. Howard Wilkins to be ambassador to the Netherlands. Wilkins
is the founder of a development corporation and head of a
restaurant corporation.
   _Morris D. Busby to be accorded rank of ambassador during his
service as the administration's coordinator for counter terrorism.
Busby has been roving ambassador and special envoy for Central
America since 1987.
   Bush also announced that Michael Ussery will remain as
ambassador to Morocco and Richard W. Boehm will remain as
ambassador to Oman.
