<FIRST>r a AM-Linares-Drugs     06-01 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Linares-Drugs,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Disconnected Son's Life-Support Taken to Hospital for Drug
Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CICERO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who sparked a national debate when he
disconnected his comatose son's life-support system at gunpoint was
taken to a hospital Thursday for a violent reaction to an illegal
drug, police said.
   Rudy Linares, a 23-year-old house painter, was discharged later
in the day after a medical evaluation, said Mac Neal Memorial
Hospital spokeswoman Diane Laux.
   Officers were dispatched to the Linares' home early Thursday
after paramedics requested help, said Cicero Deputy Police
Superintendent Steve Zalas.
   Detective Ronald Mersch described Linares as ``wild, like an
epileptic would be.''
   ``Mr. Linares told one of the officers he'd taken some bad
PCP,'' Zalas said. PCP is the hallucinogen phencyclidine, known on
the street as angel dust, a drug with both stimulating and
depressing effects.
   Zalas said Linares told officers, ``What would you do if your
son just died?''
   ``He was kind of combative,'' Zalas said. ``... There was a
confrontation and he had to be handcuffed before we could put him
on a stretcher.''
   Zalas said officers did not find any drugs in the apartment.
   In April, Linares was charged with murder after he pulled a
handgun in a hospital where his 15-month-old son was being kept,
ordered staff from the room, and then unhooked the life-support
system.
   He cradled his son, Samuel, in his arms about 30 minutes until
he was certain the boy was dead.
   Prosecutors decided they would not pursue the murder charge
after a Cook County grand jury refused to indict Linares on May 19.
   The boy had been in a coma, considered irreversible by doctors,
since choking on a balloon nine months earlier. The hospital,
Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center, had refused family
requests to withdraw life support, saying the child was not brain
dead.
   Linares and his wife have two other children.
   Neighbors said the latest incident caught them by surprise.
   ``It might have been eating him up on the inside, but he didn't
show it on the outside,'' said Kevin Camarena.
   ``All his bereavement was built up inside because he was so
composed,'' said another neighbor, Bernice Kield. ``It was just
bottled up and it exploded.''
</TEXT>
