<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Landsat     06-01 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Landsat,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Approves Funds for Landsat Satellites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush announced Thursday he had approved
funding for continued operations of two existing Landsat satellites
and for the completion and launch of a third satellite that takes
close-range pictures of Earth.
   The announcement was made by the traveling White House while
Bush was at dinner with British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on
the final evening of his four-country trip to Europe.
   The president's action saves the satellites from extinction.
They had been turned over to private industry in 1985, but the
company formed to sell the images was unable to make the venture
pay even with government help.
   Spot, a French satellite, is capable of taking even better
images than Landsat and has captured much of the market for remote
sensing.
   The Commerce Department announced earlier this year that it had
no funds to continue operating the satellite and planned to shut it
down. Vice President Dan Quayle, head of the National Space
Council, stepped in and urged the president to find money to give
the satellites a new lease on life.
   The White House announcement said continued operation of
Landsats 4 and 5 will require an additional $5 million this fiscal
year and $19 million next year. Cost of completion and launch of
Landsat 6 by 1991 has already been included in the Commerce
Department budget.
   ``Over recent years it has become increasingly evident that
commercializing the entire Landsat program would not be feasible
until at least the end of the century,'' the statement said.
   Landsat images have been used since 1972 to evaluate Earth
resources and soil moisture and search for oil and other minerals.
</TEXT>
