<DOCNO> AP890601-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BlastTest     06-01 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blast Test,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Designed To Test Blast On Structures, Equipment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIE AICHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blast of 2,440 tons of
ammonium nitrate and fuel oil rocked the White Sands Missile Range
Thursday in a simulation of the effects of a nuclear explosion.
   The test, called Miser's Gold, was the fifth in a series of
non-nuclear explosions set off since 1976 by the Defense Nuclear
Agency. It is intended to show what happens to military and
civilian equipment during and after a large explosion.
   The blast was the equivalent of a 4-kiloton nuclear device. By
comparison, the atomic bomb that devastated Hiroshima, Japan, in
August 1945 had a force of 13 kilotons.
   Miser's Gold includes 180 experiments by the United States and
five foreign countries intended to test the effects of air blast
and ground shock on such things as bunkers, underground shelters
and radar.
   Navy Cmdr. J.R. Lund of the agency's Test Directorate called the
test an unqualified success.
   However, he said it will take several months to evaluate what
was learned from all the experiments set up on the 120-acre test
bed.
   Canada, Switzerland, Norway, Sweden and the United Kingdom
mostly tested civilian equipment, while the United States
concentrated on military systems, Lund said.
   ``The foreign countries are really into testing civil defense
shelters,'' he said.
   ``I think they feel they are more at risk,'' he added.
   About 125 people gathered in the southern New Mexico desert to
witness the blast, which was delayed 30 minutes before being
detonated at 9:30 a.m.
   At T minus one minute, onlookers who sat six miles north of
ground zero readied themselves and most inserted earplugs to deaden
the anticipated blast.
   A huge cloud of brown smoke formed a distorted mushroom against
the background of the blue sky and mountains. About 25 seconds
later, the shock wave could be felt by the spectators on the
bleachers while at the same moment a loud muffled boom rocked the
area.
   The boom was followed by cheers from the crowd.
   ``This is fun to look at, but the real work begins now,'' said
Lt. Col. Al Schenker of the Defense Nuclear Agency.
   Seven missiles were launched within one minute of the detonation
and flew through the brown cloud. The missiles will be tested for
erosion.
   Schenker said the test bed, including bunkers, rooms and other
structures, cost $2.65 million and took 14 months to build.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
