<FIRST>r w AM-HHS-Fulton     06-01 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HHS-Fulton,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fulton Drops Out of Consideration for HHS Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Fulton, opposed by a group of Senate
conservatives and right-to-life advocates, dropped out of
consideration Thursday for a top welfare post in the Bush
administration.
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis W. Sullivan, who had
wanted Fulton to head the Family Services Administration which
manages the government's major welfare programs, said he accepted
Fulton's decision with ``profound regret.''
   ``I have requested my name be withdrawn, but, of course, I don't
do that with any joy,'' Fulton, Oklahoma's social services
secretary, told The Associated Press.
   In a statement issued by his office, Sullivan said Fulton would
have ``done an outstanding job'' as an assistant secretary in the
federal department.
   Sullivan said he would continue to review other candidates for
the position and would make a recommendation to President Bush ``as
quickly as possible.''
   Fulton was opposed by some right-to-life groups who criticized
his action when, as director of the Oklahoma human services
department, he became aware of a state hospital policy of
withholding life-saving care from babies with the crippling
deformity spina bifida.
   Trying to fend off the criticism, Fulton had said that after
learning of the policy, he put into effect regulations requiring
medical treatment for all infants unless it would be futile or
would shorten the baby's life.
   But critics said protections he instituted were required by
federal law and they said doctors involved were never sanctioned.
   ``He took only the most superficial investigation, did not speak
to any of the doctors and did not hold anyone accountable,'' said
Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., who last month sent Bush a letter
signed by five other conservative senators opposing Fulton.
   ``I am relieved that the nomination will not be made,'' said
Humphrey.
   ``He demonstrated an insensitivity to the right to life of
handicapped infants,'' said Douglas Johnson, legislative director
for the National Right-to-Life Committee.
   ``We felt it was inappropriate to put someone like that in a
senior policy position of a pro-life administration,'' added
Johnson in a telephone interview.
   ``The most disturbing thing about it is the influence of the
special interest groups'' on the administration, Fulton said
concerning his withdrawal.
</TEXT>
