<FIRST>u i AM-Peru 1stLd-Writethru a0787 06-01 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0787,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Prominent Peruvian Journalist</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with noted journalist killed, other detail.
ADDS byline. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas killed Peru's leading writer
on the environment along with a government agronomist Thursday, and
pro-Cuban rebels killed 10 men as drug addicts in a jungle town,
officials said.
   Journalist Barbara D'Achille and agronomist Esteban Bohorquez
were killed after Shining Path guerrillas stopped their
government-owned pickup truck on a mountain road in the highlands
150 miles southeast of Lima, reported El Comercio, the newspaper
for which she worked.
   The government meanwhile expanded the area under military
control Thursday to include all of Ucayali state and part of Loreto
state in the eastern jungle. Nine of Peru's 24 states now are under
states of emergency that give control to the military as part of
the counterinsurgency effort.
   Ms. D'Achille, 45, and Bohorquez, who worked for a state
development corporation, were shot near Huancavelica. The gunmen
spared the driver and another passenger but blew up the truck,
according to the report.
   A senior editor at the newspaper, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the writer was traveling in the region to gather
information for a story on alpacas, llamas and vicunas _ highland
pack animals used for their wool.
   Ms. D'Achille, a naturalized Peruvian born in the Soviet Union,
had worked for the newspaper five years and was recognized as
Peru's leading writer on this country's ecology and environment.
   At least 15 journalists have been assassinated since Peru's
leftist insurgency began in 1980. More than 14,000 people in all
have been killed.
   On Wednesday, 10 young men were killed before dawn in Tarapoto,
a jungle town of 35,000 people about 450 miles north of Lima at the
edge of the country's coca-growing region.
   The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement distributed leaflets in
Tarapoto two weeks earlier announcing its intention to ``clean up''
the town, the largest in San Martin state. The leaflets warned
prostitutes, thieves, drug addicts and homosexuals they had 15 days
to leave town or be killed.
   The 15-day period lapsed Tuesday.
   Eight victims were found together near the city cemetery, each
shot in the head, a city official told the AP in a telephone
interview. He said a police patrol found the other two in the same
area later in the day. The official spoke on condition of not being
identified, citing security reasons.
   The 10 young men were said to have attended a party together
Tuesday night.
   The Tupac Amaru band is a pro-Cuba group that surfaced in 1984
and operates separately from the Shining Path and in competition
with it.
   The pro-Cuban guerrillas usually engaged in urban sabotage
against property and rarely killed civilians. The group began as an
urban guerrilla organization, but in the last two years expanded
into rural areas.
   Estimates of the organization's size range from 500 to 1,500.
   In late April, a military patrol wiped out a column of 68 Tupac
Amaru guerrillas near the highland town of Jauja.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0254 </DOCNO>
