<FIRST>r a AM-PoisonedBaby 1stLd-Writethru a0696 06-01 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poisoned Baby, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Charged with Murder 5 Years After Infant Son Was Poisoned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Quentin, meanwhile...,' to CORRECT spelling
of Quinten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTH CHICAGO, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who claimed their infant son
was the victim of product tampering have been charged with murder,
accused of forcing the child to drink baby formula laced with acid,
prosecutors said Thursday.
   ``It's a case that's been on my mind for five years,'' said
Matthew Chancey, assistant Lake County state's attorney.
   Shelia Smith, 26, and Ricky Irby Sr., 29, were each charged in a
grand jury indictment with a single count of murder and put in jail
in lieu of $1 million bonds ordered Thursday by Lake County
Associate Judge Harry Hartel.
   On May 31, 1984, the parents were charged with abuse in a
juvenile petition after bringing their 3-month-old son, Quinten
Irby, to a hospital and claiming he had been poisoned by drinking
baby formula, Chancey said.
   Tests on the boy's stomach found high concentrations of a
substance believed to be pure sulfuric acid. But much of the
evidence gathered during the original investigation _ cans of
formula, a baby bottle and a nipple _ was lost at the Illinois
Department of Public Health laboratory, where it was sent for
analysis.
   Chancey said prosecutors decided not to pursue the case after
the loss of the evidence.
   Quintin, meanwhile, lingered near death for more than two years
with severe burn scars on his mouth and trachea. He also had one
lung removed and was kept on a ventilator until his August 1986
death at Children's Memorial Hospital in Chicago.
   ``He was unable to swallow, to breathe or to speak,'' Chancey
recalled.
   ``The nature of the crime ... the setback after we lost much of
the evidence, the frustration for a long time that we wouldn't be
able to indict anyone. I carried all those things around for a long
time,'' he said.
   A break for prosecutors came in November when the U.S. Supreme
Court, in an Arizona case, ruled that evidence lost accidentally
does not prevent prosecution.
   ``Immediately after that this case popped into my mind,''
Chancey said. ``I started thinking, `Maybe we can do this.'''
   Chancey said that prior to a trial of the case he would not
discuss whether he believes money was the motive for the poisoning.
   Irby filed a lawsuit in August 1987, charging negligence against
the baby formula maker, Abbott Laboratories of North Chicago, and
the grocery store where he said the formula was bought.
   The lawsuit claimed the Similac with Iron formula the couple
gave to Quinten contained a ``foreign and dangerous acidic and-or
lye substance'' and was ``unfit for human consumption.''
   Irby withdrew the lawsuit a year ago.
   ``We're not sure why that was,'' Abbott spokeswoman Cathy
Babington said Thursday. ``As I recall, there were never any
pleadings in the case when it was withdrawn.''
   A county grand jury heard evidence for four weeks before
returning the indictment Wednesday.
   Chancey said the parents have an 8-year-old son, Ricky Jr. He
said both are unemployed, although Irby has worked at area
automobile plants.
   Neither Ms. Smith nor Irby was represented by an attorney,
though Irby has retained one and Ms. Smith told Hartel she would
have one by Wednesday's scheduled arraignment.
</TEXT>
