<SECOND>AM-Gephardt-Leadership, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0800,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gephardt Appeals to Democrats to Elect Him Majority Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Gephardt interview comments, INSERTS four grafs
after 5th graf pvs, ``Gephardt, who;'' and one graf after 7th graf pvs,
``Some Democrats,</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt appealed to Democratic
colleagues Thursday to elect him majority leader as part of a ``new
generation'' to take control of the House.
   ``John Kennedy said in 1961 that it was time for a new
generation of Americans to lead our country. Now I believe it is
time for a new generation of members to lead the Congress,''
Gephardt, 48, said in a letter to House Democrats.
   The Missouri congressman noted that, like himself, two-thirds of
current House members have been elected since 1978, and he
described the Democrats as a ``young and vibrant majority.''
   The seven-term lawmaker is campaigning for the No. 2 House
leadership spot to replace Rep. Tom Foley, who is expected to
become speaker next week now that Speaker Jim Wright has announced
his resignation.
   Gephardt, who ran for president in 1988, is considered the
front-runner in the leadership race although he is opposed by Rep.
Ed Jenkins, D-Ga.
   In an interview, Gephardt said he was ``encouraged'' by support
he had already received from Democrats but would not predict
victory.
   ``The feedback has been positive, but I'm surely not prepared to
say that we've done it,'' said Gephardt.
   He made clear that his candidacy, in contrast to Jenkins', was
based on the generational appeal to Democrats as well his
experiences as a television-age presidential candidate and in
previous leadership posts in the House, including four years as
party caucus chairman.
   ``I think I learned how to put together coalitions in the House
so we can reach consensus in the Congress and be able to assert a
policy,'' said Gephardt. ``I also have learned something about
conveying an issue to voters in the country at large.''
   The Missourian confirmed in the letter that he would not seek
the 1992 presidential nomination if he becomes majority leader but
would ``devote all of my energies to the work of the House.'' He
said he had been ``seriously considering'' another run for the
White House, and said it was a difficult decision to seek the House
post.
   Some Democrats were annoyed at Gephardt's prolonged absence from
the House during last year's presidential campaign, when he was
head of the party caucus, the No. 4 leadership job. He no longer
holds that post.
   ``I am not going to use a House leadership position as a
stepping stone to something else,'' Gephardt said. ``I haven't said
this about '92 because I thought it was necessary to get elected
but because I believe that you can't do two things at once of this
magnitude.''
   In his letter, Gephardt echoed Wright's call for an end to
partisan bloodletting over ethics and said lawmakers must ``get
back to the peoples' business.''
   ``There are too many urgent needs facing our nation for us to
engage in retribution and unnecessary partisanship,'' Gephardt
wrote.
   ``It will be my goal, working with Tom Foley and with each of
you, to help shape and implement a legislative agenda that
addresses the nation's most serious concerns.''
   He cited health care, housing, education and ``economic
security'' as pressing topics before Congress.
   Gephardt said he was ``not interested in wallowing in rumor or
engaging in partisan intrigue.''
   His supporters view his as ``squeaky clean,'' certified by a
presidential campaign as free of any potential ethical problems to
cause the party further embarrassment.
   Gephardt jumped into the leadership race on Saturday after Rep.
Tony Coelho, D-Calif., the majority whip, announced his resignation
from the House in order to avoid a lengthy investigation into his
own personal finances.
</TEXT>
