<FIRST>r a AM-O'Connor-Lebanon     06-01 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-O'Connor-Lebanon,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>O'Connor Told He Was On A Hit List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor said he canceled his trip
to Moslem West Beirut during a three-day visit to Lebanon because
he was told he was on a hit list, according to a televised
interview.
   First on the list was Sheik Hassan Khaled, spiritual leader of
Lebanon's Sunni Moslems, who was killed May 17 by a car bomb,
O'Connor told WNBC-TV news in an interview broadcast Thursday.
   ``It was purported that he was to be the first of five on a hit
list and then the assumption was that I might well be No. 2,''
O'Connor said.
   The last visitors Khaled received before his death were people
who came to arrange a meeting between O'Connor and Khaled, the
cardinal said in the interview.
   Asked if he courts martyrdom, O'Connor laughed and said:
``Listen, I try to stay alive even in New York. I'm not a hero, no,
there's nothing heroic at all about me. I'm your basic coward.''
   During his 27 years as a chaplain in the Navy and Marines, the
cardinal spent some time in combat zones in Vietnam.
   O'Connor spent Saturday, Sunday and Monday in Lebanon and
returned to New York Wednesday.
   He had described his visit as an evenhanded attempt to bring
attention to the sufferings by Christians and Moslems in Lebanon,
but Moslems criticized the cancellation of his visit to Moslem West
Beirut.
   The cardinal made the trip despite U.S. State Department
warnings to stay away from the war-torn country.
</TEXT>
