<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-PartyPower     06-01 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Party Power,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Officials Reject Call To Give Up Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of the ruling Communist Party
Politburo made clear Thursday they reject populist Boris N.
Yeltsin's demand to relinquish supreme power.
   Vadim A. Medvedev, chief party ideologist, and Moscow Communist
Party boss Lev N. Zaikov told reporters the party has the right to
choose the head of state and government.
   ``As in any civilized state, the leader of the party becomes the
head of state. That's fully natural,'' Medvedev said.
   The officials spoke after members of the Congress of People's
Deputies openly questioned whether President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
should serve in the dual role of head of party and state, and after
Yelstin's sharp criticism of the party on Wednesday.
   Yeltsin, who was replaced by Zaikov as Moscow party chief,
called for an immediate transfer of power from the Communist Party
to the Congress.
   ``The Congress must take power into its own hands,'' Yeltsin
said Wednesday. He charged that Gorbachev's policy of perestroika,
or restructuring, had failed and that people were living worse four
years after it was implemented.
   The party is identified in the Soviet Constitution as the
leading force in Soviet society, and no other parties are legal.
   About 80 percent of the 2,250 members of the Congress are
Communist Party members.But the Congress' slogans declare that
power rests with the soviets, or local governing councils, and
Yeltsin's demand recalled that still-powerful appeal from the first
days of the Bolshevik revolution.
   Neither Politburo official criticized Yeltsin directly.
   Medvedev said he was an ardent supporter of a sharper line
between party and government functions, with the party taking the
work of shaping policy, ideology, organization and political work,
and the government being responsible for legislation and executive
functions.
   Asked which job was more important, Communist Party chief or
president, he responded that the jobs simply had different
responsibilities.
   Zaikov said opposes removing the Communist Party's special
status in the Soviet Constitution, but held open the possibility
that competition might some day be allowed.
   Asked about the possibility of a multi-party system, he
responded: ``Who thought our socialist revolution would take place?
Who thought that perestroika would start? Who can say when it will
be, if it will be? Maybe.''
   But he added that now was not the time. The Communist Party ``is
at its most difficult, critical stage,'' and it would be unfair to
allow another party to spring up and ``practice pure politics,'' he
said.
   The party must concentrate on consolidating the strengths of
Soviet society rather than allowing it to break down in partisan
politics, Zaikov said.
   Yeltsin has been accused by party official of speaking out in
favor of a multi-party system. A commission of the party's
policy-making Central Committee is investigating the accusation.
   Yeltsin denies it, but says that the issue must be discussed
rather than repressed as it has been for decades.
</TEXT>
