<FIRST>r a AM-AxTrio     06-01 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ax Trio,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Ax Attackers Wanted Human Sacrifice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three women accused of trying to kill a
26-year-old man by bashing his head with an ax were followers of
the supernatural and wanted to perform a human sacrifice,
authorities said.
   Deborah Kazuck, 26; Catherine Lipsham, 22; and Ramona Barry, 27,
were charged Wednesday with attempted murder in connection with the
attack Monday in Ms. Lipsham's and Ms. Barry's apartment. They were
each being held under $75,000 bail.
   The man suffered a severe gash to the forehead when hit with an
ax, but he managed to flee. The wound required 50 stitches. He was
being kept at an undisclosed location under a witness protection
program.
   Ms. Kazuck told authorities she had been the mother of Jack the
Ripper in a previous life, according to the criminal complaint. She
said that if she killed someone, she would prove her love to the
legendary 19th century British murderer in an attempt to get him to
return to this world, the complaint said.
   Alan Olshan, Ms. Kazuck's attorney, said, ```In my judgment, she
is mentally ill.''
   The women chanted ``redrum,'' or murder spelled backward, during
the attack, police said. ``Redrum'' was a term used in ``The
Shining,'' a book and movie about supernatural violence.
   Lt. Gary Marks said the women searched the city for six months
for someone to ``kack,'' the term they gave for ``kill,'' before
luring the man to the apartment.
   ``They all have been engaging in seances to communicate with
different spirits,'' he said. ``One of them said she has been
trying to bring Hitler back from the dead.''
   Marks said the man met the women about two weeks ago in a park
and occasionally visited with them.
   ``They were just friends,'' Marks said. ``He said they seemed
perfectly normal.''
   The criminal complaint said the man went to the home late Monday
after Ms. Barry telephoned and said she was frightened by a storm.
   When he went to use the bathroom, he heard a noise and pulled
back a shower curtain hanging over the bathtub, the complaint said.
Ms. Kazuck, who was in the bathtub with Ms. Lipsham, lifted an ax
over her head and struck him, the complaint said.
   The two women tried to grab the man as he fled, it said. Ms.
Barry remained outside the bathroom, hearing a crash and the man's
screams, the complaint said.
   ``They were saying, `Redrum, redrum, redrum' in a low voice,''
Marks said.
   ``He went for the door and had a hard time getting out, but he
made it. He kept running and never looked back,'' he said.
   Before the man arrived, the three women spoke about draining his
blood into the bathtub, cutting his body into pieces and eating his
kidneys, the complaint said.
   The women said ``kack'' is derived from Jack the Ripper's
nickname, with the ``j'' substituted with a ``k'' for ``kill.''
</TEXT>
