<FIRST>r w AM-HousingResumption     06-01 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Resumption,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspended Subsidies to Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Housing and Urban Development Department
said Thursday it will resume subsidies, under new rules, for the
rehabilitation of privately owned housing used by low-income and
moderate-income families.
   Secretary Jack Kemp had suspended the program in April,
canceling awards made this fiscal year, after the department's
inspector general reported it had been mismanaged and riddled with
favoritism for former high-ranking Republicans serving as
consultants to developers.
   The department's announcement said new awards will be based on
numerical rankings in a competitive process for available funds.
   ``I am fully committed to admistering a reformed Moderate
Rehabilitation Program in a fair, open, competitive manner _ with
no special favors, no insder's access and no secret deals,'' Kemp
said in a statement.
   The ranking formula will consider area poverty, crowding and
quality of housing for the poor; will eliminate reserve funds
allocated according to the discretion of headquarters and will
limit awards to projects of fewer than 100 units to discourage
participation by big developers.
   The department said it could have $250 million available for the
remainder of the fiscal year, depending upon congressional action.
</TEXT>
