<FIRST>r a AM-PipelineExplosion     06-01 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pipeline Explosion,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Losses Court Effort To Stop Pipeline Reconstruction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court on Thursday denied
a request by city officials to stop the reconstruction of a
gasoline pipeline through a neighborhood that was virtually
destroyed when it exploded last week.
   The U.S. Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco, citing
lack of jurisdiction, refused to grant a temporary restraining
order, said city attorney James Penman. A state judge made the same
declaration earlier this week.
   Calnev Pipe Line Co. wants to replace the line along the same
course it occupied when it exploded in flames May 25, killing two
residents and injuring 31. The same area was struck two weeks
earlier with a fatal runaway train wreck.
   City officials want to have the pipeline relocated on the other
side of train track and away from the devastated residential
neighborhood. A 35-foot- high levee separates the track and the
neighborhood, said Penman. The wall of dirt would provide some
protection in the event of a similar accident, he said.
   The petition sought a stay of federal Pipeline Safety Director
Richard Beam's order for reinstallation, pending a federal court
review.
   While city officials try to find a way to halt the line and
divert it to another area, workers for Calnev continued to lay the
reinforced pipeline course, said Penman.
   ``Either the pipeline company is going to agree to move the pipe
west of the railroad tracks,'' Penman said, ``or we are going to
keep going to courts until we find one that can exercise
jurisdiction, until there are no courts left to go to.''
   Calnev officials said the replacement line could be in place and
ready to restart sometime next week, barring additional legal
action by the city or further changes from the U.S. Transportation
Department's Office of Pipeline Safety.
   Officials from the company say they will use several new safety
features, such as burying the pipe at twice its former depth and
covering it with concrete and using a thicker, seamless,
plastic-coated pipe. Welds between pipe sections also will be
X-rayed.
   Department of Transportation officials on Tuesday announced
additional requirements for Calnev to follow as they bury the pipe,
including replacement of an additional 1,000 feet and the addition
of a safety valve.
   Calnev operations manager Dave Andries said rerouting the line
may actually be cheaper than the precautions Calnev plans for using
the same course, but the company is concerned with possible flood
damage on the other side of the levee.
   On May 12, a runaway Southern Pacific train derailment in the
same neighborhood on San Bernardino's northwest side killed four
people and injured 11.
   Authorities believe either the train wreck or salvage equipment
brought in to clean it up damaged the 14-inch pipeline, which was
delivering unleaded gasoline to Las Vegas from storage tanks in
Colton. The combined accidents destroyed 22 homes.
   City officials expected to be back in court Friday, either with
a new petition for the federal court or an action for U.S. District
Court in Los Angeles, Penman said. The city also was trying to
negotiate with Calnev out of court, Penman said.
</TEXT>
