<FIRST>u i AM-JumboJetNosedive     06-01 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jumbo Jet Nosedive,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Up To 30 People Hurt In Jumbo Jet Nose Dive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARWIN, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Qantas Airways jumbo jet with 325
people aboard inexplicably pitched upward at 30,000 feet Thursday
and then nose-dived, catapulting passengers around the cabin so
hard they left dents and injuring up to 30 people.
   A Qantas official on Friday described the effect as like a
``roller coaster ride'' for the 305 passengers and 20 crew members
bound for Singapore. The plane, a 747-200, left from Sydney and was
diverted to Darwin, far northern Australia.
   Fleet Manager Capt. Les Hayward said he did not know whether air
turbulence or a fault in the autopilot could have caused the
malfunction.
   He said 61 people were taken to Royal Darwin Hospital, but more
than half of them were relatives of the injured.
   Passenger Judy Maher, 22, of Melbourne, told Australian
Associated Press, ``There was this drop and I saw people, plates,
everything go flying. We hit the ceiling and when we hit the floor
again I was overcome with nausea. There was blood spattered
everywhere.
   ``Stewards were yelling for everyone to be calm, but no one
screamed and there didn't appear to be any panic.''
   Hayward said the aircraft was flying at a cruising speed of
about 520 mph southeast of Derby, Western Australia, when it
suddenly pitched and reared up 1,500 feet before nosing over.
   ``The captain disconnected the autopilot and rolled the aircraft
back to a normal altitude as gently as he could,'' Hayward said.
   ``As the aircraft pitched up the passengers would have been
forced more firmly into their seats as the aircraft rolled over the
top and pitched down again. Some of them did float out of their
seats.''
   A doctor on board treated passengers for bruises and minor
injuries.
   Hayward said the ceiling was dented where people bounced against
the fuselage interior.
   He said there was ``cosmetic damage'' to the rear of the plane,
which later took off for Singapore, Bahrein and Amsterdam. Hayward
said the airline was investigating the cause of the mishap.
   ``It would have been a bit like a roller coaster ride,'' he said.
   Qantas said six passengers were detained overnight. They were
listed in stable condition Friday and most were expected to be
discharged during the day. A cabin attendant was among the injured.
   A former air force fighter navigator aboard the QF5 flight said
he thought the aircraft was going to disintegrate as the pilot
fought for control.
   ``When he opened up the engines, the vibration was incredible. I
thought the wings were going to drop off,'' said 59-year-old Peter
Jensen, who had set out from Sydney with his wife Brigitta on a
round-the-world trip.
   The pilot, Capt. Lyn Williams, was not available for media
interviews.
   Australian Associated Press said at least one dozen passengers
wore medical neck supports. It said the shirt of one man, whose
head was bandaged, was caked with blood.
   ``It felt like we hit an air pocket,'' Jensen said. ``The plane
dived away and I went straight up to the ceiling with a lot of
others. I couldn't be sure we were going to float out of the nose
dip, but we went straight back down to the seats.''
   Jensen said he saw one man smash into an overhead locker,
breaking it off its hinges.
   A 22-year-old Sydney man who received slight neck injuries said
the plane appeared to jerk forward ``in a catapult action.''
   ``It was like being on a trampoline,'' said the man, who spoke
on the condition of not being indentified. ``Then I can only
remember the plane engines roaring out and a lot of vibration.''
   Dutch student Eric Grooters, 24, of Amsterdam, said he had his
seat belt on as he watched his 21 year-old girlfriend, Monique
Lookman, thrown to the plane's roof.
   ``It seemed like everyone was flying around inside the plane,''
Grooters said. ``First the plane seemed to shake and everyone was
terrified.
   ``There were people stretching out in front of me without their
seat belts.''
</TEXT>
