<FIRST>r a AM-TonkovichIndictment     06-01 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tonkovich Indictment,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Senate Leader Accused Of Taking Money From Hotel To Push Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT HARVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state Senate president was
indicted by a federal grand jury Thursday on charges he extorted
$15,000 from hotel officials who were lobbying for a casino
gambling law.
   Daniel R. Tonkovich, 43, is accused of extorting money in 1986
from a hotel group called WVCC, which is now bankrupt but at the
time owned the Grande Hotel in Weirton, according to an official
from Tri Mark Management, which now owns the hotel.
   At time of the of the alleged extortion, WVCC was lobbying for
passage of a casino gambling measure in the Legislature, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Nancy Hill.
   Tonkovich also was accused of unsuccessfully trying to extort
money from Resorts International Inc., a Delaware company that
operates the Resorts International Hotel and Casino in Atlantic
City, N.J., Hill said.
   Resorts International also was lobbying for the casino measure,
which eventually was voted down by lawmakers, Hill said. According
to the indictment, Resorts International planned to develop one or
more casinos in West Virginia if the legislation had passed.
   A spokesman for Resorts International had no comment Thursday
night.
   Tonkovich is accused of taking a total of $15,000 in three
extortion payments from WVCC at the same time the casino
legislation was pending, Hill said.
   Repeated calls to Tonkovich's home were not answered Thursday
evening.
   The indictment accuses Tonkovich of accepting the payments by
drawing up a false contract involving an assistant. In return for
the money, the senator pledged to back the casino legislation, the
indictment alleges.
   If convicted on all counts, Tonkovich would face 80 years in
prison and a $1 million fine, Hill said.
   Tonkovich, a Democrat, was elected to the House of Delegates in
1972 and won election to the Senate in 1976. In 1985, he was
elected Senate president.
</TEXT>
