<DOCNO> AP890601-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     06-01 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Florida Crackers' Opens off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the next to last scene of ``Florida
Crackers,'' somebody mentions that a red tide is coming in and soon
there'll be dead fish on the beach.
   ``Why don't they just swim away?'' asks a character named Lori.
``They don't know any better,'' answers a character named Dean.
It's playwright William S. Leavengood's metaphor for the
increasingly dangerous drug scene in which his characters swim.
   In his play, which opened Thursday at off-Broadway's Circle
Repertory Company, Leavengood has made his grungy people likable,
worth saving and interesting without the audience having to
identify with them. And, though drugs permeate ``Florida
Crackers,'' Leavengood does not glorify them.
   The set, by John Lee Beatty, is the cheaply made Florida
ocean-front house of 30-year-old Joe, played by John C. McGinley.
McGinley gives the play's strongest performance as the father
figure to his two brothers in their 20s, thrown out of a family
split by divorce. Joe peddles dope and sometimes drives delivery
trucks of dope for Dean. McGinley conveys the impression that Joe
has an inner core of integrity. He calls all the men ``son'' and
when McGinley says it, it sounds natural and caring.
   Michael Piontek plays Grant, the second brother, whose luck
always is bad. Scott Rymer plays Russell, the youngest brother,
just out of college, who had the brains to become a doctor, studied
philosophy instead and now does nothing. A warm moment in a play
marked with sadly wasted potential and premonitions of violence has
the three brothers singing the Eagles' ``Take it to the Limit.''
   Brian Jensen plays Strings, a would-be guitarist living in Joe's
house, stoned all the time. Joel Anderson plays Dean, who sees
Mafia and other sharks moving in on his drug-running business and
believes they're out to kill him.
   For lighter moments of a feminine kind, there's the upscale Lori
(Kim Flowers) and the loose, funny Tracey (Cyndi Coyne). Playwright
John Bishop directed Florida-native Leavengood's off-Broadway debut.
   There's no happy ending. When Joe finally could swim away, the
pull of the family he has created with his brothers is stronger and
he does something terrible and stays, their leader, in the deadly
tides of dope.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpendingBill 2ndLd-Writethru a0844 06-01 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0844,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Nears Clash With House Over Spending Bill Minus Drug Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new 3rd graf, ``Lawmakers went,'' with new amendments,
Senate finishing business for day. Stands for AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate party leaders united Thursday to fight
off a wave of White House-opposed drug spending proposals as
lawmakers debated a bill providing $3.3 billion for veterans and
other domestic programs.
   The measure, for the waning months of the current fiscal year,
includes $1.2 billion for health care and other programs for
veterans that are running low on funds. It also carries $892
million for the Guaranteed Student Loan program for college
students, $423 million for state foster care programs, and other
funds for agencies needing money for the final four months of the
1989 fiscal year.
   Lawmakers went home Thursday evening after nearly 14 hours of
debate and planned to resume work Friday. They adopted amendments
ranging from providing $1 million for development of medicines for
rare diseases, to urging the bankruptcy court handling Eastern
Airlines' bankruptcy proceedings to consider appointing an
independent trustee to replace chief executive Frank Lorenzo in
running the strike-bound carrier.
   But the most controversial aspect of the Senate bill is its
omission of any additional anti-drug money _ unlike a $3.7 billion
version passed by the House on May 24 that contained $822 million
for more prison cells, extra drug agents, improved education
programs and other anti-drug efforts.
   That anti-drug spending was shaved from the legislation by
Senate leaders before it reached the floor, following Bush
administration threats to veto the entire bill over the anti-drug
money. The White House says the extra spending would inflate this
year's already swollen federal deficit and can wait until 1990, and
senior Democratic and Republican senators argued that adding drug
monies would be futile.
   ``This bill is for programs that are broke,'' said Senate
Appropriations Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.
   However, that did not stop some senators from trying to increase
spending against illicit drug dealers.
   The Senate voted 71-20 to defeat an amendment by Sen. Joseph
Biden, D-Del., that would have spent another $1.8 billion this year
for prevention and treatment programs, grants to local governments,
more federal agents, and other anti-drug measures. The provision
would have raised the money by boosting federal taxes on cigarettes
and alcoholic beverages.
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., pressed an amendment diverting $70
million from Defense Department anti-drug efforts to increasing
federal prison space for drug offenders.
   Specter said the money would be ``a little something to show the
American people that Congress does more than pontificate and talk
about the problem.'' He was defeated 77-18.
   A proposal by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., to boost this year's
drug programs by $227 million was defeated 81-15.
   Although the measure exceeds the $2.2 billion supplemental
spending bill President Bush sent Congress in March, the
administration indicated in a statement Thursday that it would
support the Senate proposal ``in view of the need for prompt action
on veterans funding.''
   The legislation includes $342 million for the expenses of
battling last year's forest fires, $225 million for the food stamps
program, $125 million for United Nations peacekeeping forces, $100
million to help Soviet and other refugees to this country, and $91
million for workers whose jobs were lost due to overseas
competition.
   It also contains $7.3 million for cleaning up the Alaska oil
spill.
   As so often happens with spending bills, the legislation has
also picked up less far-reaching provisions that reflect the
interests of members of the Appropriations Committee.
   Thus, it also provides $75 million to rebuild a radio telescope
that toppled in West Virginia, home state of appropriations panel
Chairman Robert Byrd. And it urges the Department of Health and
Human Services to hire more health care workers in Honolulu, thanks
to the efforts of Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, a ranking member of
the committee.
   It also contains $1.6 million for a Philadelphia foundation to
train unemployed people, $1.8 million for a White House Conference
on Library and Information Services, $1.5 million for Puerto Rico's
political parties to conduct a referendum on the island's political
status, and $6.6 million for subsidies for air carriers that serve
small communities.
   A non-binding provision was also included expressing the
Senate's desire to prevent Panamanian ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega from nominating a new administrator to the Panama Canal
Commission. A treaty allows Panama to nominate an administrator for
the U.S. agency, which oversees the canal.
   The language was introduced by Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind., and other
conservative Republicans, and was approved on a voice vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
