<DOCNO> AP890601-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2356EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Drugs     06-01 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Drugs,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Police Arrested, 10 Fired for Drug Links</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national police said Thursday that
three high-ranking officers were arrested and 10 officers were
fired on charges of working for Colombia's powerful drug
trafficking cartels.
   The force's commander, Gen. Miguel Gomez Padilla, said in a
communique his office ``will be inflexible in applying whatever
corrective measures are needed to maintain discipline, order and to
guarantee good service to society.''
   The Bogota newspaper El Tiempo said on Thursday that five
officers have been arrested and 23 expelled from the force in
recent months on corruption charges, including a captain in the
provincial capital of Sincelejo caught with a suitcase full of drug
money.
   Gomez Padilla said drug dealers were trying ``with unusual
persistence to destabilize the nation's institutions.''
   A car bomb blew up on a main Bogota boulevard Tuesday as the
head of Colombia's national bureau of investigation was passing. He
escaped death, but four bystanders were killed. He blamed the
attack on drug traffickers working in conjunction with murderous
right-wing vigilantes.
   It was the latest in a series of assassinations or attempts
against high-ranking justice and police officials in Colombia, a
land plagued by cocaine trafficking, rightist death squads and
leftist guerrilla groups.
   President Virgilio Barco said in an address to cadets at the
military academy on Thursday that such attacks only stiffen
government resolve.
   ``Instead of weakening the fighting will of the country, of our
armed forces and of our security agencies, it generates redoubled
enthusiasm to move ahead,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 2324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SpellingBee 5thLd-Writethru a0847 06-01 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spelling Bee, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0847,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Youth Wins National Spelling Bee</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 15th graf pvs, bgng: ``Ojas, meanwhile...'' to make it
Scott sted Ojas; picks up 16th graf pvs, bgng: ``After six...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scott Isaacs, an eighth-grader from Littleton,
Colo., won the 62nd annual National Spelling Bee on Thursday by
correctly spelling the word ``spoliator.''
   It was the 14-year-old's third time in the national finals. He
defeated Ojas V. Tejani of Hixson, Tenn., in a duel that capped the
two-day finals.
   They were the survivors of the largest field in the bee's
history, outlasting 220 other contestants.
   The word ``spoliator'' means a spoiler.
   In the final rounds, Ojas, a 12-year-old sixth-grader, correctly
spelled ``saponaceous,'' an adjective for something resembling
soap, and Scott countered with the correct spelling of
``ideaphoria,'' which is a capacity for creative thought or
imagination.
   Both spellers, however, missed ``pasigraphy,'' which means an
artificial international written language, and Ojas then missed the
next word, ``senescing,'' which means growing old.
   Scott spelled the word correctly and under contest rules had to
spell the next word correctly. He did and won the $1,500 first
prize.
   Ojas will collect $1,000.
   In third place was Arthur A. Hodge, 14, from Pottsville, Pa.,
who missed ``trinklied,'' a word meaning a drinking song. In fourth
was Samantha Cassell of Johnson City, Tenn., who lost out on the
word ``pedicled,'' which means having a slender stalk.
   Scott was one of seven students competing in the national finals
for the third time.
   He is an eighth-grade pupil at Kent Denver Country Day School in
Englewood, Colo. His father, Bud, is an oil engineer and his
mother, Kaye, is a homemaker.
   He was the 1987 and 1988 Denver spelling champion.
   Ojas is in the sixth grade at St. Nicholas School in
Chattanooga, the son of a chemical engineer, Vinay, and a
homemaker, Indu.
   Scott was to fly to New York later in the day to appear on
Friday's ABC ``Good Morning America,'' and he is booked for next
week on NBC's ``Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson.''
   Also, Scott and the entire Indiana delegation of spellers have
been invited to meet on Friday with Vice President Quayle.
   After six rounds, only six boys and nine girls remained. The
next round cut that number to four and four, and only the final
four were left for the ninth round.
   In quick succession, Arthur spelled ``wight,'' a living being;
Samantha spelled ``dihara,'' a buddhist monastery; Ojas had
``halieutics,'' which relates to fishing, and Scott was correct
with ``morion,'' a helmet worn by 16th and 17th century Spanish
footsoldiers.
   In the 10th round, Arthur was correct with ``vigentennial,''
which means once every 20 years, and Ojas had ``stereopsis,'' a
capacity for depth perception; Scott spelled ``diluvial,'' which
concerns a flood or deluge, but Samantha tripped up on ``pedicled.''
   Arthur then lost out with ``trinklied.'' And that left only the
two finalists.
   The winner's eyes brimmed with tears as he was handed the
championship trophy and friends and relatives came to the stage and
embraced him. He also received a handshake from the runner-up and
Ojas' father.
   Scott said that he had been studying 104 dictionary words a day
_ the number that will fit on a shet of computer paper _ since
January. He said he has participated in 15 bees counting local,
regional and national contests, and has won eight of them.
   As for the future, he said, ``I might be into words when I get
older, or I might be a pilot.''
   The runner-up, Ojas, said he had started preparing for spelling
bees when he was in the third grade. He was born in the United
States but said he has visited the area of northern India that his
father comes from.
   There was one tense moment near the end of the competition when
the judges ruled that Melody Yung, 12, of Fall River, Mass., had
misspelled ``salariat,'' a class of salaried persons.
   There were cries of dismay from the audience and a flurry of
activity among the judges. They finally played a tape over the
loudspeaker system, which showed she had spelled the word
``salariet,'' and the judges' ruling stood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
