<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:IntellectualRefugee Adv09   06-01 1044</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Intellectual Refugee, Adv 09,1064</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, June 9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>An Emotional Escape From Australia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jill Ker Conway was a smart little girl
who survived the Australian wilderness and grew up to be an
intellectual refugee fleeing an impossible mother and a sexist
society.
   It's a sometimes harrowing story the 54-year-old historian,
feminist and former president of Smith College tells in her memoir,
``The Road From Coorain'' (Knopf, $18.95).
   Right through to the close of her account, she voices the pained
discontent that has sent many Australians far from that isolated
island continent in the Pacific. The memoir ends in 1960 at the
airport in Sydney, standing on the tarmac of long goodbyes. She is
26 and on her way to study American history at Harvard University.
   ``I was leaving because I didn't fit in, never had, and wasn't
likely to,'' she writes. ``I was going to another country. To begin
all over again. ...
   ``Where, I wondered, would my bones come to rest? It pained me
to think of them not fertilizing Australian soil.''
   Since landing here, the Australian expatriate has made a
brilliant career. She earned a doctorate at Harvard, served as the
first woman vice president at the University of Toronto and, in
1975, began a 10-year stint at Smith that put her on the cover of
Time magazine as a woman to watch in the Year of Women.
   Congressmen solicited her opinion on education so often that in
1978 she became a U.S. citizen. Her honorary degrees could paper a
large wall and she serves on a slew of corporate boards, from
Colgate-Palmolive to Nike.
   Now a visiting scholar and teacher at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, she is turning out an unconventional
trilogy she hopes will light a fire under a generation grown
complacent about equal rights for women. One book is about Third
World women; a second will be a women's history of the past 25
years in the context of American life; the third is her memoir,
which offers a personal view of women in a world run by men.
   Jill Ker Conway is a tall, genteel woman who speaks in a
near-whisper and has an inquisitive, open face. She has no regrets
about leaving the land of her birth, she said in a recent interview.
   Australia ``is a culture obsessed with the anarchic male hero
from Ned Kelly (a revered Australian outlaw) to `Crocodile
Dundee,''' she said. ``Men in Australia suffer a great deal from
having that as an ideal. Women have no territory in that country.
   ``It's not that I don't like men. But you need a world that
recognizes there are two sexes.''
   Conway's account of how she broke away from that place tells of
a young woman who battled outrageous misfortune to fulfill her
potential. In a stunningly direct, no-nonsense Australian way, she
describes a sometimes harrowing childhood, the emerging power of
her largely self-taught intellect and her anguished decision to
leave her bitter and possessive mother.
   For starters, she explains that she wasn't even meant to be born.
   Her mother and father were eking out a life on Coorain _ an
aboriginal word meaning ``windy place,'' an 18,000-acre sheep
station in the flat plains of outback New South Wales, Australia's
southeastern quadrant. The Kers settled there in 1929 during a
drought.
   They already had two sons when Mrs. Ker discovered in 1934 that
she was pregnant again. A nurse-gone-bush, she attempted in vain to
abort the fetus. Jill Ker was born without incident, however.
   At Coorain, the family lived in a weatherboard bungalow with
wide verandas and a corrugated iron roof. It was a lonely place of
punishing heat in summer and the alternating threat of floods and
fatal dry spells. Sustenance in the early days consisted of meat,
potatoes, eggs and pickles. When it rained there was wild spinach,
but in the general absence of fresh fruit and vegetables, there was
cod liver oil and lime juice.
   The family read by kerosene lamps the books that arrived in the
mail from a lending library 500 miles away in Sydney.
   The sheep station prospered, however. By age 6, Conway was
helping her father muster sheep, check fences and maintain
windmills. He also taught her to be stoical and not to cry. But
drought returned and five years of dust storms, dying sheep and a
depressed father came to a tragic end when the father drowned
trying to extend piping in a dam. Conway was 10.
   The family packed up and moved to Sydney. There the precocious
autodidact with a huge vocabulary from all those borrowed books was
accepted at an elite girls school. She went on to the prestigious
University of Sydney and graduated at the top of her class. But
when she tried to join the Australian foreign service she was
turned down on grounds that she was too attractive and too
intellectually aggressive.
   All the while her mother grew increasingly critical and
dependent. Violating her own sense of duty and quiet suffering,
Conway decided she had enough and fled to Harvard.
   ``It helped cinch the decision that Boston and Cambridge were
about as far away from Sydney as one can get on this planet, and
that I'd be totally safe from family visits,'' she wrote.
   In the nearly 30 years since then, Jill Ker married Canadian
John Conway, now 73 and a retired historian. They spent 11 years
teaching in Canada until 1975 when she took over at Smith.
   In her decade in Northampton running the prestigious liberal
arts college, Conway introduced major programs in business
management and women's studies, enriched Smith's endowment from $82
million to $179 million and, for the first time, made room among
the school's 2,500 places for older women and welfare mothers.
   She said the book of her early life was written for several
reasons, including honoring the courage of her parents and
recording a vanished way of life. There's a feminist message too.
   ``It is very important to find some rhetoric that will
communicate to a broad public about feminist issues,'' Conway said.
``Young women think they're all solved.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 9</NOTE>
