<FIRST>a d BC-FUN--Food-Kids'Food     06-01 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FUN--Food-Kids' Food,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>FOOD 5-26</HEAD>
<UNK>HEAD: Kids choose pizza as their No.1 food    ___</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pizza is the favorite food among kids 6 to 14
years of age, according to a recent poll by the editors of Kid City
and 3-2-1 Contact magazines.
   Over 25 percent of the more than 12,000 respondents to the
magazines' survey selected pizza as their favorite food. Most of
those said they thought that pizza was probably bad for them, but
they liked it anyway.
   The survey showed that kids sometimes have their nutritional
facts wrong, as is the case with pizza, which is basically a
nutritious food.
   In other cases, kids know a food like fish, for example, is good
for them, but they seldom eat it, even though they may like it.
Some 82 percent reported that they know fish is healthful and 52
percent said they like it, yet only 34 percent eat it regularly _
possibly because their parents don't prepare it for them.
   As for vegetables _ nearly 61 percent of the respondents between
the ages of 6 to 10 said they regularly eat vegetables, even though
they may not like them. In the 8 to 14-year-old category, 82
percent said they regularly include vegetables among the foods they
eat.
   The magazines are urging their young readers to eat vegetables,
unsweetened cereals, fresh fruit and yogurt, and to avoid lots of
fried foods and fizzy soft drinks.
   Kid City and 3-2-1 Contact magazines are published by the
Children's Television Workshop, which produces ``Sesame Street''
and other educational television programs.
   A book by the Children's Television Workshop, ``Parents Guide to
Feeding Your Kids Right,'' which deals with good nutrition from
birth through the teen-age years, is scheduled for publication this
year by Prentice Hall Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
