<HEAD>CULTURE 5-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>HEAD: Culture Cues</HEAD>
<NOTE>JEWISH</NOTE>
<NOTE>HISTORY</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The history of Asian Jews, a story spanning 25
centuries and covering 13 lands, is told in a new, colorful and
imaginative permanent exhibit in the Hall of Asian Peoples at the
American Museum of Natural History here.
   The exhibit centers around a spacious wall grid that indicates
diagrammatically the diversity of Asian Jewish life through history
in many different lands. On the grid are placed appropriate
examples of ceremonial and folk art objects, portraits and
quotations to bring the history to life.
   At the same time, two screens make available interactive video
programs by means of which museum visitors can explore individual
areas that interest them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE BEAUTY</NOTE>
<NOTE>OF THE EARTH</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Smithsonian Institution's National Air and
Space Museum has announced plans for the next large-format
IMAX-OMNIVAX film: it's to be ``Blue Planet,'' being produced in
cooperation with NASA, and it will focus on the beauty of the earth
and its changing environmental systems.
   The film will premiere at the museum in the fall of 1990, and
then will be seen in the more than 60 giant-screen IMAX and OMNIMAX
theaters worldwide.
   ``Blue Planet'' will be funded and presented as a public service
by the Lockheed Corp.
</TEXT>
