<DOCNO> AP890601-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-FUN--Music-Kernfeld 1stadd   06-01 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FUN--Music-Kernfeld, 1st add,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>BOOKS AND HOBBIES 5-26</HEAD>
<TEXT>UNDATED: might elsewhere.''    Kernfeld now lives in Oxford, England,
because his wife won a two-year fellowship for North American Ph.D. women
under 35. She studies 19th-century American agriculture, especially dairying,
about which Oxford has much material.    Wanting to be a performer, San
Francisco-born Kernfeld went to the University of California at Davis.
``I discovered to my surprise I really liked looking at music carefully
and seriously, and that I had some gift for writing about it.'' Entering
graduate school at Cornell, Kernfeld surprised himself again. ``I thought
I'd work on Berlioz and ended up working on Miles Davis, to my great pleasure.''
   Asked his personal favorite, Kernfeld says: ``There are things I love
from all parts of jazz. Coltrane is my favorite.''    Editing the dictionary
included ``a brutal eight months of proofreading,'' he says. ``Fortunately,
I hadn't thought about that when I started.''    But mostly, he says,
``It was wonderful. It was a four-year learning experience. It was like
getting to go to school again and getting to study this stuff in entirely
different ways.    ``It put me on the alert for strange and fun things
that I otherwise might not have paid attention to, except that I was trying
to define things for the dictionary. There's an article on `honk.' I found
a wonderful Frank Foster and Frank Wess example of honking on the tenor
sax. I made a two-bar musical example of it.''
</TEXT>
