<FIRST>a l BC-FUN--Camera     06-01 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FUN--Camera,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>BOOKS AND HOBBIES 5-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>HEAD: Camera Angles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>ART: 2 col. group of Little Leaguers    ___ ^By SANDY COLTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Little League Baseball fans can win a trip to this year's Little
League World Series, held in Williamsport, Pa., as well as a great
camera to take along and use to photograph the action.
   Minolta Corp. is sponsoring a photo contest for all amateur _
not professional _ photographers, including the approximately 2.5
million youngsters who participate in Little League, as well as
their parents and fans.
   The winner of the grand prize will receive an all-expenses-paid
trip for four to the Series, scheduled for Aug. 22-26, plus a
Minolta MAXXUM 3000i camera system.
   The contest, which runs through July 15, honors Little League
Baseball's 50th anniversary. An exhibit of winning photographs will
be displayed at the Series, and proceeds from the contest will be
used to initiate a drug education program for Little Leaguers.
   Photos entered in the contest must be of an official Little
League Baseball activity. To enter, submit a color slide, or a
black-and-white or color print no larger than 5-by-7 inches
(normal, drugstore-size prints will do) to: Little League Baseball,
50th Anniversary Photo Contest, P.O. Box 3485, Williamsport, PA
17701.
   Official entry forms are available at photo stores or through
local Little League programs, and also by writing to Little League
Baseball at the above address, or to Minolta Corp., 101 Williams
Dr., Ramsey, NJ 07446.
   To benefit the drug education program, a recommended donation of
$1 should accompany each entry.
   In addition to the trip and camera, a number of other prizes
will be awarded.
   It's a great cause and there are great prizes, so take plenty of
pictures and submit lots of entries.
   Good luck.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>New from Leica</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Surprise _ Leica, the ``Cadillac'' of cameras, has entered the
point-and-shoot market.
   The Leica R reflex and M rangefinder cameras now have an
autofocus and auto-exposure sibling. The new camera, called the
AF-C1, has a suggested retail price of $698 _ less than the cost of
a typical Leica lens. (Now you know why Leica is called the
``Cadillac'' of cameras.)
   The AF-C1 is a dual-lens system with both 40mm f2.0 and 80mm
f5.6 capability. The autofocus system projects five independent
infrared beams so that it can focus on a subject that is not in the
center of the viewfinder. The shutter release can actuate a focus
lock for out-of-center subjects. The camera focuses from 28 inches
to infinity in less than a second.
   The auto-exposure system uses center-weighted integral
measurements with automatic correction in cases of high contrast.
It has DX coding that sets film speeds from ASA 50 to 3200. With
non-coded film, the camera exposes for ASA 100.
   Coupled to the exposure system is a built-in flash that operates
automatically in low light, when contrasts are extreme, and in
back-lighted situations. When the lens is switched from wide-angle
to tele, the flash angle is changed accordingly and the distance of
the flash reflector from the optical axis is altered to reduce the
possibility of red-eye. The flash recycles in two seconds and can
be operated manually.
   The viewfinder shows the autofocus frame and parallax indicators
for close-ups. A green light in the finder indicates that there is
adequate available light. A flash symbol appears when the flash has
cut in, and a red dot shows that it is not yet fully charged.
Another symbol warns the user that the subject is too close.
   The AF-C1 features autoloading to the first frame, a self-timer
and automatic rewind. You can also power-rewind midway through a
roll of film. A lithium battery powers the camera.
   The new camera should become available at Leica dealers in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
