<DOCNO> AP890601-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a l BC-FUN--Books-Small     06-01 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FUN--Books-Small,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>BOOKS AND HOBBIES 5-26</HEAD>
<TEXT>HEAD: Small book packs a big wallop    ___    WORDSTRUCK: A Memoir.
By Robert MacNeil. Viking. 230 Pages. $18.95.    ``Wordstruck,'' by Robert
MacNeil, is an endearing book that traces his love of literature and language
as a young man in Nova Scotia up through his early years as a Canadian
broadcaster.    His formative years were richly seasoned by his parents'
love of books. Dramatic readings of the classics by his mother left an
indelible appreciation for the spoken word, and his father's library of
nautical books was a constant source of entertainment for the young MacNeil.
   MacNeil gives his readers a glimpse of innocent times, unfortunately
long gone. While his dad was out to sea for months at a time during the
war, his mother kept up a brave front for the children at home. His narratives
of childhood experiences illustrate a world quite different from today's
media-oriented society.    Radio was a new and innovative way for the
world to communicate and inform, and MacNeil describes his fascination
with the ``sounds from across the sea'' with the same enthusiasm as a child
at his first circus. Readers will find his explanations on the origins
of commonly used phrases and colloquialisms most interesting, and his explanation
of the game of cricket is very amusing.    Perhaps the most poignant passage
in this book is one that tells his thoughts on his father's ``legacy''
after his death: ``To his three sons he bequeathed his accomplishments
and the things he did not do. It is significant how much of our lives we
have spent doing just those things, balancing his account with life. Thus
in his fantasies he moves us still. There was plenty of him to go around.''
   ``Wordstruck'' is a small book that packs a big punch. It is a wonderful,
appealing chronicle of one man's boyhood recollections of life and family,
and it leaves the reader with a warm feeling for the past, and hope for
the future of our language and culture.    Cecilia McNally    Associated
Press
</TEXT>
</DOC>
