<DOCNO> AP890601-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a l BC-FUN--Changing-Maze 2Takes   06-01 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FUN--Changing-Maze, 2 Takes,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>An AP New Dimensions Feature</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHANGING 5-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>HEAD: Getting Through the Financial Maze</HEAD>
<NOTE>By CHANGING TIMES</NOTE>
<NOTE>The Kiplinger Magazine</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Do you have a plan of action in case one or both of your elderly
parents cannot take care of themselves or their finances?
   Caring for your elderly parents can mean taking responsibility
for their financial health as well as their physical well-being. If
you find yourself in that position, you'll have to negotiate a
tricky legal and financial maze to determine, among other things,
who should control your parents' assets, how they should be used
and who, if anyone, will realize any tax benefits.
   Joint ownership of assets with right of survivorship is a
popular strategy for parents and children, but it is often not the
best one. Holding a small bank account or two jointly with your
parent makes sense if the amounts involved are relatively small.
Or, it can work when your parent's finances are fairly
straightforward _ if, for example, he or she doesn't own a home and
receives income solely from Social Security. And jointly held
property bypasses probate.
   As assets mount, however, so do the problems, warns Changing
Times magazine. If your father, for instance, makes you a joint
tenant, generally he makes a gift to you. That gift is subject to
the federal gift tax when half the value of the assets exceeds
$10,000, the annual exclusion from the gift tax. Depending on the
asset, you may owe income tax on half the income earned by the
property, even if your father keeps all of it for his own use.
   You control the assets subject to the joint tenancy, and you can
do whatever you want with them. Your father thus has no guarantee
you'll use them on his behalf. And when he dies, you have no legal
responsibility to share the assets with anyone else, regardless of
what your father may have wished.
   Two alternatives avoid those pitfalls: the durable power of
attorney and the revocable living trust.
   Durable Power of Attorney: This technique is so crucial that ``a
lawyer would be remiss in not suggesting that an older person have
a durable power as well as a will,'' says John Regan of the Hofstra
University School of Law, who has written extensively on tax and
estate planning for the elderly.
   Like a regular power of attorney, a durable power is an
inexpensive, easily executed document. It allows your father to
name you (or someone else) as his agent, and he can make the power
as narrow or as broad as he wishes. Unlike a regular power of
attorney, which ceases when the person granting it becomes mentally
incompetent, a durable power remains in effect.
   One catch: To create a valid power, a person has to be mentally
competent at the time he or she signs it. If your father already
suffers from Alzheimer's disease or some other mental illness, it
may be too late. You may have to ask the court to appoint a
guardian for your father and-or his property _ a procedure that's
expensive, degrading to the parent, and may require doctors and
family members to testify in open court.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0322 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a l BC-FUN--Changing-Maze 1stAdd   06-01 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FUN--Changing-Maze, 1st Add,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>An AP New Dimensions Feature</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHANGING 5-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDARTED: court.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   So it's critical to plan in advance. But that too can raise a
thorny issue. A durable power takes effect as soon as it is signed,
which means you, as agent, have the power to manage the property
immediately. That may not sit well with a parent who is still fully
capable of running his or her own affairs. In that case, consider a
``springing'' durable power of attorney, if your parent lives in a
state that permits it. A springing durable power, though executed
now, springs to life in the future, normally when your parent
becomes mentally unable to handle things.
   Even if a springing durable power isn't permitted in your state,
your mother can leave a signed durable-power document with her
lawyer. Since you won't have proof in hand that you are the
authorized agent, you won't be able to do anything with her
property. Should your mother become mentally incompetent, the power
would be turned over to you. She can revoke a power of attorney at
any time while she is still mentally competent.
   All powers of attorney end automatically when the principal
dies. In a few states, durable powers have to be renewed
periodically.
   A durable power is becoming the cornerstone of all estate
planning for the elderly. But it does have one possible drawback:
Since your mother gives up control of her own affairs as soon as it
takes effect, you, as agent, may be able to do anything you want
with your mother's property during her lifetime.
   Revocable Living Trusts: If your mother prefers to retain more
control over her affairs, she might consider a revocable living
trust. Such a trust takes effect during the lifetime of the person
who sets it up, who can change or revoke it as long as he or she is
mentally competent. It gives the creator a great deal of control
during and after his or her lifetime. Usually your mother can
continue to manage her property by acting as her own trustee, with
another trustee standing by to take over if she becomes
incapacitated. So the trust, in effect, operates like a springing
durable power of attorney, says Changing Times magazine.
   Perhaps even more important from your parent's point of view,
trust language will spell out exactly how the trustee should use
the income and principal. If your mother doesn't want to transfer
assets to the trust right away, she can arrange for it to be done
later by the trustee or another agent using a durable power of
attorney. At your parent's death, a trust can distribute property
much like a will _ and the assets don't go through probate.
   Revocable living trusts have some drawbacks, however. In
exchange for retaining control of his or her assets, your parent
does not get the tax breaks of an irrevocable trust, which gives
assets away permanently. The creator of a revocable trust pays
income tax on its earnings, and at death the value of the assets is
included in his or her gross estate for federal estate-tax
purposes. Drafting a trust also costs more than drafting a power of
attorney. Lawyers' fees run $300 to $400 or more. You can figure on
an additional $500 to $2,500 a year if you choose a bank as
trustee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
