<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:MartinAuction Adv04   06-01 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Martin Auction, Adv 04,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 4 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sotheby's To Sell Rare Book Collection of 7,000 Volumes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H. Bradley Martin was born to money, well
educated, discriminating, loved books and lived a long time _
qualities that made him one of the great book collectors of the
20th century.
   When he died last year at age 82, his library included more than
10,000 books and manuscripts, all of which he kept in his New York
apartment and at Rose Hill, his handsome Georgian house in Virginia.
   ``I suppose we were one of the few families to consider the care
and cleaning of books a favorite activity,'' says his wife,
Jacqueline Martin. ``We loved working together, and we rejoiced
with him in each new edition.''
   Sixty-four years after the 18-year-old Martin purchased his
first rare book _ a copy of ``Tom Sawyer'' _ at a shop on 14th
Street in Manhattan, his collection will be sold at auction by
Sotheby's. The series of eight sales will start June 6 and continue
through the next year. They are expected to fetch more than $30
million.
   A copy of naturalist John James Audubon's masterwork, ``Birds of
America,'' is expected to bring $2 million to $3 million. Edgar
Allen Poe's first edition copy of ``Eureka,'' with his own
annotations, is estimated at $100,000 to $150,000, while a
watercolor of a Woodchat bird is listed at $400 to $600.
   The quality of the sale is so high, said Selby Kiffer, an
assistant vice president at Sotheby's, that non-book collectors _
including people who want only the best for their homes _ are
expected to join the bookish set in tendering bids.
   The first sale, to run June 6-June 8, will focus on Martin's
ornithological collection, considered by experts to be the best in
private hands. His collections of American, English and French
literature, children's books, Americana and natural history books
will be sold later on.
   ``He had lots of the ingredients one needs to have to form a
great collection,'' said David N. Redden, a senior vice president
at the auction house. ``He had wealth. He had a good education. He
had an interest in his collecting area, starting at a very early
age. And he had great taste and discrimination. Put all those
together and you end up with potential for a great collection.''
   Martin was the oldest of five sons of Bradley Martin and Helen
Phipps, and the grandson of Henry Phipps, a partner of Andrew
Carnegie. He lived a privileged life, attending Oxford as an
undergraduate and serving as a director of the trust companies that
managed the family fortune, originally made from steel interests.
   Book collecting was his passion. During World War II, he had
proof sheets for one sale catalog sent to him while serving with
the Office of Strategic Services in North Africa.
   Friends and associates describe him as ``a gentleman in the old
school'' _ polite, quiet, modest, handsome and an interesting
conversationalist. He was also admired as a meticulous collector.
   ``I've been in this business 78 years. My first sale was in
1912,'' said bookseller David Kirschenbaum of Carnegie Bookshop in
Manhattan, a lifelong friend of Martin's. ``There are people who
are accumulators and there are people that are collectors. This is
a collection.
   ``A collector has a reason for every book that he buys; an
accumulator just buys this thing or the other.''
   Martin also gets high marks among book lovers for being a
prolific reader as well as a collector of books. But he spent much
of his time reading catalogs produced by booksellers and auction
houses.
   One of Martin's favorite acquisitions was Audubon's five-volume
folio of 435 handcolored etched plates of 489 supposed species,
including the Trumpeter Swan, the Roseate Spoonbill and the Snowy
Owl. He bought it through the Carnegie Bookshop in 1956. A special
cabinet designed for the folio was the focal point of Martin's
sitting room in New York.
   Other highlights of the collection include his copy of ``The
Federalist,'' which was presented to George Washington by Alexander
Hamilton. The two-volume book, estimated at $250,000 to 400,000,
has Washington's signature and book plate and annotations by James
Madison.
   ``When I picked up the Federalist Papers, which had been on
deposit at the Morgan Library, it was a little nerve-racking,''
said Kiffer who is cataloging the books. ``It was one of the few
times my hands were shaking.''
   Martin's copy of the Declaration of Independence, which is one
of 23 copies known to survive from the original printing of 100, is
expected to fetch $400,000 to $600,000. He acquired it in the 1970s
from a New York City bookseller.
   ``There is tremendous interest in this. There is every
indication that the high estimate will be exceeded,'' Kiffer said.
``There is general concern that this copy might leave the country.''
   Martin carefully assembled his library over 64 years; the
Sotheby's sale will dismantle it in one year.
   But Kirschenbaum, who lunched with Martin three times a week,
said Martin would be happy about the auction. Mrs. Martin is
because the sale will give other collectors a chance to fill out
their own libraries as her husband did.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0327 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1346EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-DrugRepackagers Adv04   06-01 1276</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drug Repackagers, Adv 04,1309</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 4, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Business of Medicine IV: Patients, Money Promised to Doctors Selling
Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With series logo, Laserphoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Years ago, doctors counted pills into white
envelopes for patients. Today, a new industry is taking over that
role, promising ``practice building'' and ``revenue enhancement''
to doctors who sell the prescriptions they write. In a continuing
series, ``The Business of Medicine,'' Science Writer Daniel Q.
Haney and National Writer Fred Bayles look at the drug repackaging
industry.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</NOTE>
<NOTE>and</NOTE>
<NOTE>FRED BAYLES</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writers</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soft click and hum of pill-counting
machines give a high-tech tone to the operations of the
Pharmaceutical Corporation of America, but the heart of the
business is simplicity itself _ moving medicine from big bottles
into little bottles.
   In the company's brightly lit, air-filtered filling room, women
in surgical garb stuff in cotton, screw on tops and paste on
labels, readying stacks of machine-filled plastic containers for
resale in clinics and doctors' offices around the country.
   Despite its small size, just 12 employees, PCA is a big player
in a new industry called repackaging, a business that is helping
physicians remold themselves from professionals into entrepreneurs
_ and in the process prompting ethical questions and calls by
legislators for tighter regulation of doctors.
   Repackaging houses are mass production versions of the local
drug store. Instead of one pharmacist counting out pills to fill
one prescription, the repackagers buy antibiotics, decongestants
and other drugs from manufacturers in large lots, then break them
down into bottles that can be resold to individual patients. These
are sealed, labeled and shipped to doctors, who add $2 to $4 per
prescription to the wholesale cost.
   An estimated 8 percent of the nation's 330,000 office-based
doctors have become retailers of repackaged medicines.
   ``The repackagers are trying to remake the role of the doctor as
a patient advocate into something else, in effect, making the
physician a vendor,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who has
sponsored legislation to prohibit doctors from selling
prescriptions for profit.
   ``There is a growing number of fast-buck artists who are telling
doctors they can make $50,000 without any more difficulty than
reaching for a prescription pad.''
   Repackagers say they only are responding to an increasingly
competitive medical profession where anything that brings in
additional patients and income to a practice might make the
difference between success or failure.
   ``The industry developed because there was an opportunity,''
said Dr. Mason Goodman, a lung specialist who is also chief
executive officer at PCA. ``All of the changes in the marketplace
made physicians more receptive to this than they would have been 10
years ago.''
   Indeed, 10 years ago the repackaging industry was just getting
started, but it has grown fast.
   Market analyst Joy Twiss Thompson of Marshall &amp; Co. of Atlanta
predicts 10 percent of the $20 billion annual prescription drug
market will move from the pharmacy to the doctor's office over the
next seven years. She estimates repackagers' revenues will climb
from $25 million in 1986 to more than $75 million this year.
   ``When I survey doctors and nurses to see their attitudes, I
could probably sell 10 to 15 accounts in an average day,'' she
said. ``They have been waiting for a dispensing company. The
repackagers have not had the ability to get out and meet the
demand.''
   Critics say the demand was created in part by hard-sell
brochures and medical journal ads that promised doctors up to
$50,000 a year in additional income. One ad, no longer used by PCA,
talked of $15,000 to $30,000 ``with no additional work.''
   Much of the advertising has cooled, partly in response to
criticism. The repackagers now emphasize physician dispensing as a
convenience to patients and a way to build a practice.
   ``It's not a huge money maker, but it's a great practice
enhancement tool,'' said Goodman of PCA. ``The first law in
medicine is not to erode your patient population. You want to grow
it.''
   Steven Geringer, executive vice president of the Nashville-based
Clinical Pharmaceuticals Inc., puts profits from drug sales at
$8,000 to $10,000 annually for the average doctor.
   Many repackagers say their business strategy was _ and in many
cases still is _ aimed at clinics, ambulatory care centers and
large group practices. Smaller physicians' offices, they say, don't
do the volume of drug sales the repackagers need to make a profit.
   ``This is a business of low margin with high selling costs,''
said Charles Hampton, chairman and president of Allscrips
Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Vernon Hills, Ill. ``About half our
business by number are groups under five, but in terms of volume
they probably account for less than a third of our sales.''
   Allscrips is a good example of how the repackaging industry
began and grew. Founded three years ago by Hampton, a former drug
company executive, and funded with venture capital from Allstate
Insurance Co. and several other groups, the company is approaching
$20 million in annual revenues.
   ``We got into it because there were a lot of things happening in
the market,'' Hampton said. ``There was the growth of the urgent
care centers and the large group practices where they were
traditionally dispensing out of envelopes. There was a change in
the industry in general.''
   But this change has brought calls for tighter regulation of
dispensing doctors.
   While the repackagers are regulated as drug companies under
federal and state law, a recent study by the U.S. Department of
Health and Human Services' inspector general's office found less
governmental scrutiny of drug selling doctors than of pharmacists.
   ``We felt there should be some of the same procedural
requirements that exist for pharmacists, such as record-keeping,
supervision and labeling,'' said Martha Kvaal, a deputy regional
inspector general who headed the study.
   Kvaal also noted some 15 states reported taking disciplinary
action against physicians for dispensing abuses since 1986. Often
it was for procedural errors, such as improper labeling of
medication. But there also have been cases of overprescribing by
physicians who make money from drug sales.
   Such concerns led Rep. Wyden to file a bill last year to ban
doctors from selling drugs for profit. The bill, which failed to
make it to a House vote, was strongly opposed by repackagers, who
formed the Competitive Health Care Coalition and hired Washington
lobbyists and public relation consultants to fight the bill.
   Geringer, who headed the coalition, said the bill would have
killed his industry even though it would still allow physicians to
dispense drugs at cost.
   ``If there weren't any profit in it, the doctors wouldn't do
it,'' Geringer said.
   The repackagers have found an ally in the federal government.
The Federal Trade Commission's Bureau of Competition has endorsed
physician dispensing and even advised Maryland and Georgia against
over-regulation.
   The two states are among some 20 that over the past three years
have tightened regulations on doctors who sell drugs.
   The repackaging industry is likely to flourish. The new Medicare
Catastrophic Coverage Act allows doctors to be reimbursed by the
government for drugs they sell to elderly patients, and repackagers
are lobbying insurers to include doctors in their drug coverage.
   Analysts like Thompson even see repackagers branching into other
products to market through physicians offices' _ weight loss
programs that include diet food, behavior modification tapes and
other materials.
   Geringer see nothing wrong with using doctors' offices as retail
outlets.
   ``If a client is sitting out there, you want to think of other
things you can sell them,'' he said. ``That's true of any
business.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 4</NOTE>
