<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-WalterMears Adv04   06-01 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 04,0907</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 4, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thirty-three Years Later, A Retort To ``We Will Bury You''</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the new world according to President Bush, the
West has won the Cold War _ even though it isn't over yet.
   Time and again, Bush has told the Soviet Union that it is the
losing side. That theme accompanies and helps to explain his drive
for U.S. policy that looks beyond containment of the Soviets.
   After summoning the Atlantic allies to join in an effort to
redraw the military map of Europe with sharp East-West cuts in
conventional weapons, Bush urged that the political map be redrawn,
too.
   And on Western terms.
   He wants to erase lines that carved Europe apart after World War
II. He promises to carry that quest beyond ``the rusting Iron
Curtain'' when he goes to Poland and Hungary next month.
   ``The Cold War began with the division of Europe,'' Bush said in
Mainz, West Germany, on Wednesday. ``It can only end when Europe is
whole.''
   And Bush sees that coming, with ``the liberating power of
democracy'' already at work in eastern Europe. He said the West and
its values have succeeded, while in the Communist world, ``their
vision failed.''
   The words aren't as harsh as the ones Ronald Reagan once used,
consigning the Soviets to the ash heap of history, denouncing their
``evil empire.'' Bush calls them losers, citing their political and
economic performance as evidence.
   ``Winds of change are blowing in Eastern Europe, including the
Soviet Union,'' Bush said in a dinner toast at a West German
castle. ``It is happening, in part, because Mr. Gorbachev has seen
that our society works and that his does not.''
   The president has said repeatedly that he wants the reforms of
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to succeed.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said that is the
administration's hope ``because what he is doing is embracing the
political and economic agenda of the West.''
   ``The West has won,'' Baker said. ``We've won the struggle of
the past 40 years ... The Soviet Union is moving in our direction,
and we ought to continue to encourage their moving in our
direction.''
   Constant reminders of Soviet failures have to be grating in
Moscow.
   Bush's words are, in a way, further rebuttals, 33 years later,
to Nikita S. Khrushchev's claim that ``history is on our side . . .
We will bury you.''
   ``The situation is favorable for us,'' Khrushchev said in 1956.
``If God existed, we would thank him for this.''
   Those taunts echoed for years in U.S. foreign policy debates.
There are no such menacing words from Bush, but what he's saying
may have a political echo inside the Soviet Union, with opponents
of the Gorbachev course.
   Then again, Bush also has a hard-line conservative bloc to
handle at home. His emphasis on ``the momentum for freedom'' as
western political and economic ideas move eastward will soften
conservative opposition to his arms control ideas.
   ``As president, I will continue to do all I can to help open the
closed societies of the East,'' Bush said in Mainz. ``We seek
self-determination for all of Germany and all of Eastern Europe.
And we will not relax and we must not waver.''
   Well aware of his own conservative constituency, Bush and his
aides were careful to note that they are not doing Gorbachev any
favors with the new-look arms control offer.
   ``This proposal is very, very good for the United States,''
Baker said. ``That's why he has suggested it. It's not something
we're doing for the Soviet Union.''
   But no deal flies if it does not have benefits for both sides.
Bush pointed out more than once that by accepting his offer,
Gorbachev could save defense dollars and ease his own economic
problems.
   For good measure, Bush and Baker both have dared Gorbachev to do
some more unilateral arms cutting, to offer deeds to match words.
   ``Prudence and realism will be the standards which will guide
this relationship,'' the secretary of state said. ``The fact that
the president has put a bold proposal on the table doesn't mean
that he has abandoned prudence and realism.''
   Bush and his high command know at first hand the political peril
that can come from the Republican right. They worked for President
Gerald R. Ford during an earlier cycle of thaw followed by Soviet
buildup, during a 1976 campaign in which pressure from Reagan's
Republican right forced the word ``detente'' out of the
administration vocabulary.
   The president also sought to reassure the Soviets that he does
not seek ``to undermine their legitimate security interests. Our
goal is to convince them, step by step, that their definition of
security is obsolete, that their deepest fears are unfounded.''
   That is an ambitious undertaking. Since World War II ended, the
Soviet concept of security has been founded on a Communist zone in
central and eastern Europe. Russian suspicion of the West has
historic roots that go deeper than Communism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 4</NOTE>
