<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-01 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0893</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's chief economic forecasting
gauge jumped 0.8 percent in April, the Commerce Department
reported, easing fears that the nation might be about to tumble
into a recession.
   The increase reported Wednesday in the Index of Leading Economic
Indicators followed declines of 0.3 percent in February and 0.6
percent in March. Three monthly declines in a row has been a
traditional signal of a possible recession on the horizon.
   Still, analysts were not suggesting the strong numbers for April
meant a robust economy this summer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to factories for manufactured goods
rose in April for the second straight month in the biggest increase
since December, the Commerce Department said.
   The strong 2.7 percent April gain reported Wednesday followed a
0.7 percent hike in March and 1.2 percent and 2 percent declines in
January and February. Orders had soared 4.7 percent in December.
   Total orders registered $239.4 billion on a seasonably adjusted
basis in April.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal judge with a reputation as a
corruption fighter and an ex-Wall Street prosecutor were among
three watchdogs appointed to oversee Teamsters union operations.
   The appointments, announced Wednesday at federal court in
Manhattan, were part of the settlement of a civil racketeering
lawsuit against the nation's largest trade union.
   The three overseers appointed are: Frederick B. Lacey, a former
federal judge and U.S. attorney in New Jersey; Charles M. Carberry,
former head of the commodities and securities fraud unit of the
U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan; and Michael H. Holland, former
general counsel to the United Mine Workers of America.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said it will expand from 79 daily
flights in June to 221 in July, the company's largest increase in
service since a strike began March 4.
   Eastern said Wednesday it will serve 27 cities in June and 52 in
July as it moves toward a new full schedule of 600 flights by the
end of the year.
   Separately, travel industry executives meeting in New York said
the strike against Eastern continues to disrupt the Caribbean
tourism industry, slashing business at some hotels and sending air
fares in the region soaring.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading national TV ratings company is
teaming with a well-known technology research concern to develop a
system that measures who watches television by recognizing specific
viewers' faces.
   The entirely passive system theoretically would provide a more
accurate measurement than existing systems that require viewers to
push buttons or write down what they have watched.
   The passive system would use a camera-like recorder programmed
to recognize faces and to note electronically when individual
members of a family watch TV.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that once made asbestos products asked
a federal bankruptcy judge to approve a reorganization plan that
would compensate victims of asbestos-linked diseases and bar future
lawsuits.
   Bankruptcy Judge David H. Coar on Wednesday listened to
arguments on the plan proposed by UNR Industries Inc., whose 1982
filing was the first seeking approval to use Chapter 11 of the
Bankruptcy Code to deal with legal claims.
   Manville Corp. sought similar protection later that year, citing
overwhelming asbestos-related damage claims.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari unveiled
an ambitious plan to transform Mexico's stagnant, debt-burdened
economy into a robust modern engine generating a steady 6 percent
growth a year.
   The National Development Plan for 1989-1994, announced
Wednesday, proposes the ``modernization of the nation in all its
aspects'' during Salinas' 6-year term of office.
   The Salinas administration's 164-page blueprint touches on
everything from drinking water to foreign policy, but the
centerpiece is economics.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop called for
restrictions on alcohol advertising to help curb drunken driving.
   Koop urged Congress Wednesday to support the effort and also
proposed much tougher state blood-alcohol standards to determine
when a driver is legally drunk, increased taxes on all alcoholic
beverages, and a series of voluntary restraints from the industry
and advertising media.
   The recommendations brought immediate protests from the National
Association of Broadcasters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson's son quit a
summer internship in Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s junk bond
department because he was ``bombarded'' with calls from reporters,
a Jackson spokesman said.
   Jonathan Luther Jackson, 23, a business student, started working
May 15 in the much-publicized division once run by indicted Wall
Street financier Michael Milken.
   He resigned Tuesday, Frank Watkins, spokesman for Jackson's
Rainbow Coalition in Washington, D.C., said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks seesawed Wednesday but ended mostly higher, supported by
a late recovery in the bond market. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 4.60 points to close at 2,480.15.
   The dollar slumped amid speculation about central bank
maneuvering. Gold prices fell in New York trading after rising in
the Far East and Europe.
   Bond prices rebounded in late trading.
   Coffee futures prices sank; precious metals slid; grains and
soybeans were mostly lower; energy futures were mixed; cattle
futures were mixed and pork futures advanced.
</TEXT>
