<FIRST>r f PM-AutoIncentives     06-01 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Incentives,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Expands Jeep Incentives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s Jeep-Eagle Division
has extended $1,000 rebate offers to all of its Jeep Cherokee and
Wagoneer models.
   The company said Wednesday that buyers could choose the rebates
or financing ranging from 4.9 percent interest for two-year loans
to 11.9 percent for five-year loans. The offer runs indefinitely.
   In early April, Chrysler reacted to incentive programs announced
by Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. by offering a variety of
rebates and interest-free financing on two-year loans on all of its
cars and Jeep Comanche and Grand Wagoneer models.
   Those offers also run indefinitely.
   Meantime, Ford said that incentives that have been in effect
since late March on a wide variety of its cars and trucks were
expiring at midnight Wednesday. It was expected that Ford may
announce a new incentive package on Thursday.
   Since Ford began the latest round of rebates and low-interest
financing deals, the nation's No. 2 automaker has increased some,
added models and extended existing offers.
   Many of GM's incentives are to expire June 5.
</TEXT>
