<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TVMeters Bjt   06-01 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Meters, Bjt,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Ratings Company Joins Sarnoff Center on Passive Meter Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advertising agency and network officials say
they are encouraged by an effort by the leading national TV ratings
company to develop a system that measures who watches television by
recognizing viewers' faces.
   They said they agreed with the sponsors' assessment that the
passive measurement system would provide a more accurate reading of
TV audiences than existing systems that require viewers to push
buttons or write down what they have watched.
   The passive system would use a camera-like recorder programmed
to recognize faces and to note electronically when specific members
of a family watch TV.
   Nielsen Media Research, the Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp. unit that
compiles national TV ratings, announced Wednesday that it had
reached an agreement with the David Sarnoff Research Center of
Princeton, N.J., to jointly develop the passive TV-viewing
measurement system.
   The system could have potentially wide-reaching effects on a
medium that carried nearly $25 billion in advertising last year.
   It is being developed as advertisers are demanding more proof
and media outlets such as the TV networks are under more pressure
to show that advertising is reaching its intended targets. Ratings
are used to help set prices for commercial time.
   ``We support their effort 110 percent,'' said Richard Kostyra,
director of media services for the ad agency J. Walter Thompson.
   He said the passive system brings researchers closer to
measuring ``actually what is happening'' rather than relying on a
survey group's cooperation in pushing buttons or writing down what
they watched.
   Nielsen has been measuring national TV audiences with a ``people
meter'' system since 1987 that automatically records the channel a
set is tuned to while relying on those watching to punch in when
they start watching TV and punch out when they leave.
   For local ratings, Nielsen has people note in diaries what shows
each member of the family watched during a given period.
   Advertisers and the television networks long have complained
that systems requiring viewers to do something while they are
watching TV may distort estimates of who is watching specific shows.
   John A. Dimling, a top marketing executive for Nielsen, said a
passive system should yield ``even higher quality, more accurate
data because the respondents don't have to do anything'' other than
``be themselves.''
   Dimling said the passive system could eliminate the problem of
people who simply grow weary of pushing a button each time they
start or quit watching TV.
   The networks have argued that children, for instance, often fail
to punch the people meter buttons and say the ratings therefore
understate the audience for children's programming.
   Bill Reubens, who as an NBC research executive was very critical
of the introduction of people meters, said the passive meter system
``would be a major step forward.''
   ``I think everybody felt the people meter was an intermediate
step,'' said Reubens, who retired from NBC at the end of 1988 but
continues to do consulting on ratings methodology for NBC, CBS and
ABC.
   Dimling said the passive system could also someday be used to
measure who is watching individual commercials as well as shows.
   Nielsen selected the Sarnoff Research Center as its partner in
the passive meter project because of the center's extensive work in
image recognition.
   Sarnoff, formerly the research arm of RCA Corp. but now , calls
its image recognition approach ``Smart-Sensing'' and would use it
in connection with TV audience measurement to recognize the faces
of those watching television.
   The sensory equipment could be packaged to resemble a
videocassette recorder and placed on top of the television set. It
would electronically record the names of those it recognizes and
the periods during which they watched television. Strangers would
be listed simply as visitors.
   Asked whether the system is ``too Big Brotherish,'' Dimling
said, ``I don't think we are talking about Big Brother here at
all.''
   He said the system would not film or otherwise record anything
that goes on in the room other than the names of those watching TV.
And he noted the equipment would be installed only in homes where
families agree to it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0333 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Tourism Bjt   06-01 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Tourism, Bjt,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caribbean Tourism Feeling Impact of Eastern Strike, Executives Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Caribbean tourism industry continues to be
pinched by the 3-month-old strike against Eastern Airlines, with
business slashed at some hotels and air fares in the region
soaring, some travel industry executives say.
   ``It makes a tremendous difference ... it's a major concern to
us,'' John Bell, executive vice president of the Caribbean Hotel
Association, said in an interview Wednesday.
   Bell said some hotels in the popular resort region had lost as
much as 40 percent of their business this season due to the strike
by Machinists union members, pilots and flight attendants against
Miami-based Eastern, which began March 4 and sharply curtailed the
airline's operations.
   The losses were greatest in the Bahamas and Puerto Rico, said
Bell, whose association represents 740 hotels in 31 Caribbean
countries.
   Eastern has reduced its Caribbean operations to flights to the
Bahamas, Puerto Rico and Haiti, compared with its pre-strike
schedule of about a dozen Caribbean destinations.
   The president of one large tour operator that sought bankruptcy
protection from creditors due to the impact of the Eastern walkout
said discount fares to the Caribbean now cost substantially more
than last year and are less available.
   Joseph Garzilli, president of Flyfaire Inc., considered one of
the biggest U.S. tour operators specializing in Caribbean vacation
packages, said the cheapest round-trip fare between New York and
San Juan, Puerto Rico, was $249 on American Airlines, compared with
$174 last year on Eastern.
   ``There have been some great voids in the marketplace,'' said
Garzilli, whose Hawthorne, N.Y.-based business sought protection
from creditors on March 13, four days after Eastern did so.
   Garzilli said the retreat of Eastern, which had been the leader
in discount fares to the Caribbean, means cheaper fares are
``slowly slipping away.''
   Some competitors, such as American and Eastern's sister carrier,
Continental Airlines, have increased their flights in the region
since the Eastern strike.
   Flyfaire, which had used Eastern flights as the basis for about
70 percent of its tour packages, says Eastern owes it about $1.5
million. Garzilli said, however, that Flyfaire has continued
operating under bankruptcy protection and doesn't plan to sever its
relationship with Eastern if the airline returns to the Caribbean.
   Bell spoke earlier at a news conference announcing a new program
by which travel agents dealing with Flyfaire would make payments to
Caribbean hotels. Mark MacKenzie, a senior director of Citicorp
Services Inc. in Chicago, said the Eastern situation had aggravated
the long-standing problem of hotel payment delays in the region.
   Eastern stopped paying creditors, including tour operators,
after it sought bankruptcy court protection. That in turn delayed
or dried up payments by those businesses to hotels.
   Under the new hotel payment program, all payments to Caribbean
hotels from Flyfaire vacation packages will be processed through
Citicorp's World Travel Payment system. Citicorp will receive
payments from travel agents and send them directly to hotels.
   Traditionally, payments to hotels in the Caribbean pass through
airlines or tour operators, often causing delays of up to four
months, industry executives say.
   If the new system had been in place before the Eastern strike,
Flyfaire wouldn't have been forced into a bankruptcy proceeding,
Garzilli said, because the tour operator wouldn't have had to rely
on payments from Eastern to pass on to hotels.
   Other Caribbean tour operators are expected to join Flyfaire in
the program, Citicorp's MacKenzie said.
   Eastern management plans to rebuild Eastern into a smaller
carrier and sell about $1.8 billion of its assets. Some financial
analysts and other observers believe the carrier might sell its
Caribbean routes under the plan.
   The Eastern plan still must be approved by the federal
bankruptcy court in New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
