<SECOND>BC-Maxicare Layoffs,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>100 Layoffs at Health Plan in Chapter 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxicare Health Plans Inc., which is
operating under the protection of bankruptcy court, will lay off
100 of its 700 headquarters staff.
   The layoffs, to be finished by July 28, follow the sale of 20 of
the company's health maintenance organizations in recent months,
Maxicare said in announcing the decision Wednesday.
   Maxicare, once the nation's largest publicly traded HMO with
more than 2 million members, is operating under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy code, which allows a company to try to salvage
itself through reorganization.
   Wracked by losses blamed on an ambitious expansion program, the
company filed for Chapter 11 protection from its creditors in U.S.
District Court in Santa Ana in March.
   The company currently operates in California, Illinois, Indiana,
Louisiana, North Carolina, Ohio, South Carolina and Wisconsin.
