<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-EuropeTrade     06-01 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Europe Trade,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Report Sees Danger to Trade With Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional report warns of danger to 2
million American jobs and $75 billion worth of U.S. exports because
of the efforts by West European countries to eliminate internal
trade barriers by 1992.
   The plans of the European Community are sometimes called
``EC-92.'' A congressional subcommittee has been holding hearings
on their effect.
   ``Witness after witness, 21 in all, argued that despite many
benefits of EC-92 to U.S. business, key aspects... were already
reducing, and would continue to reduce, American exports to the EC
and U.S. jobs in critical sectors of the economy,'' Rep. Sam
Gejdenson, D-Conn., said Wednesday.
   Gejdenson chairs the subcommittee on international economic
policy of the House Foreign Affairs Committee. The subcommittee
approved the report without dissent, but only three of the 13
members attended the session.
   Gejdenson singled out the process by which the European
governments are setting standards for their industries. He said the
Europeans do not let outside observers take part in the process,
while U.S. standard-setting is open.
   He said he had not heard of the agreement, announced earlier
Wednesday, to resume talks on standards this summer. The Commerce
Department said U.S. products would get the same access to testing
and certification procedures as European products. Ella Krucoff,
press officer for the EC delegation in Washington, said that did
not mean American firms _ except those with subsidiaries in Europe
_ could take part in setting the standards.
   Gejdenson also complained that:
   _European rules require that some imported products, such as
auto parts and electronic equipment, be manufactured partially
within the 12 member countries.
   ``Though many of the policies requiring a high level of European
content in products assembled in the EC are aimed at Japan, the
effect(s) of these policies are already being felt by the U.S.
electronics industry,'' he said.
   _In some cases American companies will not be treated the same
way as EC companies after 1992. ``This would likely result in a
continuing U.S. inability to win bids for contracts in the $600
billion per year EC government procurement market,'' Gejdenson said.
   The subcommittee recommended:
   _That the Bush administration adopt a more aggressive strategy
instead of reacting to European decisions.
   _That a firm timetable be set for negotiations with the EC
unless difficulties are settled in the 96-government ``Uruguay
round'' of trade talks
   _The United States press for observer status at sessions where
European industry standards are set.
   _An increase in the staffing level of the U.S. mission to the EC
in Brussels and of groups analyzing EC decisions
   ``While taking a hard line on protectionist EC-92 policies may
cause friction in the short run, such actions will improve
long-term U.S.-EC trade relations,'' Gejdenson predicted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0341 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 0803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HughesLayoffs     06-01 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hughes Layoffs,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Layoff of 6,000 Latest Fallout of Defense Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the latest shock wave to hit the aerospace
industry from Pentagon budget-tightening, Hughes Aircraft Co.
announced it would lay off 6,000 workers over the next six months.
   The layoffs announced Wednesday, which amount to 8 percent of
Hughes' workforce, follow smaller reductions at Northrop Corp. and
Grumman Corp. Analysts predict the Bush administration's
tight-fisted approach to defense spending will bring further
layoffs and cut into profits in the aerospace industry.
   ``It presumably is the first blast of winter in the defense
environment but I don't think it will be the last,'' said Wolfgang
Demisch, who follows the industry for UBS Securities Inc. in New
York.
   Hughes will lay off workers in all areas of management,
engineering and manufacturing, the company said.
   Hughes, a General Motors Corp. subsidiary, has 75,000 employees
in 12 states, with the bulk of its work force in Southern
California and around Tucson, Ariz.
   Hughes will try to cushion the blow by making some staff cuts
through attrition and voluntary resignations, and offering
retraining and job-hunting help.
   The company's Pentagon work includes manufacture of air-to-air
and air-to-ground missiles, satellites, radar for fighter jets and
other military gear.
   The decision was based on executives' expectation that defense
budgets under the Bush administration will be smaller than they
were under Ronald Reagan, the company said.
   ``We're getting down to fighting trim,'' said Malcolm Currie,
Hughes' chairman and chief executive officer.
   Industry-wide aerospace employment fell 1.7 percent in 1988, to
1.3 million, largely because of slower military sales attributed to
a slowing of the defense buildup begun by Reagan. A similar decline
is expected this year, according to the Aerospace Industries
Association, which compiles the figures.
   The administration's 1990 budget before Congress would devote
$295.6 billion to the military, down from the $305.6 billion
proposed by the outgoing Reagan administration and below the $299.3
billion earmarked for this year. Because the bulk of military
spending is for such fixed-cost items as salary and retirement
benefits, the brunt of any cuts falls on development and purchase
of hardware.
   The result: Fewer contracts for new aerospace programs,
stretched-out buying schedules for programs already under way and
layoffs at companies trying to maintain their profits.
   ``Every company in the business will be touched by job losses
over the next year or two,'' predicted Howard Rubel, an industry
analyst at Cyrus J. Lawrence in New York.
   Grumman has announced plans to lay off 3,000 on Long Island, New
York, and Los Angeles-based Northrop says it plans to cut its
44,000-member work force by 2,500 to 3,000 over the course of the
year.
   To some extent, job losses in this normally cyclical industry
will be offset by a boom in civilian airliner construction.
   But only two U.S. companies, Boeing Corp. and McDonnell Douglas
Corp. make big civilian planes, and civil aviation accounts for
only about 30 percent of the industry.
   Hughes' layoffs aren't a response to changes in any one
contract, said spokesman Mike Murphy, who noted that no one
contract accounts for more than 6 percent of sales, he said.
   However, the company may be smarting from Pentagon decisions in
the last two years to qualify a second company to submit
competitive bids on several key Hughes contracts. Among the weapons
are three plane-launched missiles, the AMRAAM, Maverick and
Phoenix, which Raytheon Corp. won the right to bid on.
   GM doesn't reveal separate financial data for Hughes Aircraft.
GM-Hughes Electronics Corp., the aircraft company's parent,
reported profit of $256.9 million on sales of $11.24 billion in
1988. That was down from profit of $219.2 million on sales of
$10.48 billion the year before.
</TEXT>
