<FIRST>r f PM-MinorityEngineers 1stLd-Writethru f0023 06-01 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minority Engineers, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0023,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 1:30 p.m. EDT, TIME set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Number Of Beginning Engineering Students Shows First Rise Since 1982</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to clarify minorities made up half the total increase.
Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Freshman engineering enrollments rose last
fall for the first time since 1982, with minorities making up more
than half the increase, the National Action Council for Minorities
in Engineering said today.
   Black, Hispanic and American Indian students accounted for 55
percent of a 2.7 percent increase in freshman enrollment from fall
1987 to fall 1988, the organization reported. Those students posted
a 13.8 percent gain _ from 10,325 in 1987 to 11,754 in 1988.
   The rise in minority participation comes at a time of increasing
concern over an anticipated shortfall of science and engineering
professionals. The National Science Foundation estimates that by
the year 2000, the nation will turn out 400,000 fewer scientists
and engineers than it needs.
   Council President George Campbell said the minority engineering
gains reflect changing demographics as well as efforts by several
organizations to increase minority participation in technical
fields. He said his own group spent $1.1 million over three years
on more than 20 programs designed to introduce minority students to
engineering careers and help them develop the academic skills
needed to enter the field.
   The increase in enrollments contrasts with the low rate of
minority engineering graduates, which Campbell puts at between 36
percent and 40 percent. The graduation rate nationally is 70
percent, while for Asians it is 100 percent.
   ``There is an ongoing problem'' with blacks, Hispanics and
American Indians leaving the field, Campbell said, adding there has
been some recent progress in retaining those students from their
freshman to sophomore to junior years. ``We can't count them as
having been retained until they graduate,'' he said.
   ``But we have seen fewer freshmen dropping out than in previous
years so in 1989, 1990 and 1991 we expect to see some improvement
in retention rates,'' Campbell said.
   A plethora of reports from teachers, corporations, universities,
associations and government agencies have cited the need to improve
math and science education in the lower grades and generate more
interest among women and minorities, who make up a growing
proportion of the nation's work force.
   According to the action council, one out of three Americans will
be non-white by the turn of the century, but only 6 percent of
annual engineering graduates currently are black, Hispanic or
American Indian.
   Citing data from the Engineering Manpower Commission, the
council said American Indians made the most dramatic percentage
gain in freshman enrollment from 1987 to 1988, up 22.3 percent from
354 to 433. Blacks also showed a substantial increase, up 15.1
percent compared with a 4.6 boost the year before. Hispanic
freshman enrollment increased 11 percent, slightly less than a 13.9
percent hike from 1986 to 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
