<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Court Examiner To Report No Viable Offers For Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 new grafs to UPDATE with cut-rate fares.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The court-appointed bankruptcy examiner for
Eastern Airlines is expected to report at a hearing today that no
viable offers have been made for the airline, The New York Times
reported in today's editions.
   Miami-based Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
from its creditors March 9, five days after the start of a strike
by the Machinists union that has been supported by pilots and
flight attendants.
   David I. Shapiro was appointed by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton
R. Lifland in New York as an examiner to help reorganize the
carrier, which is a division of Texas Air Corp. of Houston.
   The Times, citing anonymous sources, said Shapiro will report
today that no acceptable buyout bids for the carrier have been
received.
   The lack of an offer deemed acceptable by Shapiro is expected to
reduce the leverage of Eastern's three main unions in their
3-month-old strike.
   The unions recently have supported proposed buyout proposals
from two investor groups, one led by former Piedmont Airlines
chairman William Howard and the other by Chicago commodities trader
Joseph Ritchie. Shapiro has challenged the two groups to put at
least $100 million of their own cash at risk.
   Management, on the other hand, is proceeding with a plan to
rebuild Eastern as a smaller carrier and sell $1.8 billion of its
assets.
   Eastern on Wednesday announced an expanded schedule that it said
will allow the company to recall by July more than 1,700 non-union
workers placed on ``no work'' status when the airline curtailed
service shortly after the strike started.
   Eastern said it has 5,000 employees now and eventually will have
about 17,000, compared with a pre-strike total of about 30,000.
   Eastern said it will expand from 79 daily flights in June to 221
in July, the company's largest increase in service since the strike
began.
   The airline said it would offer bargain fares of $39 to $139 on
domestic tickets, including a one-way New York-Miami fare of $79
and $59 between New York and Atlanta. The only requirement is a
three-day advance purchase.
   Eastern said it also will offer first-class tickets at $10 below
the normal full coach fare to attract business travelers.
   ``Because of the turmoil here, we'll need to use price as an
incentive to get customers to try us again,'' said company
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak in Miami.
</TEXT>
