<FIRST>r f PM-ClintonShutdown     06-01 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clinton Shutdown,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Plant Shut Down After Leak Discovered</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear power plant was shut down early
today after a faulty seal in a pump spilled hundreds of gallons of
slightly radioactive water around the base of the reactor,
officials said.
   No injuries were reported and no radiation was released to the
environment, Illinois Power Co. spokesman Frank Beman said. ``Our
workers and the public were never in danger. It was an orderly
shutdown.''
   The low-level radioactive leak prompted plant officials to call
an alert, Nuclear Regulatory Commission spokesman Frank Ingram
said. That was downgraded to an ``unusual event'' 24 minutes later,
he said from the NRC's Rockville, Md., headquarters. By 3:25 a.m.,
the plant was reported back on normal status.
   Beman said only about 10 such alerts are issued each year by
nuclear power plants.
   It was the first such incident at the Clinton plant, which came
into full operation last year. The plant was restarted May 27 after
being down for refueling and was operating at about 40 percent of
capacity at the time of today's problem.
   The pump which leaked feeds water into the reactor, where it is
heated into steam that spins turbines and powers the generators.
   ``The water collected in a well at the base (of the reactor) and
we're going to start cleanup as soon as we can,'' Beman said. ``The
cleanup should be completed by this weekend, then we'll repair the
pump and expect to be back up in a few days.''
   Beman said he could not be more specific about the plant's
return to operation. Clinton is the only nuclear power plant
operated by Illinois Power and provides one-third of the
electricity used by the Decatur-based utility's half-million
customers in central Illinois.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
