<SECOND>BC-Father-Son Scheme,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father, Son Charged With Insider Trading In Lucky Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father-son duo was charged with insider
trading in an alleged scheme that netted $328,844 in stock-trading
profits ahead of American Stores Co.'s takeover of Lucky Stores
Inc. last year.
   David Hellberg, a financial specialist with American Stores unit
Alpha Beta, was accused by the federal government Wednesday of
tipping off his father, Gerald Hellberg last March about the plans
to buy Lucky.
   The elder Hellberg used the information to buy Lucky stock
options, then sold the securities at a large profit when the
takeover plans were announced, the Securities and Exchange
Commission charged.
   The pair deny the charges.
   ``I believe the charges are without merit, and I intend to
defend them vigorously,'' said David Hellberg, reached by phone in
Salt Lake City. His father, a Salt Lake City retiree, also denied
the allegations.
   In a suit filed in federal District Court, the SEC said American
Stores officials had asked David Hellberg to prepare a computer
program to forecast the financial effects of acquiring the rival
Lucky chain.
   The government alleges that the younger Hellberg knew of
American Stores' takeover plans by March 13, 1987, and tipped off
his father by telephone that same day.
   Two months later Lucky agreed to be acquired by American Stores
for $2.5 billion.
   The elder Hellberg allegedly purchased some $15,049 in Lucky
stock options, whose value soared as much as 25-fold after plans
for the takeover were announced, the SEC alleges.
</TEXT>
