<FIRST>u f PM-ConstructionSpending     06-01 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Construction Spending,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Edges Up 0.1 Percent in April</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending, propped up by an
increase in work on government projects, edged up a slim 0.1
percent in April after dropping in the previous three months, the
Commerce Department said today.
   Overall, spending on both public and private construction
projects rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $414.9
billion in April after dropping 0.3 percent in March, 0.6 percent
in February and 0.7 percent in January.
   The January-March string of declines had marked the first time
construction spending dropped three times in a row since it fell
for five straight months from February through June 1981, just
before the start of the 1981-82 recession.
   The construction industry has been among the sectors of the
economy hardest hit in recent months by the Federal Reserve's
campaign to push up interest rates to slow economic growth and thus
restrain inflation.
   April's spending level was 4.7 percent above the pace in April
1988.
   Spending on public construction projects rose 5.7 percent in
April to a seasonally adjusted $79.3 billion. The increase included
an 8.9 percent rise in construction on highways and streets, the
biggest government category.
   The increase in spending on government projects barely offset
declines in private construction of both residential and
non-residential buildings.
   Spending on private, non-residential construction projects fell
4.8 percent in April to an annual rate of $97.2 billion, reflecting
a downturn in spending on offices, motels and hotels, hospitals,
and other commercial buildings.
   Construction of new housing units, meanwhile, fell 1.3 percent
to an annual rate of $141.8 billion after falling 1.2 percent in
March. Spending on single-family homes dropped 2.3 percent, while
construction of multi-family units rose 2.9 percent.
</TEXT>
