<SECOND>BC-Ford Moves,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford's Great-Grandson Promoted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edsel Ford II, the great-grandson of Ford
Motor Co.'s founder, on Thursday was named executive director of
the automaker's marketing staff, effective next month.
   Philip E. Benton Jr., president of the Ford Automotive Group,
said Ford, general sales manager of the company's Lincoln-Mercury
Division for two years, would succeed Douglas McClure, who retires
Nov. 1 after 42 years with the company.
   Ford, 40, will direct the company's worldwide marketing
operations and will be responsible for the company's corporate
advertising program and its research, long-range planning and
strategies covering vehicle distribution, according to a news
release.
   He is one of two of Henry Ford's great-grandsons active in
company affairs. The other, William Clay Ford Jr., becomes head of
the company's heavy-truck engineering and manufacturing operations
next month after heading Ford of Switzerland for nearly two years.
   Both are members of the company's board of directors. Late last
year, Edsel Ford complained that he and his 32-year-old cousin, son
of retired Ford Vice Chairman William Clay Ford, held relatively
meaningless positions on the board.
   Following the company's annual meeting last month, the cousins
were appointed to the board's executive and audit committees.
