<FIRST>u f PM-Productivity 1stLd-Writethru   06-01 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Productivity, 1st Ld-Writethru,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revised Figures Show Productivity Drop; Greater Gain In Labor Costs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 6 to CORRECT 5.4 percent to 5.2 percent; moved general
news wires also.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Productivity in the non-farm business sector
of the economy fell at an annual rate of 1.1 percent in the first
quarter, helping trigger a significant increase in unit labor
costs, the government reported today.
   The Labor Department's revised data for first-quarter
productivity should prove disturbing to analysts who have said
improved output per hour by American workers is essential to curb
inflation and make up for labor shortages in some fields.
   The government in May had reported productivity, on a seasonally
adjusted annual rate, rose 0.5 percent in the first three months of
1989 compared to the final quarter of 1988. That report also listed
a 5.2 percent increase, at an annual rate as well, in unit labor
costs for the first quarter.
   But revised data released today showed productivity declined at
an annual rate of 1.1 percent as output rose 2.2 percent while
hours worked climbed 3.4 percent from the prior quarter.
   That compared to a 1.0 percent gain in productivity on an annual
basis n the fourth quarter of 1988 and a 1.5 percent gain reported
for all of last year.
   Unit labor costs rose 6.6 percent in the quarter on an annual
basis, up from the 5.2 percent reported in the preliminary data in
May and higher still than the 4.1 percent increase reported in the
fourth quarter of 1988.
   The jump in unit labor costs reflected the decline in
productivity and a 5.4 percent increase, on an annual basis, of
hourly wages in the quarter. That figure was revised downward from
the previously reported 5.7 percent but was still up from the 5.2
percent annual increase reported for the fourth quarter and the 4.6
percent jump for all of 1988.
   But the data showed consumer inflation continues to erode the
wage gains made by workers.
   Although hourly pay on average climbed 5.4 percent on an annual
basis in the first quarter, real hourly compensation was unchaged
because consumer prices rose at the same rate as wages.
   In the manufacturing sector, productivity in the first quarter
rose 2.1 percent on an annual basis, down from the 3.8 percent gain
reported in May's preliminary data. Revised data showed output rose
2.8 percent in that sector while hours worked climbed by 0.7
percent. Unit labor costs in manufacturing rose a revised 2.0
percent in the first quarter on an annual basis.
   Th sector reporting the most significant productivity declines
was non-financial corporations, which reported a 1.3 percent drop
in output per hour in the first quarter. That figure was unchanged
from the previous data but the downward revisions in other sectors
brought overall non-farm productivity into a decline.
   In the overall business sector, which includes agriculture,
productivity was up 1.7 percent in the first quarter at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate, down from the 3.5 percent gain
reported in May's early data for the first quarter.
</TEXT>
