<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-01 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Lower On Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were modestly
lower in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade
following a night of steady rain in the upper Midwest.
   The showers were moving south, and more rain was predicted for
the region, which was good news for corn and soybean growers but
bearish for the markets.
   A National Weather Service 6-to-10-day outlook issued after the
close of trading Wednesday helped to further dampen fears of a
recurrence of last year's drought. The agency predicted normal
rainfall for the Corn Belt for the five days beginning Tuesday.
   Prices for near-term deliveries of soybeans were off more
sharply than those for fall, or new-crop deliveries, an indication
that traders were taking profits after several weeks of selling the
new-crop contracts and buying the old crop.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents
to 2{ cents lower with July at $2.59 a bushel; oats were 1{ cents
to 2{ cents lower with July at $1.64} a bushel; soybeans were 2{
cents to 5 cents lower with July at $7.09 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent to .35 cent higher with June at 69.07
cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .33 cent higher with
August at 76.70 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent to .18 cent
higher with June at 48.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.15 cent to .23 cent higher with July at 30.05 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
advanced.
</TEXT>
