<FIRST>u f PM-PrimeComputer     06-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Lowers Offer For Prime Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. lowered its offer for Prime
Computer Inc. today and said it had firm commitments of financing
needed to complete the deal.
   Although the offer was lower than the old one, which was valued
at about $970 million, investors apparently thought it was more
credible.
   Prime was up 37{ cents a share at $16.75 in early composite New
York Stock Exchange trading today after gaining 25 cents a share on
Wednesday.
   Prime said it was evaluating the offer.
   The new offer is $19.50 a share in cash for the 49.5 million
shares of Prime currently outstanding, plus securities with a face
value of $21 a share for other shares of Prime that could be issued
through the exercise of options.
   The old offer was $20 a share, all in cash, for all shares.
Investors are likely to value the paper portion of the offer at
less than the stated $21 a share, so it is hard to put a total
value on the new offer.
   MAI Basic, a computer maker based in Tustin, Calif., has been
pursuing Prime since November. It is about a fourth the size of
Prime, a maker of minicomputers and computer-aided design equipment
based in Natick, Mass.
   MAI Basic came up with the new, lower bid after Prime last month
challenged it to come up with financing for the old bid or drop it.
   Bennett S. LeBow, the chairman of MAI Basic, said it lowered the
bid because Prime's earnings projections had worsened and Prime had
created potentially expensive employee-benefit and pension plans,
known as ``golden parachutes.''
   MAI Basic said its $1.4 billion backing for the new bid
consisted of $550 million from Drexel Burnham Lambert Group Inc.,
$400 million from Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce, $300 million
from Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. and $150 million from Brooke Partners LP.
   The money would go to pay off old debts, buy Prime and provide
working capital for the combined company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
