<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     06-01 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0308</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market worked its way higher today as
traders tried to sort out the Federal Reserve's next move in
setting its credit policy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.64 to 2,488.79 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 6 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with
690 up, 587 down and 536 unchanged.
   Hopes have been increasing for some time in the financial world
that the Federal Reserve might soon begin to ease credit, seeking
to cushion a slowing economy against the risk of recession.
   But some doubts have been voiced lately about the likelihood and
prospective timing of any such action.
   The picture of a dropoff in the pace of business was blurred a
bit Wednesday by reports showing strength in factory orders and the
index of leading economic indicators in April.
   The Fed's strategy may be strongly influenced, analysts said, by
the monthly statistics due out Friday on the employment situation
in May.
   Advance estimates call for the data to show an increase of about
200,000 in nonfarm payroll employment, up from 117,000 in April but
still well below the pace set in the first quarter of the year.
   Gainers among ther blue chips included USX, up { at 35];
International Business Machines, up 1 at 110|; General Motors, up |
at 41, and Eastman Kodak, up 1 at 45}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .52 to 179.37. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .37 at 357.03.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 83.54 million shares at
noontime, up from 73.66 million at the same point Wednesday.
</TEXT>
