<FIRST>u f AM-Giuliani-WallStreet Bjt   06-01 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Giuliani-Wall Street, Bjt,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street Execs Are `Friends' of Prosecutor Who Led Fraud Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hand that's feeding New York mayoral
candidate Rudolph Giuliani is the same one he was biting not long
ago.
   In five and a half years as Manhattan U.S. attorney, Giuliani
engineered highly public investigations of Wall Street investment
firms and denounced what he termed ``systemic'' insider trading
abuses.
   Now he's getting major campaign support from top lawyers and
executives on Wall Street, where some labeled him as a
publicity-mad zealot who abused his considerable prosecutorial
powers to crack down on securities fraud.
   ``The fact that I made a contribution to his mayoral effort has
nothing to do with his performance in any case _ or lack of
performance,'' said attorney Paul J. Curran, who butted heads with
Giuliani over an insider trading case in which an arbitrager was
handcuffed and frisked before his colleagues.
   More than 20 top executives are included in an inner circle of
about 145 ``Friends of Rudy Giuliani,'' who raised more than
$800,000 at a $500-a-plate campaign luncheon at the Waldorf Astoria
hotel this week.
   Major players from Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.,
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co., Salomon Brothers Inc., Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc., Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. and PaineWebber Inc. are on
the list.
   The roster also includes the head of Donaldson, Lufkin and
Jenrette Inc., one of the nation's 15 largest securities firms; two
general partners at the investment bank Lazard Freres & Co.; and a
founder of the leveraged buyout powerhouse Forstmann, Little &amp; Co.
   ``I don't think it's surprising because I think the people on
Wall Street have the same concerns as other people in the city
have,'' said Giuliani press secretary Charles Perkins. ``The
problems of crime and corruption are problems whether you work on
Wall Street or ... at a factory in the Bronx.''
   Giuliani is vying with multimillionaire businessman Ronald S.
Lauder for the Republican nomination in a bid to unseat 12-year
Democratic Mayor Edward I. Koch, who is facing challenges within
his own party.
   Many of Giuliani's pin-striped supporters said they are backing
the 44-year-old former prosecutor because he is the first strong
Republican contender for mayor in this heavily Democratic city
since John V. Lindsay in the 1960s.
   They like his tough pledge to ``take back the city'' from
violent criminals, drug dealers and ``crooked politicians who have
abandoned their oath of office.'' They want him to improve public
education because, as one Wall Street supporter said, ``I can't get
a receptionist that can type.''
   Some even say Giuliani's highly publicized campaign against
financial sleaze was just what Wall Street needed in a decade of
excess.
   ``Look, he did a job he was supposed to do,'' said Muriel
Siebert, the first woman member of the New York Stock Exchange, who
heads her own brokerage firm. ``I really feel, if you want the
truth, that we've had a hell of a lot of greed downtown.''
   Under Giuliani, who stepped down at the end of January, the
Manhattan U.S. attorney's office brought charges in more than 50
securities fraud cases, using aggressive tactics that agitated many
in the financial community.
   The most frequently cited case of excessiveness was the February
1987 arrest of Robert Freeman, a partner at Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.,
and two Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. executives, one of whom was taken in
handcuffs and tears from the firm's trading floor.
   Three months later charges against the three were dropped and,
despite promises from Giuliani, no new indictments have been
brought. Giuliani has conceded that the arrests were made too soon.
   His nemesis in that case was Freeman's attorney, Curran, now a
campaign financier. Curran said the case hasn't affected his
support for Giuliani, a longtime friend and assistant prosecutor
under Curran in the mid-1970s.
   ``I do my commenting on the Freeman case in court,'' Curran said.
   ``That's Curran,'' said securities defense lawyer Stanley Arkin,
who represented one of the two Kidder executives and is not
endorsing Giuliani's cause. ``Some people have put it aside and
some haven't.''
   The latter group includes Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., Kidder
Peabody and Goldman Sachs _ all major targets during Giuliani's
tenure. No one from those firms is listed as a ``Friend of Rudy
Giuliani.''
   ``We're all aware of what the criticism is,'' said Giuliani
backer Chris Randolph, a Shearson senior vice president. ``Over
time I think we will know whether there is a legitimate criticism
or not.''
</TEXT>
