<DOCNO> AP890601-0370 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Economy     06-01 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Economy,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resurgent Inflation, Labor Unrest Threaten British Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Reagan traveled to Britain a year
ago, the country was basking in economic glory. But President
Bush's visit comes against a far different backdrop.
   Inflation and labor strikes, familiar symptoms of the 1970s
British economic disease, are putting a damper on Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's economic revolution.
   As Bush met with Mrs. Thatcher this week, London was disrupted
by its fifth 24-hour subway strike this year. BBC journalists and
technicians have curtailed television and radio programs. Dock
workers are threatening to walk away from Britain's 40 ports.
   The strikes are hardly comparable to the disruption that helped
topple the Labor Party government in 1979, and inflation is still
below the 10.3-percent level when Mrs. Thatcher took office a
decade ago.
   But Goldman Sachs International said in its monthly economic
review: ``The recent upsurge in labor unrest raises unpleasant
memories of the 1970s and must cast still more doubt on how much
the United Kingdom has really changed under Mrs. Thatcher.''
   By championing free markets, keeping a tight grip on fiscal
spending and curbing union power, Mrs. Thatcher transformed an
ailing economy into a boom that has been hailed as a miracle. Gross
domestic product grew nearly 4 percent in 1988 and is expected to
grow by up to 2.8 percent this year.
   While the strikes may be only sporadic, a more ominous threat
lies in resurgent inflation, rising interest rates and a sudden
weakening of the British pound.
   A year ago, Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's sweeping
tax cuts made him the hero of his Conservative Party. Now the
British press is speculating that Mrs. Thatcher will oust him in a
Cabinet reshuffle before July, and on Wednesday the pound dipped on
rumors that he had already quit.
   A recent poll showed that the Labor Party, having dumped some of
its vote-losing defense and socialist doctrines, has a 43-percent
approval rating, two points ahead of the Conservatives.
   Experts say odds are rising that the economy will suffer a
slowdown, or what they call ``a hard landing.''
   ``Less has changed since the 1970s than might have been hoped,''
said a report by the independent National Institute of Economic and
Social Research, citing Britian's annual inflation rate, which
stood at 8 percent in April.
   That rate has more than doubled in the past year to the highest
among major industrialized nations. Lawson predicted in March that
the rate would peak at 8 percent, but private economists think it
may go even higher before easing.
   Mrs. Thatcher's fight against inflation has been made more
difficult by the pound's fall, which makes imports more expensive.
The government responded by pushing up key interest rates a full
percentage point to 14 percent last week.
   It was the 10th increase since interest rates reached a decade
low of 7.5 percent about a year ago. The latest hike brought the
rate to its highest level in more four years, and economists say it
could go higher still.
   Meanwhile, the trade deficit has ballooned to $13 billion this
year, from $8.5 billion a year ago.
   The strikes, mostly for higher pay, are expected to subside
after a current round of wage negotiations. But they are causing
fears of a wage-price spiral as workers, whose earnings increased
at an annual rate of 9.5 percent in April, demand even more money
to offset inflation.
   Critics blame the economy's overheating on Lawson's tax cuts and
a loosened monetary policy. But the chancellor says the setback is
temporary. ``Overheating is on the way to subsiding,'' he said last
week. ``It is only a matter of time before inflation is coming
down.''
