<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1949EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LoveCanal     06-01 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Love Canal,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>State, Occidental Reach Agreement On Love Canal Wastes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN F. BONFATTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Occidental Chemical Corp. has for the first
time agreed to take some responsibility for cleaning up chemical
contamination at the old Love Canal industrial dump area, officials
said Thursday.
   Occidental has signed a consent agreement that calls for it to
take over disposal of toxic wastes excavated from two creeks near
the neighborhood in nearby Niagara Falls.
   The agreement could save taxpayers up to $20 million, said state
Environmental Conservation Commissioner Thomas Jorling.
   ``We have succeeded in getting Occidental to accept some
responsibility and take an active role in the remediation of Love
Canal, even though the company continues to fight its liability for
this national disaster,'' Jorling said.
   An Occidental subsidiary, Hooker Chemical Co., used an abandoned
waterway project as a chemical dump in the 1940s. The dump was
covered over in the 1950s and homes were built on the site in the
1960s. In the 1970s, toxic chemicals began seeping into basements
and yards, causing health problems.
   Occidental has taken the position that it was not responsible
for the environmental disaster because it had sold the land and
took no part in housing development at the site.
   Under the agreement, Occidental will take contaminated sediment
dredged from creeks north of the company's former chemical dump and
store it at a newly constructed facility at its Niagara Falls
plant. The sediment is contaminated with chemicals, including the
class of toxic chemicals called dioxins, that seeped out of the
dump or washed in from sewers.
   The waste eventually is to be incinerated, officials said.
   Jorling, who flew to Buffalo to make the announcement, said
Occidental has ``grown to respect the liability aspects of the
law.''
   But he stressed that it was ``a very limited agreement,''
directed to a single remedial action and leaves many issues
unresolved at other Occidental sites.
   Occidental, which abbreviates its name as OxyChem, issued a
statement later.
   ``The decisions and actions discussed here today by the
regulatory agencies mean that we can immediately move forward on a
program that OxyChem strongly believes to be in the best overall
interests of the community and the environment,'' said Thomas L.
Jennings, the company's vice president for corporate environmental
affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
