<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Finish Mostly Higher, Reversing Recent Trend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, bucking the recent
trend caused by drought-quenching Midwest rains.
   ``I think we probably have factored a lot of rainfall into these
markets,'' said Anne Frick, senior oilseed analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``We've had sort of a steady spate of rain now for the past two
or three weeks and the result has been that we have replenished the
soil moisture situation in the eastern Corn Belt,'' she said. ``The
West still has low subsoil supplies but the topsoil has good soil
moisture conditions.''
   The rain has alleviated fears of a rerun of last year's drought.
Many traders who had sold the market earlier in the month, hoping
that prices would fall, returned as buyers on Thursday.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to 1} cents higher with July at $2.60\ a bushel; oats were 4{
cents to 5\ cents higher with July at $1.72 a bushel; soybeans were
7 cents lower to 9\ cents higher with July at $7.07 a bushel.
