<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-EddieRetires     06-01 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eddie Retires,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board of Trade's 81-Year-Old Greeter Ends 65-Year Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eddie Mansfield has never traded a futures
contract, yet his is one of the best-known names to traders on the
floor of the Chicago Board of Trade.
   His contributions to the commodities industry may never make it
into the history books, but leaders of the world's oldest and
largest futures exchange say the long-time security guard and
``grand marshal'' of the exchange will never be forgotten.
   Mansfield's 65 years of service were honored with a retirement
party Thursday, attended by hundreds of well-wishers and held near
the entrance to the Board of Trade's grain-trading floor, which in
1985 officially was dubbed the Edward E. Mansfield Trading Room.
   The area is one where Mansfield spent much his career as the
exchange's chief security guard, checking for unfamiliar faces
among those heading for the trading pits.
   Even though the exchange has been stung by recent accusations
about cheating and greed among its traders, Eddie Mansfield says he
wouldn't trade away a minute of his 65 years of Board of Trade
memories.
   ``It's the greatest institution in the world, as far as I am
concerned,'' Mansfield, 81, said Thursday.
   Nowadays, traders enter the trading floor through turnstiles
activated by magnetic cards, just one of the changes Mansfield has
witnessed in his years with the exchange.
   When he was hired at the Board of Trade as a messenger at age
16, with no goals except helping to feed his mother and five
siblings, the exchange was a market where farmers displayed samples
of their grains and prices were relayed by Morse code and displayed
on a large chalkboard.
   These days, nearly all trades are settled by cash rather than
physical delivery, prices are transmitted electronically and
grain-trading volume is dwarfed by activity in financial products
such as U.S. Treasury bond futures.
   Mansfield, who lives comfortably on the 31st floor of a
high-rise overlooking Lake Michigan, can tick off the names of
traders who piled up astounding fortunes in the grain pits. But he
said he never felt compelled to plunge into that risky business.
   ``I might have had a temptation, but I had a responsibility to
my wife and three children, so I didn't trade,'' he said.
   Mansfield had only nice things to say about commodity traders
and the futures industry, which has been beset with federal
investigations of alleged cheating.
   ``It's hard for me to believe it,'' he said. ``With most
members, integrity is the name of the game. They're full of
integrity and they're gentlemen.''
   After stepping down as head of security more than 15 years ago,
the white-haired, wizened Mansfield remained at the Board of Trade
as the exchange's grand marshal, greeting the many dignitaries who
visit the historic marketplace.
   He recalled President Carter as ``the nice, short fella,'' and
remembered President Reagan as the ``fella with a big head of
hair.''
   Mansfield received the Claude D. Pepper Distinguished Service
Award, an honor reserved for people over 55 employed by Chicago
firms, in 1985. He was lauded by the Illinois Legislature in a
resolution adopted on his 80th birthday.
   But perhaps the greatest honor was Thursday's farewell message
from Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmann, who said: ``Eddie
couldn't be more of a Board of Trader if he wore a yellow badge
(signifying a full membership in the exchange). We'll be missing
you and we'll always remember you.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0375 </DOCNO>
