<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     06-01 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose To New High of $312.68 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 467 money market mutual
funds rose $599.3 million in the latest week to a new all-time high
of $312.68 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday broke the
previous record of $312.08 billion set the previous week, the
Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. The figure
originally had been reported as a record $312.07 million was was
revised upward.
   The biggest weekly rise in the funds' assets _ $9.64 billion in
the week ended Oct. 21, 1987 _ came during the stock market
collapse as investors sought safe havens for their money.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $414.2 million to $101.66
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $167.5 million
to $131.6 billion, and assets of 141 institutional funds rose $17.6
million to $79.43 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 9.11 percent from 9.14 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield slipped to 9.14 percent from 9.15
percent, Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
37 days, down from 38 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts remained unchanged as of
Wednesday at 6.62 percent.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.15 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.17
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 9.21
percent the previous week. Yields were 9.28 percent on 1-year CDs,
down from 9.33 percent; 9.09 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 9.14
percent; and 9.02 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 9.07 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
