<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-01 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices were mixed in quiet
trading Thursday, with many investors moving to the sidelines to
await the outcome of next week's OPEC meeting.
   Pressure has been building within the cartel to raise its
self-imposed quota by more than 1 million barrels a day, a move
that some fear will dampen prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S., fell 9 cents to
close at $19.81 a barrel. Other contract months rose.
   Among refined products, wholesale unleaded gasoline for July
delivery lost 1.21 cents to 63.34 cents a gallon, while contracts
for later delivery also fell.
   Wholesale heating oil for July, meanwhile, rose 0.33 cent to
48.09 a gallon, as other contract months ended mixed.
   Traders said activity on the exchange, which has slowed
considerably in the last two weeks, was grinding to a
near-standstill as the market turned its attention to Vienna, where
the 13 ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries are gathering for their semi-annual meeting.
   The meeting, scheduled for Monday, was to be preceded by a
meeting of the cartel's price-monitoring committee on Friday. Eight
ministers form that group.
   Analysts said new speculation that the cartel would raise its
current 18.5 million barrel-per-day production ceiling by between 1
million and 1.5 million barrels set a bearish tone for the market.
   ``Although the reports are not new, they make what we've already
heard more definite,'' said Greg Dreis, energy broker with Merrill
Lynch Energy Futures.
   Crude oil prices have risen more than 30 percent from around $15
last November when OPEC agreed to lower its production to 18.5
million barrels from more than 22 million. The quota was to remain
in effect for the first six months of 1989 to drive prices up to at
least $18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
