<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-MoneySupply     06-01 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Money Supply,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadest Measure of Money Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broad measure of the nation's money supply
rose by $2.2 billion in the week ended May 22, but the broadest
measure fell by $2.6 billion, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose to a seasonally
adjusted $3,072.3 billion from $3,070.1 billion the previous week.
   The broader measure, M3, fell to a seasonally adjusted $3,952.1
billion from $3,954.7 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell to a
seasonally adjusted $772.5 billion from $773.0 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted attention from M1 to the two broader money supply measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of
3 percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since
early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Fed said bank borrowings from the Federal Reserve System at
the discount window, excluding extended credit, averaged $534
million a day in the week ended Wednesday, up from $466 million the
previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $289.6 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, unchanged from the two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0382 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest     06-01 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>KLM Part Of Checchi's Bid For Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines is part of an
investment group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi that
has submitted a friendly bid to buy NWA Inc., the parent of
Northwest Airlines, a KLM spokesman said Thursday.
   KLM spokesman Peter Wellhuener said the Dutch state airliner has
``a commitment to an American investment group headed by Mr. Alfred
Checchi to take an indirect interest'' in the company bidding for
Northwest.
   Wellhuener refused further comment, citing the confidentiality
of the agreement between Checchi and Amsterdam-based KLM.
   NWA stock rose 87{ cents Thursday to close at $108.37{ in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Mike Hamilton, an analyst for Minneapolis-based Piper Jaffray &amp;
Hopwood Inc., said KLM's participation in the bid doesn't change
the proposal, which NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier has described as
friendly.
   Laws limiting foreign ownership of U.S. carriers would prevent
KLM from taking a controlling stake in Northwest, said Kurt Rivard,
an analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc. of Minneapolis.
   Barbara Beyer, president of Avmark Inc., an aviation consulting
firm in Arlington, Va., said the move may strengthen Checchi's bid
because it would allow KLM and Northwest to strike a working
relationship similar to a marketing agreement between United
Airlines and British Airways.
   ``It would probably make a lot of sense,'' Beyer said. ``I guess
if I have any concerns, it's that I don't have a feel KLM is big
enough to carry something like that off.''
   Other known bidders for NWA include Pan Am Corp., which has
offered about $110 a share, or $3.3 billion, and Marvin Davis, the
billionaire Los Angeles investor. The size of the bids by Davis and
Checchi have not been disclosed. But a Davis spokesman said the oil
mogul's latest offer is a revision ``upward'' from his hostile
tender offer of $2.7 billion, or $90 a share.
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., the leveraged buyout specialist,
is also rumored as a possible bidder for NWA, but a KKR spokesman
in New York on Thursday declined comment.
   Hamilton said the prevalent belief on Wall Street is that KKR is
a player in the takeover struggle, even if it failed to meet the
bidding deadline of Tuesday set by NWA's board of directors.
   ``One way or another, if KKR wants to be involved, they're going
to be involved,'' Hamilton said.
   Also making a proposal to Northwest Airlines is its
20,000-member machinists' union. Guy Cook, president of the
International Association of Machinists District Lodge 143, has not
revealed details of the union's offer. But in the past he has said
it would seek to team a ``patient investor'' with Northwest's
37,000 employees in buying a large block of NWA stock.
   Northwest said it will not identify its suitors or disclose
proposals. Four of the airline's board members will review the
bids, which are expected to remain open until June 16.
   Checchi, a former Marriott Corp. executive who has associated
with the Bass brothers' investment operations, has two other former
Marriott executives as partners: Walt Disney Co.'s chief financial
officer, Gary Wilson, who is a former NWA board member; and
Washington investment banker Fred Malek. The group also includes
Elders IXL Ltd., a diversified Australian company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
