<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TreeTop     06-01 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tree Top,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alar Stand May Have Cost Tree Top Chief His Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute over Tree Top Inc.'s stand
against Alar use may have cost company president Dennis Colleran
his job, a source with the apple processor said Thursday.
   The company's refusal to accept Alar-treated apples has angered
some of the growers who own the nation's largest apple juice maker,
said the source, who wished to remain unidentified.
   ``The warehouses are choked with Alar-treated fruit that can't
be marketed fresh,'' the source said.
   Many of those growers had hoped to divert the Alar-treated fruit
to Tree Top for processing into juice, making less money but
avoiding a total loss, the source said.
   But under Colleran that option has been closed.
   Tree Top for the past three years has refused to accept
Alar-treated apples for its own brand of apple juice. In May, the
company also announced that it planned to break contracts with
grower-members who used Alar on any of the coming season's crop,
even if the apples were not sent to Tree Top for processing.
   In addition, Colleran has been calling for an immediate ban on
Alar as a way to restore consumer confidence.
   Alar has been labeled a possible carcinogen by a private
consumer group, but is still legal to use. The federal government
has announced plans to ban Alar.
   An unknown but apparently large number of Alar-treated apples
are still filling Washington warehouses, and fears are growing that
many will have to be dumped, substantially increasing the estimated
$100 million in losses the apple industry has suffered nationally
so far this year.
   Colleran's resignation was announced on Wednesday, but no reason
was given.
   ``It is a private matter between Mr. Colleran and the board of
directors,'' Tree Top spokesman John McAlister said Thursday. ``The
resignation results from differences in management philosophy.''
   McAlister refused to elaborate and also retracted his Wednesday
statement that the resignation was not Alar related. He said he was
not supposed to offer any explanation on the cause of the
resignation.
   Colleran declined to comment Thursday. He said he was
negotiating his severance package with Tree Top's directors.
   Several of the cooperative's board members failed to return
telephone messages.
   Public fears over consumption of Alar apples have devastated
sales of both the fruit and apple juice.
   Sales of Tree Top juice have dropped over 20 percent since the
controversy began in February.
   Alar, the marketing name for daminozide, is sprayed on apple
trees to improve the color and crispness of the fruit and to extend
shelf life. Federal regulators estimate it is used on up to 15
percent of the apple crop.
   Colleran is one of the apple juice industry's leading figures,
serving as president of the Processed Apple Institute and also on
the board of the National Food Processors Association.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890601-0385 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-89 1937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC 1stld-Writethru   06-01 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, 1st ld - Writethru,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Set Thrash Out Oil Production, Pricing Policies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 14th graf, The July... UPDATE with closing WTI price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers are getting ready to
negotiate a new oil production strategy, amid price and output
demands aimed at changing the current cartel accord that has seen a
rise in world crude prices.
   Ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries were to gather Friday at their Vienna, Austria
headquarters in advance of their mid-year meeting set to begin
Monday.
   The cartel's eight-member price monitoring panel was to meet
Friday, although ministers from the rest of the nations were
expected to attend.
   OPEC's agreement last November to limit output in order to
support a price of $18 a barrel for its crude was seen as helping
push oil prices higher, but several members have indicated they
want to change either production quotas or the benchmark price.
   ``They will come to an agreement at the end,'' said Pierre
Terzian, editor of the Paris-based oil publication,
Petrostrategies. ``But it will be rather difficult.''
   In advance of the discussions, several ministers have made
proposals for the accord that will determine production and price
levels for the last half of 1989.
   Saudi Arabia's oil chief, Hisham Nazer, has said he would
recommend removing the $18 a barrel benchmark.
   OPEC agreed last November to limit cartel production to 18.5
million barrels a day in order to support the $18 a barrel price,
although some nations widely are seen as cheating on their
individual quotas.
   Prices have climbed since the accord, partly due to other
factors that disrupted some non-OPEC production. Some OPEC nations
have indicated the output ceiling should be raised for the second
half of the year.
   ``The government of Saudi Arabia believes that OPEC should set
for itself a production ceiling and strictly adhere to it,'' Nazer
told the New York Times earlier this week.
   ``This will give members a chance to take advantage of
situations where the price goes above $18 a barrel,'' he said.
   Algeria's Sadek Boussena was quoted in Petrostrategies as
insisting on a target of $18 a barrel for the rest of the year.
   The average price for a basket of seven crudes monitored by OPEC
has skyrocketed from $12.34 a barrel at the end of November to
$17.67 a barrel last week, although it exceeded the $18 target
earlier this year.
   The July contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, closed down 9 cents at $19.81 a barrel Thursday on the
New York Mercantile Exchange. The near month West Texas
Intermediate contract had touched lows in the $12.60 a barrel range
as late as last October.
   This year's price surge has been attributed not only to OPEC but
also to accidents in oil-producing areas, such as the oil spill in
Alaska's Prince William Sound, that caused temporary supply
disruptions.
   Nick Antill, an analyst at the brokerage County NatWest in
London, predicted OPEC would lift its production cap by a million
or so barrels, ranging from 19.5 million barrels to 20 million
barrels.
   Some analysts estimate production in April and May was about
20.5 million barrels a day.
   OPEC reported last week that 12 of its members supplied 17.54
million barrels a day into the international market last month,
compared with the supply target of 17.51 million barrels.
   Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates, analysts say, will be
pressing for a larger share of the total in a push that could anger
some of the other members.
   Sheikh Ali Khalifa al-Sabah, the Kuwaiti oil minister, said
OPEC's key issues are ``increasing the organization's production
ceiling and sharing out the increment among member countries.''
   The International Energy Agency, in its Monthly Oil Market
Report, estimated Kuwait's production in April at 1.4 million
barrels a day, compared with its 1 million barrel daily quota.
   The United Arab Emirates, considered a persistent cheater,
produced about 1.6 million barrels a day, compared with its cap of
988,000 barrels, according to the oil market report.
   The report estimated demand for OPEC would run about 20.4
million barrels a day in the second half of the year.
   OPEC members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
