<FIRST>r f AM-Bilzerian 1stLd-Writethru f0286 06-01 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bilzerian, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0286,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to make quotes conform with trial transcript;
Picks up 4th graf pvs, `The trial ...'; Subs 7th graf pvs, `Bilzerian has
...,' to delete extraneous reference to Mathews.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Defense Mistrial Request in Bilzerian Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense attorneys at the securities fraud trial
of Singer Co. Chairman Paul Bilzerian accused the judge of
prejudicing the jury and asked him to declare a mistrial Thursday.
   U.S. District Judge Robert J. Ward, who has grown increasingly
irritated with the slow pace of Bilzerian's questioning by defense
lawyer Arthur Mathews, denied the request.
   Although he told lawyers that he had ``bent over backwards'' to
accommodate the defense at times, Ward later told the jury:
``Ladies and gentlemen, I may have appeared to have been impatient
with Mr. Mathews. I would instruct you that this should not be
taken as an indication of any view of mine on the merits of the
case.''
   The trial, the first prosecution of a corporate raider using
information derived from the Ivan F. Boesky insider trading probe,
is winding up its fifth week.
   Bilzerian, 38, of Tampa, Fla., is accused of conspiracy,
violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in
connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986.
   None of the charges involve Bilzerian's $1.06 billion takeover
of Singer last year.
   Bilzerian has been on the witness stand since Tuesday, mostly on
direct examination by Matthews. The defense was forced to alter its
strategy after Ward issued an unfavorable ruling that would have
helped the government's cross-examination.
   Since that ruling, Bilzerian's testimony has dealt in minute
detail with the four takeover bids charged in the indictment.
   When Mathews said he wanted to complete his questioning after
the lunch break, the judge told him in a loud voice: ``No, I want
you to finish your examination. I have kept the jury now so that we
could conclude it. You know we have matters to take up between the
direct and cross-examination. You will finish this, please.''
   Later, when Bilzerian's testimony drifted off into a long story
about how he sought an intermediary in one of the takeover
attempts, Ward lifted a book above the bench and dropped it in
apparent exasperation.
   The judge stood up and told Mathews, ``If your client couldn't
know by now that he is not supposed to testify in this way, I will
have to tell him.''
   Ward added: ``I suggest further that you restructure your
questions concerning conversations and that we not get into this
narrative. I don't think it's helpful, under the circumstances.''
   With the jury out of the room, Mathews later asked Ward to
declare a mistrial, saying his actions were prejudicial to the
defense.
   The judge declined and the trial resumed.
   Under cross-examination by Assistant U.S. Attorney David
Brodsky, Bilzerian called a prosecution witness, stock trader
Michael Landy, a liar.
   Landy, a trader at the California brokerage, Jefferies &amp; Co.,
testified that Bilzerian promised to reverse a 1985 stock sale in
order to create illegal tax losses.
   ``I watched Michael Landy on the stand a few weeks ago and I
have no problem calling him a liar,'' said Bilzerian.
   His cross-examination was to continue Friday.
</TEXT>
